<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MATERIAL ON LEWINSKY, TRIPP LESS THAN FLATTERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Analysis) 
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It hardly seems possible, but the 4,610 pages of
additional material released Friday from Kenneth Starr's
investigation actually makes the principal characters appear even
less likable and more troubled than before.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern with whom
President Clinton has acknowledged an ``inappropriate''
relationship, comes off in the materials as even more spoiled,
gossipy and harassing than she seemed previously.
</P>
<P>
   And Linda Tripp, who secretly recorded conversations with
Lewinsky and turned them over to the independent counsel, is
depicted not only as scheming but manipulative as well, seemingly
not above leading her ``friend'' into deepening waters.
</P>
<P>
   Transcripts of the Tripp-Lewinsky tapes were made available
Friday for the first time. All of the documents, including more
grand jury testimony, were made public by the House of
Representatives. The House is preparing to vote next week on
whether to launch an impeachment inquiry based on Clinton's alleged
attempts to cover up the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are like air pollutants: The more that accumulate,
the darker the whole drama seems to become.
</P>
<P>
   There were details Friday alleging that Lewinsky virtually
stalked a former boyfriend in Oregon in 1993-94, threatened to
reveal their affair to his wife and tried to ingratiate herself
with his relatives. After the boyfriend, Andy Bleiler, broke off
the affair, Lewinsky told a friend that she continued to dream
about him months afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky told Tripp she was similarly troubled when Clinton
ended their relationship at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it that I'm supposed to gain? I don't feel any better
about myself,'' Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Tripp, ``the you-know-what of the you-know-what
(President of the United States) found you awfully attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky replied that was no compliment because Clinton would
have a certain kind of sex with ``anybody'' if he had the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The more you learn about Lewinsky's raging insecurities and
penchant for revealing her personal life, the more you have to
question how Clinton ever thought their relationship could remain
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky confided details of the affair to her mother and to
friends and, according to Friday's documents, would occasionally
announce to office workers at her Pentagon job that Clinton was
wearing a tie she had given him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told a grand jury Aug. 17 that he knew Lewinsky
ultimately would reveal their affair because ``it was a part of her
psyche.'' The president did not say how or when that realization
came to him.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton ended their relationship, Lewinsky, now 25, sought
help in obtaining a new job _ but not just any job. She wrote
presidential secretary Betty Currie that she was appreciative of
the administration's assistance but that a possible opening at the
United Nations was ``YUCK!'' In another document, she says she
wants to make $65,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new material certainly won't boost the image of Tripp,
either. She already appears in public-opinion polls to be the most
despised character in the political soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp acts as if she were Lewinsky's confidante and protector.
At the same time, she seems to be leading Lewinsky toward trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Tripp encourages Lewinsky in a telephone
conversation to get help in finding a job not only from Clinton
friend Vernon Jordan, but also from inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   House members say they want to know whether Clinton dispatched
Jordan or anyone else to find Lewinsky a lucrative job to ensure
her silence. Clinton's lawyers don't deny that the president
indirectly aided in her job search, but they maintain it was
Lewinsky who initiated the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   In one conversation made public Friday, Tripp tells Lewinsky
that White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles has ``more
connections in industry and every other thing than you can
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky says that she doesn't want job help from somebody
working inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Tripp replies that she doesn't see a problem. ``Are you
telling me that you think Erskine doesn't place people every day of
the week? I mean, come on. That's how networking works.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky holds steadfast, saying, ``Somebody could construe or
say, `Well, they gave her a job to shut her up. They made her
happy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's reply: ``Hmpf.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
