<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LARRY-BIRD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BASHFUL LARRY BIRD JOINS HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ A crowd of more than 200 was waiting across
the street, but he decided not to attend the unveiling of his
bronze statue. He also escaped most of the crowds in the hotel
lobby _ the kids who skipped school, standing next to their fathers
wearing faded No. 33 Celvics jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird was not being reclusive; he was merely trying to do
what he always does when he returns to Massachusetts: outrun his
legend. On the day he was enshrined into the Naismith Memorial
Basketball Hall of Fame, he never looked slower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I go people ask me about my playing days,'' he
said. ``It seems like it's gevting worse, not better. Once this is
over, I think I can close the book on my career and look forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But for at least one more night, he had to give in to his
legions by looking back at his remarkable 13-year Celtics career.
Before a sold-out gathering at the Springfield Civic Center, Bird
was enshrined along with Lenny Wilkens, Marques Haynes (the first
Harlem Globetrotter to be inducted), the former Rochester Royal and
Boston Celtic star Arnie Risen and three other coaches: longtime
NBA mentor Alex Hannum, University of Texas women's coach Jody
Conradt and Yugoslavian coach Aleksandar Nikolic.
</P>
<P>
   Any other year, Wilkens, the only person other than John Wooden
to be inducted as a player and coach, would be a big draw here, but
even the man with more victories than any other coach in NBA
history understood the magnitude of Bird's induction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it is an honor to be here to attend Larry's party,''
Wilkens said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Resembling a bashful kid who did not want his name called in
class, Bird spoke about growing up poor in rural Indiana. ``One
thing nice about growing up in a small town,'' he said. ``If
someone stole the nets from the court, you knew who did it and you
could always get them back.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke about his ascension to a three-time most valuable
player in the NBA and about his crowning moments: the three
championships he led the Celtics to in the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   His deadpan humor was as dead on as his 3-point shot. He was
asked about a spectacular shot he made during the 1981 finals
against Houston _ a shot in which, in one motion, Bird rebounded
his missed jumper from the perimeter and banked the ball in
left-handed as he was falling out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm the only one in the building that knew I missed the
shot so bad that I knew where it was going,'' he said. ``So I
chased it down, got it and laid it in. I can remember the play like
it was yesterday. I don't know if it was the greatest shot ever,
but in a playoff situation it sure was nice to chase down your own
miss and save a little bit of face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird had a way of gauging cities that did not include their
cuisine or their culture. When asked what he thought of Hartford,
where the Celtics sometimes played, he replied: ``Nice place. They
had good rims.''
</P>
<P>
   After Nikolic graciously thanked the committee for his induction
and apologized for his halting English, Bird rose to the podium and
said: ``That's OK, Aleksandar. I've been living in this country for
41 years, and I still have trouble with the language.''
</P>
<P>
   The room broke up laughing. Everyone, it seemed, had his
favorite Bird tale, usually about how Bird had won a game or
responded to the challenge of opposing fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest worker I ever saw, period,'' said Bill Walton, his
presenter at the enshrinement. ``Larry Bird was the epitome of what
it means to love this game and play it with passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain put it this way: ``If I had to have a forward
to start a team, I would take Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although at times he has been the most celebrated sports figure
in Massachusetts, Bird could not please everyone Friday. Between
the news conference and the induction ceremony, he was shuffled
around to different corporate engagements all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When the statue of Bird was unveiled on the third floor of the
Hall of Fame this afternoon, the sculptor asked the audience if
they had any questions. ``Where's Larry?'' someone yelled, spurring
on the impatient masses.
</P>
<P>
   Where else? Off being a legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I can put some closure on my career by being inducted
into the Hall of Fame,'' he said before stepping down from the
podium. ``They said there'll never be another kid from French Lick
that makes it to the NBA. I said there probably will be, one of
these days. Chances are slim, but if someone dedicates themself
they'll have a good opportunity to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
