<SLUG> BC-COOKIE-MURDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE IS SEIZED FROM HOME OF MOM PRESUMED MURDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police detectives seized five garbage containers behind the home
of a missing and presumed murdered Tempe woman as they tried to
shore up their case against the woman's two teenage children.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators would only say that they found evidence ``of
value'' inside the containers, as well as inside Cookie Jacobson's
home, but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   But one crucial piece of evidence still eluded them Friday:
Jacobson's body.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they remain convinced that Aaron Jacobson, 16,
killed his mother and had help from his sister, Laura, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives arrested the siblings Thursday but released them
hours later to the custody of their father after the Maricopa
County Attorney's Office determined that there was insufficient
evidence to hold the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Police accused Aaron of second-degree murder and Laura of
facilitation to commit second-degree murder. Their arrests stunned
residents near McClintock Drive and Southern Avenue, many of whom
had showered the Jacobson kids with sympathy and encouragement and
passed out fliers _ at times accompanied by Aaron or Laura _ around
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The two teens repeatedly expressed concern for their mother's
safety, which police now say was all an act.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation shifts to finding Cookie Jacobson's body,
authorities drew parallels to a 1995 murder case in which a
13-year-old boy was killed and stuffed into a garbage container.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's body was never found, but authorities secured a
conviction against his killer anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe police expressed optimism Friday that prosecution against
Aaron and Laura Jacobson will not be derailed by the lack of a
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need it, but obviously it would help,'' said Sgt.
Dave Lind, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie Jacobson disappeared Sept. 21 and was reported missing by
her husband, Bill. Police originally said she was last seen alive
at 9:30 a.m., when Aaron and Laura left for school.
</P>
<P>
   The children told police that their adoptive mother had scolded
them for being late.
</P>
<P>
   Police sources have said Aaron had a history of threatening his
mother. A friend of Aaron's said Thursday that Aaron told a mutual
friend about a previous attempt to poison his mother.
</P>
<P>
   While the investigation continues, the Jacobson family's
minister pleaded with the public to avoid premature judgments about
the children's guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it seems to be very irresponsible to jump to
conclusions,'' said Dr. Bert Lewis, pastor of Dayspring United
Methodist Church. A vigil for Cookie Jacobsonscheduled at the
church for Thursday night was canceled at the family's request
after the children's arrests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Jacobson has been active in the church's youth group,
Lewis said. This summer, Aaron and other teenagers helped build
houses on an Indian reservation in northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron is very likable,'' Lewis said. ``There would be nothing
in his background and character to suggest he would do something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, as well as Aaron's classmates at McClintock High School
and the boy's boss at a Tempe hardware store, remained in disbelief
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quiet and really, really sweet,'' said Indigo Stein, a
McClintock student. ``He was never mean to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Rogers agreed, saying, ``You would never guess that he
would do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls and other students defended Aaron against the police
suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it. It's bull,'' David Young said. ``I don't
believe he would do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said Aaron has been more quiet than usual since his
mother's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wilson, manager of Ace Hardware at Baseline Road and
McClintock Drive in Tempe, said Aaron has worked as a cashier at
the store for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron has proven himself a good employee on his first job,
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was honest and very reliable and very responsible,'' the
store manager said. ``As far as we're concerned, he still works
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he recently cut back on Aaron's work hours, at the
Jacobsons' request, because Aaron's schoolwork had suffered
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope,'' Wilson said, ``it's not true.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Jim Walsh can be reached at 444-7984 or at jim.walsh &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
