<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ DEFENDS TITLE AGAINST MAYWEATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it too soon for Floyd Mayweather or too late for Genaro
Hernandez?
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out tonight, when Hernandez, the skillful but
often-overlooked WBC super featherweight champion, defends his
title against the unbeaten 1996 Olympic bronze medalist in Las
Vegas. The fight will be televised on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who grew up and trains in Los Angeles, is one of the
most-skilled boxers in the world and has never lost at this weight
class, 130 pounds. His only setback came at 135 pounds in 1995
against Oscar De La Hoya when he had to quit because of a shattered
nose.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hernandez is 32 and has rarely faced a fighter of
Mayweather's natural ability, which might explain this: As of
Friday, Mayweather was an 8-5 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mayweather, the first 1996 Olympian to get a title
shot, has !ital!never!off! faced a fighter with the ability and
experience _ not to mention height _ of the 6-foot Hernandez. Not
even close. Hernandez has been in the ring with the likes of De La
Hoya and Azumah Nelson, fighters far more fearsome at this stage
than Mayweather.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some believe Mayweather, all of 21, is taking on too
much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages of negotiations, Hernandez was among the
skeptical. He was irked by the audacity of the young fighter to
think he could knock off so early in his career a champion who has
held world titles for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he tempered his comments but explained this isn't the
first time he's been in this position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayweather is a real good fighter,'' said Hernandez (38-1-1,
17 knockouts). ``I just think I've had some other hard fights in my
career, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Hernandez, Genaro's brother and trainer, said the champion
will determine the outcome of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   If he's passive, as he has been on occasion, Mayweather's talent
and phenomenal speed could be the difference. If he's aggressive,
Rudy Hernandez said, the challenger could be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of times in training the last few weeks that
I've thought, `There's no way Mayweather can win this fight.' My
gut feeling? Genaro is going to kick his butt,'' Rudy Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather (17-0, 13 KOs) is as confident about his own chances.
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses Hernandez's edge in experience, saying his
extensive amateur career is experience enough. And as far as the
champion's skill level goes, no one is going to convince Mayweather
that even a seasoned champion is any more talented than he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he's the best 130-pounder. I think I'm the best
130-pounder. That's why I'm fighting him,'' said Mayweather, the
son of former contender Floyd Sr. (now his trainer) and nephew of
former champion Roger Mayweather.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a stepping stone for me. This'll really get my
career going. This is the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Could be.
</P>
<P>
   The winner could defend against dangerous Angel Manfredy in
December, also on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   For Mayweather, who will make $150,000 for the fight, victories
over Hernandez and Manfredy could catapult him into an elite _ and
wealthy _ group of fighters. For Hernandez, whose payday is a
relatively paltry $600,000, these two fights could get him some of
the money and recognition that has eluded him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
