<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HRKAC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNEYMAN HRKAC FINDS PLACE WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Tony Hrkac heard the news that the Stars would
protect him in Monday's waiver draft, his face lit up as if he had
scored a game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   And in many ways, he had.
</P>
<P>
   Hrkac, the 32-year-old center who typifies the word
``journeyman,'' has scored possibly the biggest goal of his career:
a home with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's with us, he's an NHL player,'' Stars director of player
personnel Craig Button said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is quite amazing to Hrkac (rhymes with circus). In a
career that has taken him from the University of North Dakota
through six NHL teams and five minor-league teams, Hrkac is back to
being a legitimate NHL player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great; it's something I've really worked hard for,'' he
said. ``It's great news.''
</P>
<P>
   Hrkac had an assist in a 5-2 Stars victory against the Phoenix
Coyotes in preseason play last night at Reunion Arena, and expects
to add plenty more during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't so clear to him two days ago. The waiver draft on
Monday seemed a sure ticket out of town for Hrkac. He said he did
not expect to be one of the 18 skaters the Stars protected and he
thus could have been chosen by another team _ likely Edmonton, with
whom he played last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my situation, I knew it was going to be a tense day,''
Hrkac said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with getting taken by Edmonton _ or any other team _
was Hrkac would have to establish his place in another lineup, move
his family and then not be sure what his next move was. Last
season, the Stars signed Hrkac as a free agent with the thought he
would play for the minor-league Michigan K-Wings. But injuries to
Mike Modano and Joe Nieuwendyk opened up a space in the Stars'
lineup and Hrkac responded with five goals and three assists for
eight points in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars tried to send Hrkac back to Michigan, Edmonton
picked him up on waivers and he finished out the season with the
Oilers, scoring eight goals and 11 assists in 36 games. But the
Oilers packaged him in a trade to Pittsburgh in June, he was taken
by the Nashville Predators in the expansion draft and then traded
back to the Stars in July for future considerations.
</P>
<P>
   After that frantic summer, all Hrkac needed was another game of
musical teams. Now, he has the security he likely will stay on the
Stars' roster for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A talented playmaker who won the 1987 Hobey Baker Award as top
U.S. collegiate player, Hrkac is expected to take Nieuwendyk's
place as center on the second line until Nieuwendyk returns from
off-season knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   When Nieuwendyk returns, Hrkac is expected to see time on the
third and fourth lines, spelling veterans Guy Carbonneau and Brian
Skrudland. The bottom line, though, is he has earned a spot on one
of the deepest rosters in the NHL. Not bad for a guy who spent
almost four consecutive seasons in the minors before last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in at the beginning of last season and he played like
a minor-leaguer, he had a minor-league attitude,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``But after getting a break and proving he can play
in the NHL, he now has the mentality of an NHL player. His body
language says he can play in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that, Hrkac said, he can thank the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, they showed faith in me, they believed in me after
I had been in the minors forever,'' he said. ``If I had a choice of
playing anywhere, it would be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
