<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-CARD-HALTED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER HALTS LONE STAR CARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Here's one you won't see often: a rainout
at the horse track.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie have to compete
last night with the nearby baseball playoff game on the opening of
its fall quarter horse meeting, it had to contend with the wrath of
nature as well.
</P>
<P>
   The last five races were canceled at 10:40 p.m. after a
90-minute delay because of a severe thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The same torrential rain, winds and lightning that struck The
Ballpark at Arlington _ only a few exits down Interstate 30 _
swamped the track shortly before 9 p.m. as jockeys were in the
paddock preparing to mount their horses for the seventh race.
</P>
<P>
   Horses remained in the paddock and in the receiving barn
awaiting a break in the monsoon, but it never came. When weather
forecasters told Lone Star officials more storms were on the way,
the plug was pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have run, except for the lightning,'' Lone Star
general manager Corey Johnsen said. ``We're not going to do that
here. Safety should always come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Lightning is more dangerous in horse racing than other outdoor
sports _ with the possible exception of golf _ because the starting
gate is metal.
</P>
<P>
   Trash cans and debris were blown around the premises, but no
significant damage other than lost betting revenue was reported.
</P>
<P>
   The opening-night feature, the $20,000 B.F. Phillips Jr.
Handicap, was among the races canceled, postponing 6-year-old mare
Kool Kue Baby's chance to win her 21st lifetime stakes race and
move within one of the all-time record. The race will be
rescheduled for a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance was only 6,785, compared to 8,102 on the opening
night of last year's quarter horse stand. On-track betting on Lone
Star races was $195,124 for six races, with comparisons to 1997's
$477,139 total rendered meaningless because of the abbreviated
card.
</P>
<P>
   After such an ominous beginning to the new season, they'll try
again tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The first Saturday-night card in track history starts at 6:35
p.m., including the $15,000 Rheudasil Handicap for fillies and
mares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 0042EDT &QL; 
