<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM AFAR, A FATHER WATCHES HIS SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Chuck Knoblauch, the New York Yankees' second
baseman, expected that his father, Ray Knoblauch, would attend
Friday night's playoff game. Ray Knoblauch, a well-known high
school baseball coach in the Houston area, was stricken by
Alzheimer's last year, but he came here to watch the Yankees'
series against the Rangers in August.
</P>
<P>
   The son believes that his father is aware of the significance of
the game. ``He still talks about baseball,'' Chuck Knoblauch said.
``He's kind of aware of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   An adjustment in treatment has improved his father's ability to
communicate. ``It's not as bad as it was,'' Chuck Knoblauch said.
``You don't really get better with this kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   Going With the Heat
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Mariano Rivera pitched a scoreless ninth
inning in Game 1 and in Game 2 entered with two outs in the eighth
and notched his second save of the series, blowing away Will Clark
with a high fastball to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, Rivera made a point of developing other
pitches _ a cut fastball that runs in on left-handed batters, a
two-seam fastball that sinks low and inside, and a slider. But in
the postseason he has reverted to his signature pitch, a very hard
four-seam fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just letting it go,'' said Jorge Posada, his catcher in
Game 1. ``He was throwing about as hard as he has all year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   Gooden on Strawberry
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland pitcher Dwight Gooden, a former teammate of Darryl
Strawberry's with the Mets and Yankees, released this statement
through the Cleveland Indians Friday in Boston regarding his
friend:
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts and prayers go out to Darryl and his family. I
talked to Darryl last night and he seemed to be in good spirits. We
have been through a lot together over the years and I will do
whatever I have to for him to help him through this. All I can do
at this time is hope and pray. Darryl has been and always will be
like a brother to me. In my mind I know he will pull through
this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   They Came and Waited
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several fans and hospital workers waited at
Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital yesterday, along with reporters and
television crews, to catch a glimpse of Darryl Strawberry entering
the hospital for cancer surgery Friday. He was not spotted,
although some people in the hospital said he had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Several people said their prayers were with Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn McLucas, 35, a resident of the Bronx and a clerical
worker at the hospital, said he had followed Strawberry since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my idol, he's one of my favorite players, I've always
looked up to him,'' McLucas said. ``Even when he had his troubles
with drugs I still respected him. A lot of people have to go
through the same thing. I hope he's all right. I remember him as a
rookie, I got his jersey and everything. He's my man.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Guerrero, 36, a messenger from Manhattan, said: ``My hopes
and prayers are with him. I think God will be looking out for him.
I want to thank him as a New York sports fan for giving me all
those thrills.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ragonese, 22, a nuclear medical technician at the
hospital, said: ``He's really beaten the odds many times already so
I think he'll pull through this. He's got to.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVE KOEPPEL
</P>
</TEXT>
