<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S EVALUATION MAY BE MADE PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After losing a battle in a Nevada courtroom Thursday evening,
Mike Tyson will have to allow members of the Nevada State Athletic
Commission to publicly investigate the details of a psychological
evaluation he underwent last week at Massachusetts General Hospital
if he has any chance of getting his license reinstated by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation was not immediately released to the commission.
Marc Ratner, director of the commission, said there was no time
limit set on when the report had to be turned over, but if Tyson
wanted his hearing to take place on Oct. 19, he would have to
release the evaluation to the commission soon.
</P>
<P>
   The commission revoked Tyson's license on July 9, 1997, after he
bit Evander Holyfield's ears during a heavyweight championship bout
11 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's attorneys, and the doctors at Massachusetts General who
conducted the evaluations, argued against the public release of the
evaluation on the grounds of privacy. But the Nevada state attorney
general's office argued that based on the state's open records law,
the results had to be released publicly. District Judge Gene Porter
agreed and ordered the results released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do what is needed to do to satisfy the
commission, but I don't understand why the entire evaluation has to
be released,'' Shelly Finkel, Tyson's boxing adviser, said Friday.
``We are opposed to the public seeing the report, but we want the
commission to be comfortable with the decision it makes. At the
same time we don't want Mike to be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission ordered Tyson to undergo psychological testing by
an independent psychiatrist after a hearing on Sept. 19. The
commissioners expressed concerned over Tyson's mental fitness to
return to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   HERNANDEZ TO FIGHT MAYWEATHER FRIDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Genaro Hernandez (38-1-1) will defend his World Boxing Council
superflyweight championship against Floyd Mayweather Jr. (17-0)
Friday night in Las Vegas. The fight will be televised by HBO and
will be followed by a taped broadcast of the Oscar De La Hoya-Julio
Cesar Chavez welterweight championship bout, which took place on
Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather is the first of the 1996 U.S. Olympic boxing team
members to fight for a world championship. He won a bronze medal in
the 1996 Atlanta Games. The only loss in his career was to De La
Hoya, in a welterweight bout in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
