<DOCNO> NYT19981003.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HALLOFFAME-BIRD-B     10-03 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SHOWSTOPPER FOR BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME-BIRD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ He was driven to the ceremony in a very
fancy car. He was surrounded all day by sponsors and fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird was the obvious centerpiece of all that transpired
Friday during Enshrinement Day at the Basketball Hall of Fame. He
was officially inducted Friday night in a ceremony at the Civic
Center in front of thousands of fans and admirers who couldn't
resist several final chants of ``Larry, Larry,'' even as the other
inductees tried to speak. The other six inductees are destined to
be remembered as ``those who went in with Larry,'' as two-time
enshrinee Lenny Wilkens noted from the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor,'' he said, ``to attend Larry's party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was the final of the seven to be introduced, both at the
start of the ceremony and as the last speaker. On each occasion, he
was given a standing ovation of more than two minutes as he smiled
sheepishly and tried, without success, to quiet the crowd. Upon
being inducted, he told a few stories and then said he was proud of
his basketball accomplishments in high school and college, adding,
``and I'm very proud to say I spent 13 years playing for the Boston
Celtics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was the 25th individual with a Celtic tie to make the Hall
of Fame. (Several ex-Celtics were pres-ent, but conspicuous in
their absences were John Havlicek, Bob Cousy, and Dave Cowens.) One
of his fellow inductees Friday night _ former center Arnie Risen _
was the 24th. Risen came to the Celtics at the end of his career
after making a name for himself, and winning a title, in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   The other honorees were Alex Hannum, the man who coached the
only two teams to defeat Bill Russell in an NBA playoff; Texas
women's coach Jody Conradt; Wilkens, who previously had been
inducted as a player; former Harlem Globetrotter Marques Haynes;
and Aleksandar Nikolic, regarded as the father of Yugoslavian
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic Center usually hosts the ceremony, but for the first
time, seats were sold and 7,000 green-clad partisans gladly paid
for one more look at Bird. He was escorted by former teammate Bill
Walton, a 1993 enshrinee; his first pro coach, Bill Fitch; his
wife, Dinah; and children Conner and Mariah. Bird said his main
regret was that his late mother, Georgia, could not be there.
</P>
<P>
   Each inductee must have a Hall of Famer as an escort. Conradt
selected Sam Jones, who was inducted in 1993, while Wilkens
selected Red Auerbach, a 1968 inductee. Conradt accepted her award
on behalf of women's basketball, adding, ``there was a time when if
you had a car, you made the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannum, who coached ABA and NBA champions, was escorted by Wilt
Chamberlain, who was making his first visit to the Hall of Fame
since he was enshrined in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes delivered the longest acceptance speech, which basically
was an extended thank you. After signing off, fans were treated to
a brief reunion of the Globetrotters, including Meadowlark Lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Risen had considered asking Russell to escort him, which would
have been an event in and of itself given that Russell didn't even
attend his own enshrinement ceremony in 1974. But Risen decided
instead that he would have a former Rochester teammate, Bobby
Wanzer, because his best pro years were with the Royals. Risen
spent the last three years of his 13-year career with the Celtics
(1955-1958).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too great a guy not to be associated with the Hall,''
Risen said of Russell. ``He was a close friend and I would have
been proud to have him represent me. Down deep, I think he would
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton had no such hesitation about escorting Bird. The two were
teammates for two years in Boston _ only one of which was Walton a
real player _ but they have remained close and share the basic,
fundamentalist view of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been 6-11 since I was a senior in high school,'' said
Walton, who is more like 7-2 but never has owned up to it. ``But
when I got the call from Larry, I almost made it to seven feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton was always one who felt that Bird would excel as a coach,
but he said he fully understood, and endorsed, his former
teammate's decision to start anew in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird gave his life to the Boston Celtics,'' Walton said.
``When he left, there was nothing more. He has two 18-inch rods in
his back and all those surgeries. There was nothing more he could
do. It was better for Larry to go to Indiana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
