<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-03 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS WON'T LET LEGEND GOT QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ All day long it seemed like the only goal
he had was to get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's your mind-set when your elevation into the Hall of
Fame has all the suspense of a 1957 Soviet election. After all, a
Basketball Hall of Fame without Larry Bird would be like a culinary
shrine without Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on,'' he announced Friday morning. ``I can
finally bring a close to my career. I'm glad that my playing days
are behind me and I can move on with my future.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps Larry thought it was time to move on, but that
wasn't the attitude of the 7,000 representatives of the basketball
vox pop-uli who assembled at the Civic Center Friday night to see
Larry become the 25th person with Celtic blood to be inducted into
the Basketball Hall of Fame. It was ``Lar-Ree! La-Ree!'' all over
again. The oft-unruly Bird watchers practically shouted down master
of ceremonies Ahmad Rashad when he stepped to the podium, so much
so that it looked at the outset that it was going to be a long and
disrespectful evening for the other six inductees.
</P>
<P>
   They did settle down enough to permit an orderly program to
unfold, but there was never any doubt that the star of the evening
was Number 33. The organizers saved him for last, of course, and he
had a highlight video that was twice as long as anyone else's. When
he was introduced they kept cheering for well over a minute as
Larry gave out a half-dozen ``thank you''s before he could begin
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Get it over with? These people wanted him to restart the career.
Larry was looking for closure, but the fact is that the memory of
who he was and what he accomplished on the basketball court is so
far superior to anything they will ever see again that rehashing
and reliving the Legend of Larry Bird was a mandatory act.
</P>
<P>
   Larry just doesn't understand. Never has. Probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think like a fan,'' he admitted a few hours
before officially becoming a Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   What seems logical to us is decidedly illogical to him. You can
bet he wasn't camped in front of the TV set during the Classic
Sports ``Larry Bird Marathon'' last weekend. As he would say,
``Hell, I did it. Why do I have to watch it all over again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He appreciates the honor,'' assured his friend and assistant
coach Rick Carlisle. ``He cares more than he let on.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said he didn't care, or that getting into the Hall
of Fame meant nothing to him. Larry appreciates being in the
company of great players. From his earliest days as a Celtic, he
paid proper homage to those who came before, even if he never saw
them. He once asked a couple of writers why there was any debate
about who the best player ever had been. He had been looking in the
record book and it looked like ``The Wilt Chamberlain Story.''
Larry figured it was an easy answer.
</P>
<P>
   He never laid any claim to inventing the sport, and he went out
of his way to reject any notion that he and Magic Johnson deserve
credit for reviving the NBA. ``Two guys did not turn the league
around,'' he said firmly. ``There were a lot of great players
before us and after us.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't understand why anyone would not understand his
desire to stop talking about his playing career. ``It's just time
to get it over with,'' he explained. ``I really feel that way.
Yeah, I was a great player, but I don't want to keep talking about
it. I've got a new career going. I'm a coach now. I'd like people
to talk about my team a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Lar. Nice try. This is Boston. They're still talking
about Cousy. They're still talking about Russell. They're still
talking about Heinsohn. They're still talking about Havlicek.
They're still talking about Cowens. Somebody probably is still
talking about Fat Freddy Scolari. And you think that with the
massive video tape trail you left behind they will ever stop
talking about you?
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Larry had a similar blase attitude toward ``Larry Bird Night'' 5
1/2 years ago, and now he says it was one of the greatest nights in
his life. ``That was very special,'' he said. ``It is still amazing
to me that people came into the building on a night when there was
no game. I can still remember the feeling I got looking at all the
seats filled in the Garden, and I'm very proud we raised a lot of
money for charity that night. To look around and see the seats
filled was amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he has a second night to ponder. Surely on that trip back to
Indianapolis Friday night he had to be feeling more awe and wonder
about what he accomplished during those 13 years in Boston. Because
of Larry Bird, the Hall of Fame officials had to accommodate triple
the amount of media than they had for the previous grand attraction
(Dr. J, 1993). Because of Larry Bird, the Green People came out of
their six-year hibernation from as far away as California and
Seattle to seek autographs and Bird sightings. Because of Larry
Bird, the atmosphere at the Hall of Fame induction was transformed
into something akin to a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   And when Larry Bird came out on the stage to be greeted by a
raucous standing ovation, his face broke into a smile. Surely now
he has to know.
</P>
<P>
   It may be over for him. But it's never going to be over for the
rest of us. Larry Bird gave us the best moments of our
basketball-loving lives. And we're supposed to forget?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
