<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHREBET IS LEAVING IT UP TO PARCELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Wayne Chrebet of the New York Jets has been
spending six hours a day trying to make his sprained left ankle
healthy enough to carry him against the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The wide receiver was asked Friday if he would be starting on
Sunday at Giants Stadium. ``Bill is the only one in the whole
entire world who knows,'' he said, referring to the head coach,
Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that Chrebet would play, but perhaps not start,
against a defense that has held opposing quarterbacks to fewer than
50 percent completions.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Chrebet must have told Parcells he wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' replied the sure-handed, acrobatic receiver. ``But I
don't think it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Chrebet has emerged as a receiver with big numbers
this season. He is averaging 16.1 yards a catch, compared with his
career mark of 11.7. But he remains one of those players whose
success belies computers, scouting reports and all the other
football verities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the National Football League drafted 31 receivers.
Chrebet, from Hofstra, was not among them. He showed up on the Jets
as a free agent. Yet, of all those players drafted that year _
including the first-rounders Joey Galloway of Seattle, J.J. Stokes
of San Francisco and Michael Westbrook of Washington _ Chrebet is
the leader in receptions with 223. He amassed 2,675 yards and 12
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet hurt his ankle two Sundays ago against the Colts. ``Most
of the swelling is down,'' he said. ``But you can still see purple.
I'm going to feel it until I lay off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dedric Ward will start if Chrebet does not.
</P>
<P>
   Running Behind Marino
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino's accomplishments take up 46 pages in the Dolphins'
media guide. And why not? No quarterback in history has tossed more
touchdowns than Marino's 388.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of passing, even over 15 years, and part of the
reason was necessity. Only one Dolphin has rushed for 1,000 yards
in a season in that time. That was Karim Abdul-Jabbar two years
ago. Now, Abdul-Jabbar is on his way to another such campaign with
291 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Marino came into the season averaging 34.6 passes a game. This
year he has had to throw only 24 times a game. Don't be fooled by
that number, though. Bill Parcells isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll try to be successful with what they've done,''
said Parcells, talking about Miami's running game. ``But they
haven't been behind, and if they are, I expect to see the other
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino has more touchdowns against the Jets, 67, than any
quarterback has thrown against another team. One factor is that the
Jets hardly pressure him. He has had 10 games against them without
being sacked. In his last seven appearances, the Jets got to him no
more than once. This year's Jets, meanwhile, do not have a sack
from the defensive line, the only NFL team with such a negative
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Foley Concerned for Mother
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Glenn Foley said Friday that he was ready to give up
his career by donating a kidney to his mother, Sue, who is waiting
for a kidney transplant. Foley was expecting to be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother didn't want any of her children to give up a
kidney,'' he said. ``She wouldn't let any of her sons be tested to
see if they matched. She has four boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her sisters and brothers were tested along with Foley's
father, Ed, who has a compatible kidney. Tests are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Red-Zone Tough
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense has permitted only three touchdowns in the
nine times opposing teams have got inside the 20-yard line. Only
two other clubs, the Broncos and the Jaguars, have a better
percentage in preventing touchdowns in the area referred to as the
red zone. ... The Jets' offense is doing a good job on first down:
5.47 yards an attempt, third best in the American Conference. But
the Jets have been burned on defense, with opposing teams averaging
more than 7 yards on first down, the worst in the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
