<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee on
Friday released the final mass of evidence in its consideration of
impeachment charges against President Clinton, offering a pungent
store of furtive tapes and grand jury delvings into Clinton's
intimate relationship with a White House intern. By Francis X.
Clines. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONICA-LINDA (Washington) _ They talked on and on, about
haircuts, diets, sex and more sex. But the tapes of the phone chats
between Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp show less a real friendship
than a temporary alliance between two women obsessed by Bill
Clinton who often don't even seem to like each other very much. By
Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BETTY (Washington) _ Appearing last January as the first
witness before the grand jury investigating President Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky, Betty Currie, the president's private secretary,
conceded that her memory about important events ``was getting worse
by the minute.'' In fact, as the months wore on and Mrs. Currie was
recalled repeatedly to the grand jury, her testimony grew
increasingly forgetful and confused. By Stephen Labaton. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN (Durham, N.C.) _ In other election years, Reps.
David Price and Julia Carson would have had little in common other
than that they were Democrats with relatively safe seats. But party
officials who opened this election year with high hopes of
recapturing the House are beginning to worry that Democratic
incumbents like Price and Mrs. Carson share something else:
greater-than-expected peril on Election Day. By Richard L. Berke.
(With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BILINGUAL (Los Angeles) _ Bilingual education in
California was supposed to be in a grave by now, essentially killed
when residents voted last spring to end it. But more than a month
into the current school term, bilingual education is clearly still
breathing. The reasons are a subject of hot debate. By Don Terry.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PENSION-POLITICS (New York) _ While pension funds for public
employees in nearly every other state are run by boards of public
officials and employees representatives, the New York state
comptroller by law single-handedly controls New York's pension
fund. That gives Carl McCall and his aides the power to hire
investment firms, real estate advisers, lawyers and others to help
invest the holdings of the fund, the second largest of its kind in
the nation, after the California Public Employees Retirement
System. By Clifford Levy.
</P>
<P>
   METHADONE-HEROIN (New York) _ Methadone, which blocks heroin
craving, is the preferred treatment for heroin addiction, though
the notion of fighting one drug with another is still being
debated. But as the White House drug policy director, Gen. Barry
McCaffrey, spoke this week of making methadone more available, New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani continued to insist that abstinence,
not methadone, is the only solution for heroin addicts. By
Christopher S. Wren. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE-TOWNHALL (Austin, Texas) _ In that dark epoch
between the discovery of fire and the discovery of the World Wide
Web, the Bolsheviks had to storm the Winter Palace to get their
point across. Now it can all be done with the gentle click of a
mouse button. By Rick Lyman. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ECON (Washington) _ President Clinton on Friday proposed
changing the International Monetary Fund's procedures so that it
can act earlier to help countries ward off economic crises, rather
than waiting until disaster strikes and bailouts are more
expensive. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-IRAN (Mirbacakot, Afghanistan) _ Just as a final Taliban
victory seems near in this country left impoverished and
demoralized by 20 years of war, so does the possibility of a savage
new chapter in one of the world's bloodiest histories. Some 200,000
Iranian troops are staging military exercises on Afghanistan's
western border. By Barry Bearak. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POSTOFFICE (Moscow) _ In a season of crashing banks,
plunging rubles, bouncing paychecks, failing crops and rotating
governments, maybe it is not the ultimate insult. But the nation
that bore Tolstoy and Chekhov and still regards a well-written
letter as a labor of love is buckling a little this week, because
it can no longer wish good health to Baba Anya in Omsk. The Post
Office is broke. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-U.S.-INDIA-PAKISTAN (United Nations) _ While Congress
debates a temporary waiver of sanctions imposed on India and
Pakistan because of their nuclear tests in May, the Clinton
administration is getting ready to release a long list of companies
and government institutions in those countries that Americans will
be barred from doing business with if the sanctions stay in place.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SALINAS (Mexico City) _ Even in Mexico, where people are
used to hearing that politicians have fat bank accounts, Swiss
police caused a stir when they announced three years ago that Raul
Salinas de Gortari, the brother of the former president, had about
$100 million in secret Swiss bank accounts. Now Mexican
investigators say that his fortune is even heftier. By Julia
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Dobrovode, Yugoslavia) _ For the second day, the thud of
artillery and columns of smoke from burning villages were largely
absent from much of Kosovo Province, leading Western officials to
conclude that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia had
ordered his troops to halt obvious operations against separatist
rebels. By Jane Perlez. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-LESOTHO (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Nine days after
South Africa's disastrous invasion of tiny, mountainous Lesotho,
the kingdom's government and its opposition parties finally sat
down at the negotiating table Friday and agreed that new elections
would be held within 18 months. By Suzanne Daley. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added jobs at a
slower-than-expected pace during September, and the unemployment
rate rose to 4.6 percent from 4.5 percent in August as factories
and builders slashed jobs. By Sylvia Nasar. (With graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-UBS (London) _ As more fallout from the near-collapse
of Long-Term Capital Management LP cascaded over Europe on Friday,
the chairman and three high-ranking officers of UBS AG of
Switzerland resigned _ the most visible casualties to date of
dealings with the American hedge fund. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   LASVEGAS-LAND-DEAL (Las Vegas) _ A deal that saved land on a
Nevada mountainside from development, and at the same time helped
Las Vegas grow, is now at the center of a web of questions and
accusations. By Jon Christensen. (With graphic and photos.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND (Undated) _ Can John Meriwether, the founder of
Long-Term Capital Management and the man behind the hedge fund's
crumbling tower of multibillion-dollar bets on world financial
markets, make another comeback? By Joseph Kahn and Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ After plunging the last two days, stocks
rallied on Friday. But the rebound may be no more than the expected
rebound after a long fall. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROUST-COMIC (Paris) _ A comic book rendering of Marcel Proust's
immense novel, ``Remembrance of Things Past,'' causes an uproar. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-RANGERS (Arlington, Texas) _ Rain slows Yankees'
playoff drive in Texas. By Buster Olney. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LARRY-BIRD (Springfield, Mass.) _ A Bashful Larry Bird joins
hall of fame. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-SPENCER (Arlington, Texas) _ An overnight success, in
just nine seasons. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-PITCHING (Undated) _ A wider strike zone helps good
pitching. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-STRAWBERRY-CANCER (Undated) _ The Strawberrys talk about his
colin cancer. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-STRAWBERRY-SURGERY (Undated) _ Colon cancer is rare for
someone of Strawberry's age, 36. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (Arlington, Texas) _ Cone takes his friends
with him. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   OPINION _ COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `k' category)
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Porgy and Bill. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   OBITUARIES
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-AUTRY _ Gene Autry, America's first movie singing cowboy
and a multimillionaire businessman, died Friday at the age of 91.
Using his familiar theme song of ``Back in the Saddle Again,'' and
riding his famous chestnut stallion Champion, Autry began his climb
to fame in the mid-1930s. Although he later owned hotels,
broadcasting stations, oil wells and a baseball team, he did not
give up performing in films, on radio and television and in his own
rodeo until 1964. By Albin Krebs. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GILL _ Robert Gill, 87, collector of antiques.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BENSON _ Elaine Benson, 74, writer and gallery owner.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-TAYLOR _ Robert Lewis Taylor, 88, novelist and biographer.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-JULIEN _ Pauline Julien, 70, chanteuse who inspired
Quebecois.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service. &QL;
</P>
