<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY AN EXORCISM CAN END MISADVENTURES OF RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It's witch doctor time in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Forget courting Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind improving the starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Put re-signing Royce Clayton to play shortstop on hold.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers need more than anything else right now is an
exorcist.
</P>
<P>
   The Curse of Roger Moret _ what else can it be? _ hangs heavy
around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain it? They've become the team that can't
win for losing. Even when they do something right, it turns out
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Take last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   In a continuing series of misadventures, the Rangers were swept
out of the divisional playoffs by the Yankees, who rode spectacular
rookie Shane Spencer's three-run, sixth-inning homer to a 4-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Make that washed out.
</P>
<P>
   Noah was in the process of throwing a two-hitter for the Yanks
when he realized he'd forgotten his umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it was really David Cone on the mound for the New
Yorkers. But I'll lay 10-to-1 that had to be old Noah, taking a
break from building the ark, who came skidding and sliding across
the tarp disguised as a drunken fan during a 3-hour, 16-minute rain
delay in the bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say rain delay? That hardly does the flooding of The
Ballpark last night justice. That wasn't rain, that was a torrent.
Three batters after Spencer's home run broke the Rangers' hearts,
the heavens opened up like even God was crying.
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise was that when Spencer's shot disappeared into
the left field seats, the lights didn't explode in a shower of
sparks, just like in ``The Natural''.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I forgot. There had already been a pregame power failure
that knocked the lights out for an hour or more, just one more
piece of evidence that something malevolent hovers over this team.
</P>
<P>
   This is the franchise that let a guaranteed spot in the 1981
playoffs slip through its fingers when the Rangers blew a lead in
Milwaukee and lost on the night before the players' strike.
Everyone in first place at the strike got a free ride into a
postseason tier of games.
</P>
<P>
   The same Texas franchise led the terrible West Division by a
game on Aug. 11, 1994. The next day, the owners locked down the
game and the postseason was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they ended a 25-year wait and won their first division
championship in 1996, it came awkwardly and with little fanfare.
While the Rangers were in the midst of a 15-inning loss to the A's,
the Mariners lost to the Angels to clinch it for Texas. It was well
after 1 a.m. before the Rangers finally broke into the champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for this season. Again the Rangers ``clinched'' when
second-place Anaheim lost at Oakland. The Rangers went on to lose
in Seattle before kicking off their champagne party at around 2
a.m. Texas time. Most of their fans had already gone to bed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even mentioned the Sammy Sosa trade.
</P>
<P>
   Now this.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers can't even get their butts kicked in the playoffs
without messing it up.
</P>
<P>
   With a sellout crowd on hand after one of the hottest and driest
summers in Texas history, it rains like the proverbial cow
straddling the flat rock. Only this time the flat rock is The
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Until the rain finally stopped and the game resumed at 12:24
this morning, the Rangers were contemplating being part of the
first suspended game in baseball postseason history.
</P>
<P>
   Some accomplishment, huh?
</P>
<P>
   And pity poor manager Johnny Oates. He states the obvious _ that
the Rangers' chances of winning this best-of-five series with the
Yankees depended on starting pitching _ and the baseball gods throw
it back in his face like acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers get the starting pitching Oates had prayed for, but
their offense, which was second only to the Yankees in scoring runs
this season, suffers a complete blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' best hitters _ Juan Gonzalez, Rusty Greer, Will Clark,
Pudge Rodriguez _ the heart of his lineup, turn to mud pies, going
a combined 4-for-44 (.091) with 1 RBI in 27 innings.
</P>
<P>
   One is a very lonely number when it's your team's only run in
three games.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for desperate measures; time for Rangers' ownership to
put out an all points bulletin and find the witch doctor or priest
who can lift the voodoo Curse of Roger Moret. Moret is the Rangers'
left-hander who went into a catatonic trance in the clubhouse in
1978, waved a shower shoe at his teammates and put a curse on the
franchise that still bites them at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody or some thing has been doing a rain dance on the
Rangers' heads for 27 years now. The next sprinkles that hit The
Ballpark in Arlington had better be holy water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
