<HEADLINE>
CONE COMES THROUGH WITH INSPIRED OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ David Cone was concerned about his friend,
Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the Yankees outfielder had colon cancer hit all
his teammates hard, but none more so than Cone. The pitcher and the
outfielder have known each other since 1987, when both played for
the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very close for a long time, and we've had our ups
and downs in New York,'' Cone said. ``When it strikes this close to
home it shakes you up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought that Cone might be too shaken to pitch
Game 3 of the American League Division Series against the Rangers,
but the pitcher rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl would want me to go out there and pitch,'' he said. ``I
am going to be ready to pitch, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than letting his good friend's ailment negatively affect
him, Cone seemed to use it as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   He shut out the Rangers for 5 2/3 innings last night, and had a
4-0 lead when the rains came. He did not return to the game after a
delay of more than three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Strong pitching was nothing new for the Yankees. David Wells was
virtually untouchable in Game 1. The Yankees left-hander pitched
eight shutout innings, allowing five hits and striking out nine, to
beat the Rangers, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte was almost as good in Game 2. He allowed one run
on three hits in seven innings as the Yankees won again, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expected it to be different last night for Game 3.
After all, they did hit .304 and averaged 6.02 runs per game at The
Ballpark during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, though, made this game look like a clone of the first two.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Yankees right-hander was even better than Wells
and Pettitte. Cone allowed two hits, and walked one batter. He
struck out six.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious early that Cone, a 20-game winner in the regular
season, had his best stuff. He struck out Tom Goodwin to open the
game, and got Mark McLemore on a routine grounder to third.
</P>
<P>
   He showed a little weakness by walking Rusty Greer on four
pitches, bringing Juan Gonzalez to the plate, but Cone got the
Rangers' RBI machine to pop up to short.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' first hit came in the third inning when Royce
Clayton led off with a single and Goodwin bunted him to second to
put the potential go-ahead run in scoring position in a scoreless
game. Cone, though, didn't fold. He struck out McLemore and got
Greer on a grounder to second.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had to work hard to preserve the shutout in the fifth. Todd
Zeile singled with one out, and Clayton battled through a 10-pitch
at-bat. Cone finally struck him out, and Zeile, going with every
3-2 pitch, was thrown out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
