<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORYBOOK SEASON FOR SPENCER SPELLS MIDNIGHT FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Whether he is a rising star or a flash in the
pinstriped pan does not matter for the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   By the dim light of next April, Shane Spencer may turn out to be
another Kevin Maas.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, he is Roy Hobbs.
</P>
<P>
   Need a replacement for Darryl Strawberry? There is Shane
Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Need a fairy-tale answer to their left-field prayers? There is
Shane Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Need a home run in the sixth inning that loomed last night as
the fatal blow to the Rangers? Here comes Spencer again.
</P>
<P>
   His name sounds like that of a soap-opera star, but what Spencer
has done is too farfetched for the movies. Even in Hollywood, the
heroes don't always hit home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But Spencer seems to.
</P>
<P>
   His three-run smash off the Rangers' Aaron Sele last night
turned a taut pitchers duel into a vigil for the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In 27 Yankees games this season, as the rookie bobbed up and
down from the minor leagues, Spencer hit 10 home runs _ one for
every 6.7 times at bat. In his first postseason trip to the plate
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium, Spencer homered again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane-Saw Massacre,'' the headline in the New York tabloid
read.
</P>
<P>
   Like the mythical Hobbs in the movie ``The Natural,'' whatever
the situation calls for, Spencer seems to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys keep saying it's a dream, then I guess it's a
dream,'' Spencer told the media before Game 3 of the American
League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Reeking of Cinderella innocence, he said he was happy just to
get in the game. He said he hoped he got a chance to play again.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, pinch him. Make his clock chime midnight. Tell Spencer
that he's a career minor-leaguer who, toiling this season for
Triple-A Columbus, hit only 18 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, of course, did not need a Shane Spencer. They had
114 victories. They had capable left-field hands in Chad Curtis and
Tim Raines. They had David Cone, David Wells and the legend of the
Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they also didn't need the motivation/distraction
caused by the sobering diagnosis of Strawberry. The next time you
chant, ``Dar-ryl, Dar-ryl,'' please attach a prayer at the end of
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the saga in New York keeps adding more chapters, lending
more and more credence to the notion that this Yankees team, of all
Yankees teams, has been kissed by fate. You'll probably get no
arguments from the Rangers, who clearly were blinded by the New
York marquee lights in this series.
</P>
<P>
   From the first pitch Tuesday to Spencer's soaring home run last
night, it was no contest. The scores were close, but the poker
hands were not.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you give a team that has everything?
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' Spencer said between games 2 and 3. ``I
guess I'm surprised it's all happening at once. I only thought that
if I had the chance, I could probably do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's chances had come in sporadic doses. As various Yankees
lapsed on and off the disabled list, Spencer became the team's
outfield Kelly Girl. On April 7, he was called up from Columbus to
take the place of Chili Davis. Three weeks later, he was sent back
down.
</P>
<P>
   Three more times, the Yankees yo-yoed Spencer to and from
Columbus. He returned for keeps on Aug. 31, and in the month that
followed, Spencer batted .421 with eight home runs, including three
grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   (Cue theme from ``The Natural'' here.)
</P>
<P>
   For nine seasons, Spencer punched his clock in the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, everybody gets discouraged in the minor leagues,'' he
said. ``But if you see some of your friends make it on other teams,
that's what keeps you going.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't be for real, or can he? Yankees fans remember another
candle in the wind, outfielder Maas. He joined the Yankees during
the 1990 season and promptly exploded for 21 home runs in 79 games.
He was dubbed the next young Yankee hero.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991, Maas' average dipped to .220. By the '93 season,
his last in the major leagues, Maas' output was down to nine home
runs and he was batting .205.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not just a one-month thing,'' Spencer said of his
own meteoric arrival. ``I think if you were to ask anyone who has
played with me, they would say that I'm for real. I hope to just
carry on to next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, of course, does not matter. For now, the Yankees are
rolling and Shane Spencer is playing like a Hollywood creation come
to life.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, pinch him. Pinch the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It's midnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
