<HEADLINE>
LOUSY WEATHER CAN'T BREAK RANGERS' SCORING DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It rained so hard and for so long Friday
night that even:
</P>
<P>
   Noah abandoned ship.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard cutters docked in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Seals did underwater training dives in both dugouts.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Bob Costas and Joe Morgan quit their telecast to do
commentary for The Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs drowned.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine pitch was outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   The spitter was too soggy.
</P>
<P>
   Bass fishing was permitted in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires were issued scuba gear.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines changed his name.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, who cares if the skies opened up and it poured a
foot of water? Or if Arlington's treasure of a stadium is renamed
The Ballpark in Grand Prairie after it floated a few miles down
I-30?
</P>
<P>
   Heavy flooding and high water might have signified an end to the
longest, hottest and driest drought in years, but who's talking
about the weather anyway?
</P>
<P>
   One drought, the one that has brought dust-bowl, postseason
misery to the Texas Rangers, showed no signs of breaking. Right up
until the storm hit in the sixth inning Friday night, the Rangers'
bats continued to suck the playoff life out of this team.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was the Yankees' David Cone in Game 3. Before Cone,
of course, it had been David Wells and Andy Pettitte. All are
capable of dominating any batting order at any time. But to do it
back-to-back-to-back suggests maybe other circumstances are
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Has the Yankees pitching been this great, or have the Rangers
hitters simply choked in the postseason spotlight?
</P>
<P>
   And if the choke theory has any validity, which it does, then it
wouldn't be the first time. Two years ago in a division series
against the same Yankees, Juan Gonzalez became a one-man RBI
machine (five homers, nine RBI in four games). But Juan alone kept
the Rangers alive for those four games. The remainder of the
batting order disappeared into the October pressure-cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this time even Gonzalez is missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Through two outs in the sixth inning Friday night, the Rangers
had been shut out on two hits by Cone. And while Aaron Sele pitched
impressively through five shutout innings, the Yankees pounced on
him in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   In that inning, Paul O'Neill drilled a 408-foot solo shot into
the Yankees bullpen. That was probably enough to beat the Rangers.
But with two outs and the bases clear, Sele came apart after an
infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Already over the 100-pitch mark, Sele received a mound visit
from pitching coach Dick Bosman, who must have seen something from
the dugout he didn't like. The Yankees, however, would suddenly see
plenty of hittable pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Raines drilled a double to left, and with two runners on, Babe
Ruth's rookie ghost, Shane Spencer, cashed in again.
</P>
<P>
   Sele started Spencer with a hanging curveball that was
immediately jacked into the left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Down 4-0, the Rangers were waiting for the sweep of the broom.
Here's a team that had scored once in 23 innings on the Yankees,
and then had two quick outs to start the bottom of the sixth.
That's when the skies opened and the flood came.
</P>
<P>
   Choking bats or great pitching? It is a worthy debate.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates is a manager who strongly backed his hitters after
the first two games at Yankee Stadium. And in pregame interviews
Friday night, he was again vocal in saying this was a case where
New York pitching should receive full credit.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a concession by Oates to either New York pitching or
his gagging batting order, Oates backed his words with game
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   When shortstop Royce Clayton led off the third with a single,
Oates had Tom Goodwin bunting. Goodwin got it down, moving up
Clayton, only to have Mark McLemore take a called third strike and
a hopeless Rusty Greer roll out weakly on a check swing.
</P>
<P>
   But the second-highest scoring team in the league (to the
Yankees) was bunting in the third inning of a scoreless game _
highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it was, however, label the bunt as the right move
even if it didn't produce a run. Oates has been stuck with a
dreaded ``small-ball'' team in this series.
</P>
<P>
   And late Friday night, as the long delay continued, it was
unlikely even the rainstorm from hell could postpone the Rangers
quick and scoreless exit from the postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
