<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNCHLESS RANGERS GO MEEKLY INTO THE NIGHT, 4-0, SWEPT AWAY BY
YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Perhaps God, too, grew disgusted by the sight
of the Rangers' futile at-bats throughout this American League
Division Series. Maybe that explains why the heavens unleashed
intense rains, intimidating thunder and bolts of lightning upon The
Ballpark in Arlington after second baseman Mark McLemore took a
called third strike during the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, though, only prolonged the inevitable, with the New
York Yankees eventually defeating Texas, 4-0, after a rain delay of
3 hours, 16 minutes, to sweep the best-of-five series. The game
resumed at 12:24 a.m. today and ended shortly before 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The punchless Rangers generated only three hits, totaled only 13
in the series, and scored only one run in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Shane Spencer, the Yankees' rookie cult hero, broke
open the game with one sixth-inning swing that yielded more
offensive production than the Rangers managed in the entire series.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, whose eight home runs and 21 runs batted in during
September led the Yankees, crushed a first-pitch curveball thrown
by right-hander Aaron Sele and deposited it into the left-field
seats. The 371-foot, three-run homer placed the Rangers' dormant
lineup at an insurmountable, 4-0 disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander David Cone became the third member of the Yankees'
vaunted rotation to dominate the Rangers. Cone allowed only two
hits. He did not return after the rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who surrendered only four hits and one walk through five
innings, found the home run his undoing. Right fielder Paul O'Neill
plated the Yankees' first run with his one-out, opposite-field home
run, and consecutive, two-out base hits by first baseman Tino
Martinez and designated hitter Tim Raines brought Spencer to the
plate for the game's definitive at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who surrendered only 0.59 home runs per nine innings this
season, avoided that particular torment as well as any AL pitcher
this season. The right-hander surrendered only 14 through 212 2/3
innings. That ranked second only to Blue Jays right-hander Roger
Clemens, who surrendered 0.37 home runs per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Those two home runs, though, did not cost the Rangers this
series.
</P>
<P>
   Their stagnant lineup did.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton's third-inning single to center field
marked only the fourth time this series that the Rangers' leadoff
hitter in an inning reached safely.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates acknowledged the Rangers' offensive woes
when he chose to sacrifice during the third inning of a scoreless
game. Clayton advanced 90 feet on the ensuing bunt by center
fielder Tom Goodwin, but Cone retired McLemore on strikes and
induced a weak, inning-ending ground ball from left fielder Rusty
Greer.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton also became involved in another offensive threat
short-circuited by a lack of execution. Third baseman Todd Zeile
reached on a one-out single, and Clayton found himself embroiled in
a 10-pitch at-bat with Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton fouled three consecutive 3-2 pitches before swinging
through what appeared to be ball four, and Zeile _ who ran with the
pitch _ was caught stealing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
