<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-NATO-TROOPS (Camp Dobol) _ By and large, American and
other NATO troops have accomplished what they were sent to do under
the Dayton peace accords that ended Bosnia's civil war in 1995:
they have separated the warring armies, stockpiled their arms,
opened roads and rebuilt bridges, made it safer for the people of
Bosnia to get on with their lives. What they have not yet done is
find a way out.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-CROATIA (Marija Bistrica, Croatia) _ In Croatia, Pope John
Paul II beatified the World War II archbishop of Zagreb who was
later imprisoned by the Tito regime as a Nazi collaborator. But by
paying so high a hommage to Cardinal Alojzije Stepinac, the pope
also stepped into one of the most divisive disputes between
Croatians and Serbs throughout the embattled regions of the former
Yugoslavia. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-WORLDBANK-MEET (Washington) _ As financial leaders from the
world's largest nations, as well as from many of the most
shell-shocked, gathered on Saturday for talks on stabilizing the
global economy, the Clinton administration faced unusual challenges
from Europe, Japan and emerging-market nations, each of which is
arriving with different and even contradictory strategies.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POVERTY (Xian) _ A look at urban poverty in China. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ELECT (Rio de Janeiro) _ Brazil gets ready for a national
election on Sunday. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-MAHATHIR (Kuala Lumpur) _ Among Asia's leaders, Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad was notable as a man with a bold vision:
a physical and social transformation that would push Malaysia into
the forefront of world affairs. It almost came true. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-CORRUPTION-REPORT (United Nations) _ Transparency
International, a small independent organization that has been
tracking for four years how the public and international businesses
view corruption worldwide, has published its largest survey to
date, looking at 85 countries and ranking only one completely
clean: Denmark. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SYRIA (Istanbul) _ Tension between Turkey and Syria has
risen to the point where the top Turkish military commander says
the two hostile neighbors have reached ``a state of undeclared
war.'' By Stephen Kinzer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-IMMIG-SURVEILLANCE (Toronto) _ A new law that tightens
America's borders by tracking every foreigner who enters the United
States has been postponed because immigration officials say they
are not ready to handle the job and Congress is not sure it really
wants the measure enforced. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   APOCALYPTIC-RAPTURE (Undated) _ In an instant, millions of
people disappear from the face of the Earth, shedding clothing,
shoes, eyeglasses, jewelry. Were they snatched by aliens? Vaporized
by a spontaneous chemical reaction? No, what has occurred is the
Rapture. Jesus Christ has returned to take the genuine Christians
to heaven. So goes the plot of ``Left Behind,'' a series of four
books of apocalyptic fiction that have now sold nearly 3 million
copies _ as many as a John Grisham novel and have now ascended to
the top four slots on religion best-sellers lists. The ``Left
Behind'' phenomenon is one indication of the public's fixation on
the approaching millenium and the widespread anticipation that the
year 2000 portends some Earth-shattering event.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-MINING (Golden, Colo.) _ A massive, illuminated `M'
burns nightly on a hillside here, a reminder that this town was
founded by gold miners and is home to the Colorado School of Mines.
For tourists, Golden celebrates its mining heritage with a mining
museum and welcoming banners featuring a broad-hatted miner panning
for gold. But, this spring Jeff Keller, president of a Golden
paving company, committed the ultimate faux pas in the faux west.
He asked to open a mine. Throughout the Colorado Rockies, mining
tourism is the booming business. But visitors should not confuse
Western sentimentality over mining history with a love for modern
mining. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SPACESTATION (Undated) _ In a concession born of crisis,
Russia has agreed to sell to the United States most of its allotted
research time aboard the first phase of the international space
station. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-FORECASTER (New Orleans) _ Nash Roberts, a meteorologist
from the old school, is famous for his hurricane predictions. He
struck again with Georges, forecasting, when no one else did, that
the storm would veer away from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MAYANS (Los Angeles) _ About 50,000 Mayans were among
250,000 Central Americans who fled torture, rape and murder in the
1980s during a civil war in their native Guatemala. Now, many are
facing immigration hearings under a new federal law. But many
Mayans speak indigenous Indian languages and know only basic
Spanish, not enough to represent themselves adequately at the
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   KLAN-BLACKLAWYER (Richmond, Va.) _ A black lawyer will defend a
member of the Ku Klux Klan who faces felony charges for burning a
cross at a Klan rally.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-DEMS (Los Angeles) _ In 1992, in a good year for
Democrats, Barbara Boxer won her seat in the U.S. Senate with 48
percent of the vote. In the six years since, she has been a
reliably outspoken liberal from a state that is less so, and never
managed to boost her job approval ratings above 50 percent. In
1998, in what is shaping up as a hard year for Democrats around the
nation, Ms. Boxer has struggled to hold her own in the polls
against a comparative neophyte, the Republican state treasurer,
Matt Fong, despite a prodigious fundraising advantage and the
powers of incumbency. Now their contest has become one of a handful
of closely watched races that will help determine whether the
Republicans can achieve a filibuster-proof 60 seat majority in the
Senate that could shape the congressional landscape for years to
come. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   BAIT-VENDING (Newburgh, N.Y.) _ In the closing years of the
millennium, the ancient art of angling is going through some
changes, none more startling than the advent of vending machines
for live worms, grubs, crayfish, tadpoles, even minnows. The
machines, doling out bait 24 hours a day, are attractive to
fishermen because bait shops are increasingly hard to find and are
often closed at the odd hours when the fish are biting.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
