 (ATTN: N.Y., Iowa, Mass.)  
 FISHING IN THE '90s: WORMS FROM A MACHINE  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) (bl)  
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURGH, N.Y. _ At a sleepy rural intersection here in the
Hudson Valley, the quintessential ``going fishing'' scene was
unfolding. A creaky old pickup truck drove by, with grandparents
squeezed into the cab around two boys with eager faces who had the
day off from school.
</P>
<P>
   In the back was the fishing tackle. Nearby was a small lake. All
they needed was bait. That was where the Norman Rockwell qualities
of the morning evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spading up soil or looking for a bait shop, the
family pulled in at Maisie's Deli and parked next to a refrigerated
vending machine. Mike Cerone, 76, and his grandsons, Alex and
Austin Hieronymi, 8 and 6, plunked 10 quarters into the slot. Alex
pushed a button marked ``night crawlers.'' Out plopped a Styrofoam
canister full of wriggling worms.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling broadly, the family drove away, rowed out into the lake,
and began snagging bluegills.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing years of the millennium, the ancient art of
angling is going through some changes, none more startling than the
advent of vending machines for live worms, grubs, crayfish,
tadpoles, even minnows.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, doling out bait 24 hours a day, are attractive to
fishermen because bait shops are increasingly hard to find and are
sometimes closed at the odd hours when the fish are biting.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of the machines have popped up in suburbs and rural areas
around New York City in the last two years, and Daniel Bartholomew,
a Hudson Valley farmer turned worm tycoon has quickly become the
country's second-largest operator of the devices.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are manufactured by Vending Consultants Inc., in
Des Moines, Iowa, which devised them two years ago after learning
that some bait shops and mom-and-pop stores had been modifying
refrigerated sandwich vending machines for years to serve up cups
of worms. Those jury-rigged machines were not designed to endure
the elements, however, and so Vending Consultants developed one for
outdoor use.
</P>
<P>
   It sold 15 of the new machines in 1996, 700 last year, and now
has 2,000 dispensing bait in almost every state and in parts of
Canada, said James Chico, vice president for sales. The machines
sell for $3,995, delivered. Negotiations are under way with
companies in Italy and Portugal to export them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bartholomew started last year with one machine on his front lawn
in Modena, a few miles north of Newburgh. With its glowing picture
of hungry bass and walleyes and its bright-yellow logo, the machine
quickly attracted attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys in a Mercedes in three-piece suits bought bait and
just looked at it,'' he said. ``They just couldn't believe bait was
coming out of a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   When he found he was typically pulling $900 a month in cash from
the machine, he said, he quickly expanded his business and now has
28, including the one at Maisie's Deli. He plans to have 100
machines by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After his latest customers left the parking lot at Maisie's,
Bartholomew, 37, unlocked the machine and restocked slots inside
with more of the white cups containing four types of worms and
grubs.
</P>
<P>
   The worms can stay alive for as long as 10 days on the mix of
peat moss and powdered newsprint in the cups, he said, adding, ``A
lot of the time they're bigger when you get them than when I put
them in.'' The machines have a thermostat that keeps the bait at 40
to 45 degrees in summer and warmer in winter, for ice fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this great?'' he said. ``If you told me two years ago
that I'd be making a great living selling worms from machines, I'd
have told you you were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, machines that he operates or has sold for a commission to
other entrepreneurs sit at marinas, gas stations, bait shops and
other spots from southern New Jersey to the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Often they are placed next to more conventional machines for
soda and snacks, leading to quizzical stares and questions when
Bartholomew comes by with his blue van full of worms and other
bait.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, he said, he may try to set up machines in New
York City for the growing number of urban anglers. But the city was
a bit intimidating, he said, what with persistent rumors that
organized crime still controlled the vending machine business. For
the time being, he said, there was plenty of room to expand _ for
example, in the Adirondacks, where fishing is popular all year.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are proving popular with owners of small
convenience stores, who benefit from the steady stream of anglers
they attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about convenience,'' said Farshid Hessari, the owner
of a gas station in Fishkill with one of Bartholomew's machines
outside. ``People come in and pick up beer, ice, and bait in one
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before making the rounds to collect money and replenish bait
supplies, Bartholomew started the day by entering a home-built
cooler, made from the back of an old refrigerated delivery truck,
which jutted from a converted barn behind his brick ranch house in
Modena. He pulled a Styrofoam tray of dirt from a stack and dumped
it onto a bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of six-inch night crawlers, imported from Canada,
slithered in the loam. He plunged his hands into the mass of
squirming worms and dirt, picking out a dozen to drop into each
white canister.
</P>
<P>
   When he started, he said, New York state had no worm
wholesalers, and Massachusetts companies were sending trucks from
Canada to bait stores here. Now Bartholomew has got into that end
of the business as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of money to be made in worms,'' he said,
explaining that the wholesale cost is around $25 per thousand in
the spring and up to $80 or more per thousand in the summer. They
can live for many months in the cooler, before he transfers them to
the machines.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he said, he had about 20,000 worms on hand, but he
was preparing to build a small climate-controlled warehouse where
he could stockpile up to 10 million. That way, he said, he can buy
low and sell high.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, he said, he would move some of the machines to
spots along the Hudson River that are frequented by anglers seeking
striped bass. Those machines will be stocked with live eels,
bloodworms, and other delicacies favored by ocean-going fish.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next year or two, Vending Consultants is
planning to introduce machines with a freezer inside that can
handle whole fish, which are popular as bait for deep-sea fishing,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, he continued on his rounds, dropping off worms
and picking up money. ``The sky's the limit,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
