<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RED SOX' HAUNTING HERITAGE ALWAYS THERE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the Red Sox, the past is always present. If it's
not Babe Ruth's departure, it's Bucky Dent's home run. If it's not
why Jim Willoughby wasn't pitching, it's why Bobby Sprowl was.
</P>
<P>
   After the Red Sox lost, 4-3, to the Cleveland Indians at Fenway
Park on Friday in the third game of their American League division
series, their 44-year-old reliever, Dennis Eckersley, who has
appeared in more major league games than any other pitcher in
history, was talking about Manny Ramirez's leadoff home run in the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He crushed that ball,'' Eckersley said.
</P>
<P>
   Crushed the Red Sox, too. When the Red Sox rallied in the ninth
on Nomar Garciaparra's two-run homer, Ramirez's homer, his second
of the game, turned out to be the winning run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the homer that beat us,'' Eckersley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Reggie Jackson's homer,'' somebody said.
</P>
<P>
   That somebody could have been almost anybody in what is known as
the Red Sox nation. In their haunting heritage, Red Sox fans aren't
just fans, they're historians. They'll never forget Bucky Dent's
homer in the 5-4 loss to the Yankees in their 1978 AL East one-game
playoff, but they also remember that Mr. October's homer off Bob
Stanley in the top of the eighth made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley remembered something else. As a 20-game winner as a
Red Sox starter that year, he had gone back to the clubhouse in the
seventh inning on Oct. 2, 1978, when the Red Sox were winning, 2-0.
``I was watching workmen putting up the television platform for our
celebration,'' Eckersley said. ``Celebrating on television was a
big deal then. But as soon as Bucky hit that three-run homer off
Mike Torrez, the workmen started tearing down that platform.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their rivalry, that 1978 playoff has been the only
Yankee-Red Sox post-season game in a history that has been hallowed
for the Yankees, haunted for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the possibility of a Yankee-Red Sox duel in this
year's AL Championship Series was so compelling. If it developed,
there would be at least four chances and maybe as many as seven for
another Bucky Dent moment for the Yankees or, finally, for a moment
that the Red Sox could cherish.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Red Sox confronted by elimination in Saturday's
fourth game with the Indians, the past again intruded on the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, the Red Sox ace with a 19-7 record and the
winner of the series opener, offered to start on three days' rest
instead of his usual four. Considering Martinez's six-year, $75
million contract, Red Sox historians judged that offer to be the
least he could do.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox manager, Jimy Williams, preferred to start the
left-hander Pete Schourek, who was an erratic 8-9 this season _ 1-3
with the Red Sox after being obtained on Aug.6 from Houston, where
he had gone 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for it and I was denied,'' Martinez said. ``I'm not
hurting. I can throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams acknowledged the temptation to use Martinez on three
days' rest, but resisted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Temptation, yeah,'' the Red Sox manager said. ``Come to my
senses, no. That's my opinion. I'll live with it. Schourek is a
good pitcher. Regardless of what people think, I believe this is
the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   At least publicly, his players supported the manager's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good decision,'' said Mo Vaughn, the Red Sox slugger.
``If we win, we'll have our ace going Sunday in the decisive fifth
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But every Red Sox historian worth a bowl of New England clam
chowder remembered a somewhat similar situation in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth game of that series with the Yankees in
mid-September,'' one of those historians recalled. ``After the
Yankees took the first three games, Luis Tiant asked to pitch the
fourth game on three days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, then the Red Sox manager and now Joe Torre's bench
coach on the Yankees, preferred to start Bobby Sprowl, up from
Pawtucket of the International League, who had lost his debut five
days earlier in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sprowl walked four of the first six Yankees, Zimmer
yanked him. The Yankees won, 7-4, and were suddenly tied for first
place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, in the seventh game of the World Series,
the Red Sox manager, Darrell Johnson, made another haunting
decision. In a 3-3 tie, Johnson removed his third pitcher, Jim
Willougby, who had blanked the Cincinnati Reds in the eighth
inning, and had Jim Burton open the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds scored one run, and the Red Sox lost, 4-3. Ever since,
Red Sox historians have wondered, ``Why did he take out
Willoughby?''
</P>
<P>
   And when ESPN suddenly showed a flashback of Bucky Dent's homer
during Friday's game, one of those Red Sox historians reacted with
a growl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anybody got a gun?'' the historian asked.
</P>
<P>
   The historian wasn't laughing. He wasn't even smiling. With the
Red Sox, the past is always present.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
