<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE THUNDER ROLLS, AND SO DO THE YANKEES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ What if it turned out that the Yankees are
every bit as good as their 114 victories would indicate? Could they
roll through the post-season the way they rolled through the
regular season?
</P>
<P>
   It's a valid question after the way the Yankees eliminated the
Rangers in three straight games, ending early Saturday with a 4-0
blanking. They did not let themselves be distracted by a brutal
storm that took their pitcher, David Cone, out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were they thrown off by Darryl Strawberry's scheduled cancer
surgery. Before the game, they saw a brief video with Strawberry
pointing his finger at the camera and commanding, ``Do it!'' And do
it they did.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees never let the Rangers into the series, with David
Wells, Andy Pettitte and Cone and the bullpen holding the best
hitting team in their league to one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three gems,'' Bernie Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason to think the Yankees could not do it to,
let's say, Cleveland and Atlanta in the next two rounds? Could they
sweep the post-season? ``This is a very well-balanced team,'' said
Brian Cashman, the 31-year-old general manager who is only nine
years out of Catholic University. ``In the long run, the best team
is going to win, but this is the short run now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had feared a three-of-five-game series, because one
rough pitcher or one quick slump could have sent them out of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we got our legs cut out from us in Cleveland,''
Manager Joe Torre recalled. ``We had a 2-1 lead in that series and
played well. We just had to credit Cleveland for beating us. This
is the scariest series. We're very relieved that it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Torre's inspired patience, the Yankees are currently one
of the most cohesive professional teams you will ever see,
particularly in this time of free agents moving from team to team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tells you a lot about this ball club,'' said Williams,
who was without a hit in 10 at-bats in this series. ``I'm not
hitting, but somebody like Shane Spencer picks us up. No one person
in particular is responsible for offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer might not have been playing as much if Strawberry had
not been growing weaker late in the season before discovering he
was ill. Spencer clubbed his second homer of the playoffs, a
three-run shot for the 4-0 lead in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would have wrapped it up literally a day earlier but
for the monster of a thunderstorm that held up play for 3 hours 16
minutes. The flags suddenly reversed course, as the system of
storms and tornadoes approached, and the rains came after Cone had
pitched five and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   The delay could have been a blessing for the Rangers, because it
took Cone out of the game when his side-wheeling curveball was
dropping out of the strike zone, when he still had muscle on his
fastball. The four runs were not official until the Rangers made
one more out in the sixth, so the Yankees knew the game would be
resumed.
</P>
<P>
   During the long delay, the players changed into dry clothes and
watched a movie, ``Dumb and Dumber,'' appropriately enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty dumb,'' admitted reliever Jeff Nelson, ``but it
got guys laughing together.''
</P>
<P>
   When the storm ended, Graeme Lloyd, Nelson and Mariano Rivera
took turns replacing Cone. Their innings were as placid as his had
been. These guys are all veterans of the 1996 championship, and
they just won the second highest total of games in baseball
history. Now they are on a roll, despite the loss of a popular
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days have been surreal, incredible,'' Cone said.
``An unbelievable emotional day yesterday. Guys came full circle
today, a lot of guys talked to Darryl, we got a video message from
him, and everyone felt pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   They felt even better when the rain ended and then the bullpen
ended the game. There was some question of whether the Yanks would
stage a Champagne and beer celebration in the clubhouse afterward,
given Strawberry's illness and the high expectations coming from
the 114 victories.
</P>
<P>
   However, the plastic covers were up, to protect the clothing in
the lockers from a Champagne and beer spray. Tim Raines proposed a
toast to Strawberry, and in a relieved spirit the players ran
around with bottles in their hands, spraying each other, sloshing
shaving cream on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it in 1996 when we won the division series,'' Cashman
said. ``Right in this clubhouse. We didn't get out of this series
in 1995 and 1997, so we felt this was an accomplishment, so we
celebrated.''
</P>
<P>
   They earned their celebration, and some time off to be with
their families and perhaps visit Strawberry in the hospital. Then
it is back to business Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent was not determined as they ran around spraying each
other, but the question is: just who is going to beat these guys? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
