<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ELECT-NYT &LR;      10-03 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ECONOMIC WOES, BRAZIL'S LEADER LIKELY TO WIN ANOTHER TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ With their vast country struggling
against economic collapse that could usher high inflation back in,
and with a $30 billion rescue package in the balance, Brazilians
are expected to re-elect President Fernando Henrique Cardoso on
Sunday, rejecting the three-time candidate of the left, Luiz Inacio
Lula da Silva.
</P>
<P>
   But the euphoria of four years ago, when Cardoso rode to victory
on a plan for ending inflation and modernizing the role of the
state, has disappeared. The Real Plan, named for the new currency,
the real, has been crippled by the government's failure to rein in
spending. This time Brazilians are bracing for a morning after
marked by austerity, recession, joblessness and tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   Jolted by the economic breakdowns in Asia and Russia, the
Brazilian stock market has been stumbling through the year like a
battered giant, crashing and resurging time and again, losing 41
percent of its value since January. About $30 billion in foreign
reserves have fled Brazil for safer havens since Russia's market
collapse in late August.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently a prized market for direct foreign investment,
Brazil is now feared as the country most likely to draw the storms
of Asia to U.S. shores. Foreign investors are watching Brazil
closely, in the expectation that a triumphant President Cardoso
will tackle reforms immediately. A $30 billion International
Monetary Fund plan to salvage Brazil's faltering economy also
depends on a Cardoso victory.
</P>
<P>
   Though congressional seats and state houses in this nation of
160 million people are also at stake, attention is focusing almost
entirely on the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This last year has brought a new uncertainty,'' said Antonio
Carlos Alkimin, director of population studies at the Brazilian
Institute for Geography and Statistics. ``People are voting more
against inflation and against a leftist government than with a
sense of optimism over what will happen when Fernando Henrique
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the crisis is like a dark cloud hovering offshore. A
Central Bank doubling of interest rates to stanch the outflow of
dollars braked industrial expansion, and unemployment is the
highest in 15 years. But deeper cuts in government services, public
sector layoffs, tax increases and other drastic measures are on
hold until after the president's presumed re-election, as are the
terms Brazil will have to meet for the IMF bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Polls predict that Cardoso, who won a constitutional amendment
allowing presidents to run for re-election, will become the first
Brazilian president to succeed himself. He is expected to take 47
percent of Sunday's vote, a large enough amount to avoid run-off
elections Oct. 25. His nearest rival, da Silva of the Workers
Party, was projected to win 24 percent. Former Finance Minister
Ciro Gomes is expected to take 9 percent of the vote. And an
excitable surgeon known simply as Eneas, who calls for Brazil to
build an atomic bomb, is expected to get 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the election approaches, the images and slogans of candidates
across the political spectrum have been multiplying, their banners
fluttering from trees and lampposts. In the twice-daily free
television time that has become the centerpiece of political
campaigns, the two leading candidates present visions of themselves
and Brazil that could hardly be more at odds.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso's television programs feature a determinedly upbeat
country, with a chorus of smiling teen-agers singing the
president's praises and exhorting voters to turn out for him.
Though Cardoso used part of his air time to rebroadcast a speech he
made warning of postelection fiscal adjustments, his message has
been one of stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our efforts, all of our achievements, cannot end when
we're only halfway there,'' the president said in his final
broadcast on Thursday night. ``In the middle of a world crisis, a
country with so many resources and possibilities, a country with so
much international support, which gains more respect abroad each
day, whose people are serious and hard-working, has no reason to
change direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The program for da Silva, who is universally known as Lula,
features black-and-white footage of him marching against the
military dictatorship that ended in 1985 and commiserating with the
poor. A former president of the Metalworkers Union, da Silva left
school to begin working at 15, and lost a finger operating a lathe.
</P>
<P>
   This election, da Silva traded the berets and polo shirts of the
past for suits and measured speech, but his ideas remain far to the
left of Cardoso's. He opposes a deal with the IMF and says Brazil's
priority should be Brazilians' social needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never accepted that a country as rich as ours should have
so much inequality, so much misery,'' said da Silva. ``The banks
and the international speculators can wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso has also committed gaffes that have fed into the Workers
Party's image of him as a leader removed from the problems of the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   During his administration's so-far-unsuccessful push to
restructure social security benefits, Cardoso said people who
wanted to retire early were ``bums.'' Although the president later
explained that he meant to attack professionals who retire after 20
or 25 years, millions of Brazilian pensioners who had begun their
working lives as children felt themselves maligned.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, word leaked that the 67-year-old President has
himself been collecting a pension, currently at $4,300 a month,
ever since Brazil's military dictatorship forced him to stop
teaching at the University of Sao Paulo in 1969. Although the
president could have returned to teaching 10 years later, he chose
to keep the pension instead.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Amaral, the president's spokesman, said Cardoso saw no
reason to give up the pension, since he had been ``retired by an
arbitrary act of the military government, and he continued working
for the country as politician and then President.'' He said Cardoso
gave up a second pension he could have collected for having been a
Senator.
</P>
<P>
   And in an August speech at the Parque Royale slum outside Rio,
the president stunned residents when he said: ``There's no way to
make everybody rich. I don't even know if it's worth the trouble,
because the life of a rich person, in general, is very boring.''
</P>
<P>
   He later explained that as a working man he did not count
himself wealthy, but that only made his misstep worse. Cardoso's
$6,000-a-month base salary, along with his pension, puts him in the
top 2 percent of Brazilians, who make more than $2,100 a month,
according to government statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the bums,'' announced Milton Peixoto, 64, a retired
bus driver, adding that there was no way he would vote for Cardoso.
``Last time I voted for him, but this time, he can go to hell. My
life's only gotten worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Real Plan tamed inflation but has done little to redress
Brazil's startling inequalities. According to the Brazilian
Institute of Applied Economic Research, the country's income
distribution is the most unequal in the world, with the richest 10
percent of the population collecting 50 percent of it. Nearly 70
percent of Brazil's voters have less than a primary school
education, and half of them are considered barely literate.
</P>
<P>
   But many Brazilians see Cardoso as the only candidate capable of
taking the country forward. For example Licinio Franco, a
representative for a check protection service here, confessed pride
at the figure that his President cuts overseas. A consummate
charmer, Cardoso speaks languages including French, English and
Spanish, and sometimes greets foreign visitors by offering their
choice of language.
</P>
<P>
   And Franco said he stood a bit taller upon hearing that a German
counterfeit gang was caught making 10- and 50-real bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they don't want to counterfeit the dollar, it's the
real,'' he said. ``Our money is worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosely de Faria Lemos, 50, who runs an advertising agency, said
she considered da Silva ``full of good intentions'' but
ill-prepared to run Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who's kind of from another era and space,'' she
said, ``who has no experience managing anything. He wasn't even
mayor. How can we give him the country to run? In one way or
another, Fernando Henrique can ease this crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
