<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOUBLE-LIFE-LADN     10-03 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUBLE-LIFE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDSOME HUNK HAD DARK SIDE AS HIT MAN, FBI AND POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Members of World Gym in suburban Woodland Hills
couldn't help but notice the movie-star-handsome hunk who greeted
them with an exotic accent and impeccable manners.
</P>
<P>
   A bodybuilder and part-time stuntman, Graham Miller embraced the
California dream fully after moving to the San Fernando Valley from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The dashing Afrikaner won a wide circle of friends and
acquaintances, built a thriving career in the fitness industry,
drove a 1990 BMW and married in Las Vegas in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Women swooned at his chiseled, 5-foot-11, 190-pound physique,
tawny hair and million-watt smile. Men admired his friendly nature
and calm confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But he was living a double life, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Last week FBI agents arrested the man known to friends as Graham
Miller outside the gym on charges that he kidnapped and murdered a
British businessman seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His real name, they announced, is Neville Vandermerwe, a
28-year-old who lived in a swirl of shifting identities while
haunted by the dark accusation from his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just shocked. I can't believe this is true,'' said Brian
Forster, a friend whose Told Partners realty company leases space
to World Gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a brother to me. He's basically like my best friend
over the last couple of years. He's outgoing, he's extremely
intelligent. Just fun to be around, very caring and helpful to
everyone that he's been in contact with.''
</P>
<P>
   Vandermerwe's attorney, Richard Crane, did not return repeated
phone calls. But his friends professed faith in his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my best friend, and I don't believe he's guilty,''
Forster said.
</P>
<P>
   Karla Shamis, 29, of suburban Chatsworth, who had trained with
Vandermerwe for six weeks this year, said she was floored by the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought of him as the perfect person who had no
problems, it seemed,'' Shamis said. ``He looked perfect, he had
lots of money, he had a perfect personality. He never lost his
temper.''
</P>
<P>
   As his friends and acquaintances struggle to understand how the
man they knew as the model of charm and civility could be linked to
such a gruesome crime, Vandermerwe is being held without bail in
the federal Metropolitan Detention Center downtown, awaiting
extradition hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office has 60 days from the date of his
arrest to prepare an extradition request on behalf of the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The international hunt for Vandermerwe began in April 1991,
after a British accountant named Simon Law disappeared from his
home in Kent County, England. Nothing but a dressing gown was
missing from his home.
</P>
<P>
   According to the arrest warrant prepared by the U.S. attorney in
cooperation with the Kent County constabulary, Law had been
involved in a bitter business dispute with a South African named
David Jenkins, who believed Law had ``ripped him off.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute was never resolved, and in mid-March, Law told a
friend, ``I wouldn't be surprised if he didn't send a couple of
blokes to sort me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Law was last heard from April 22.
</P>
<P>
   A red Vauxhall Astra automobile spotted at Law's home was traced
to Vandermerwe and another South African, Glen Chait, who had flown
to London about a week before. DNA tests showed blood encrusted on
its trunk proved an almost certain match to that of Law, whose body
was never found.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, a person calling himself Neville Uvan Der Merle
arrived in New York, the warrant states. Police said the birth date
and passport number of that man match Vandermerwe's.
</P>
<P>
   English police followed Vandermerwe to South Africa, but he was
already gone.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Willem Vandermerwe, told police his son returned
from England distraught and said: ``Someone has gone missing, and I
am going to get the blame for it and I've got no alibi,'' and ``I
will be traced here so easily, I have got to leave the country.''
</P>
<P>
   If Vandermerwe felt any such anxiety after moving to California,
he didn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never acted like a guy that was hiding anything, or was
living a double life,'' said Bill Geiger, editor of Muscle &AMP;
Fitness Magazine, who knew Vandermerwe through World Gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of self-assured about himself to maybe the point
of a little cocky. But probably deservedly, because he had a look
that could have been a model for a magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, however, Vandermerwe declined an offer to model for
Muscle &AMP; Fitness, which Geiger said is published throughout the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, hold a highly visible position at both World
Gym and the former Quest Gym in Woodland Hills. Geiger said
Vandermerwe also appeared on a fitness video.
</P>
<P>
   His role at the gym is unclear. Forster and other gym members
believed him to be general manager, and said he handled complaints
and other official business for the gym. Geiger said he thought him
part owner.
</P>
<P>
   But a World Gym official who declined to give his name said
Vandermerwe was merely a personal trainer. Thom Mrozek, a spokesman
for the U.S. Attorney's Office in Los Angeles, confirmed that
Vandermerwe did not appear to hold any official position at the
gym.
</P>
<P>
   As Vandermerwe built his new life in Los Angeles, he switched
his name often and for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Vandermerwe's 1990 BMW is registered to Manuel Boaventura,
according to the state Department of Motor Vehicles. His driver's
license is listed under the name Graham Manuel Miller, also known
as Manuel Fernando Boaventura.
</P>
<P>
   He married Christine A. Miller in Las Vegas in December under
the name Manuel Boaventura, the Clark County Marriage License
Bureau confirmed. Using a passport with his photo and that name, he
applied for resident alien status in January, the arrest warrant
states.
</P>
<P>
   While police records show his birth year to be 1970, his
driver's license and marriage certificate list it as 1966.
</P>
<P>
   With his new wife and another woman, Bernadette Miller,
Vandermerwe moved into a suburban Tarzana condominium in May under
the name Graham Boaventura, property manager Russell Beesley said.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, he traveled to the East Coast for a stunt
job, Shamis said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Even seven years after Law's disappearance, however, police in
England never abandoned the hunt for Vandermerwe.
</P>
<P>
   Kent County constables, who had searched for Vandermerwe in his
home country, learned this year that he might be in Los Angeles
near his brother, said Superintendent of Police George Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to this, we'd exhausted all other avenues to look for
Neville in South Africa, and we were inevitably drawn to the
conclusion that he may be in Los Angeles,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   They enlisted U.S. law enforcement to track Vandermerwe down. A
Los Angeles police officer sniffed him out at his brother's
Hollywood home Sept. 8 by feigning a flower delivery.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the U.S. attorney obtained a warrant for his
arrest. On Sept. 28 the FBI arrested him without incident at World
Gym.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing the next day, Forster said Vandermerwe was
characteristically calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed pretty confident and not to be worried, and in good
spirits,'' Forster said. ``When the judge asked him why he was
there, he didn't know why he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said the years that have gone by may have buttressed
Vandermerwe's own sense of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the passage of time may have altered people's
perception of him, and he may have ... talked himself out of it,''
Rogers said. ``As time goes on, he may have convinced himself he
was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
