</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-EXPANSION-OFFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION TEAMS MEAN INCREASED OFFENSE? A MYTH THAT DIDN'T
HAPPEN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The 1998 performances of Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa just got even better.
</P>
<P>
   No, they did not hit any more home runs; aren't 70 and 66 enough
for one season? But a study of baseball's offense this year reveals
how much better they really were than just about anyone else.
McGwire and Sosa shattered the previous home run barrier in a
season in which offense was stagnant, no matter how it is viewed,
no matter how it is dissected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how fantastic a season they had,'' said Florida
Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski.
</P>
<P>
   Previous expansion seasons had been marked by a significant
increase in offense. In 1969, for example, when the leagues each
added two teams, National League teams averaged 100 more runs than
the previous season, American League teams 110. Scoring rose by
1.25 runs a game in the NL, 1.37 in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when the NL added Florida and Colorado, the league's 14
teams scored an average of 100 more runs than they had the previous
season. But this year the league's 16 teams averaged 746 runs, the
same average its 14 teams had compiled in 1997. AL teams averaged
an additional 1.5 home runs over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion multiple, in fact, did not hold for any offensive
category. Increases were negligible, if not non-existent. The major
leagues averaged 2.08 home runs a game compared with 2.05 a year
ago (a 1.5 percent increase), scored an average of 9.58 runs
compared with 9.53 (half of 1 percent) and saw the batting average
slip half a point, from .2668 to .2662.
</P>
<P>
   Because home runs commanded everyone's attention this year, look
at what happened to them. The league that benefited most directly
from the McGwire-Sosa onslaught and had a third player, Greg
Vaughn, reach 50 home runs, had its home run ratio rise slightly,
1.91 a game to 1.98, but its runs per game dropped from 9.21 to
9.19.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 31 players in the majors hit 30 or more home runs;
this year that number rose by a mere two.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, who has been in baseball long enough to remember
even the earliest expansion, was among the many baseball people who
believed offense would rise with the growth to 30 teams. ``You'll
see offense go up because you won't have the talented pitching,''
the Cincinnati manager said in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, apprised of the statistics, McKeon was puzzled
and said: ``I have no idea why. I have no reason for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone. Other managers and general managers were
equally at a loss to explain the static offense.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella said he believed that expansion had something to do
with the performances of McGwire and Sosa but acknowledged that the
numbers do not ``bear out for the rest of the league and I don't
have an explanation for that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he struggled to come up with an explanation, it was clear
that Piniella was stumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an answer,'' he said. ``I wish I did. The
ball was lively. But it was just as lively for everybody else. The
two expansion teams basically didn't help the offense much. They
didn't hit very well. I do know that the good got better and the
average didn't get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella might have hit on something there. Atlanta general
manager John Schuerholz and Dombrowski of the Marlins echoed his
thought about good and average players, and the general idea
received support from another club executive who is an expert on
statistics and their interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the diminishment in pitching over all was more
beneficial to the very elite of offensive talent,'' said
Schuerholz, who had mistakenly thought that offense had improved
generally. ``I consider McGwire and Sosa in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   When the major league population rises, Dombrowski said, the
superior players ``have a chance to rise further above the rest.''
He added: ``A lot of the other people are equal so they don't show
significant difference. The top guys do more. If Tony Gwynn had
been Tony Gwynn and not hurt, he would have put up numbers that
would have been career highs.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Epstein, director of baseball operations for the San Diego
Padres, said he had not studied this year's statistics, but he had
intimate knowledge of previous expansion experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually what happens in expansion years,'' Epstein said, ``is
the standard deviation of performance gets bigger, between players
and between clubs. Even if the mean doesn't get bigger, the
deviation is bigger and the dispersion is greater. There is a wider
dispersion from the mean. This year expansion may have created more
extreme performances.''
</P>
<P>
   Performances at the high end, Epstein noted, are more readily
seen than those at the other end. ``You don't get to see the other
extreme,'' he said. ``If a player is that bad, he doesn't get to
play all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Basing an expected increase in offense on expansion, Epstein
noted, is a mistake. The increases in previous expansion years, he
said, could be attributed to other factors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, he said, the Los Angeles Angels played in
hitting-friendly Wrigley Field. In 1969, the mound had been lowered
and the strike zone shrunk. In 1993, a team played in mile-high
Denver for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff is going to affect hitting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
