<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ AND GARCIAPARRA: MORE RECORD POWER  
 SHAME IN SOUTH FLORIDA  
 LEYLAND TO DENVER, UNLESS ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More Record Power
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are the poor man's Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, but
Alex Rodriguez of Seattle and Nomar Garciaparra of Boston achieved
their own remarkable height of home runs. They are shortstops who
slammed a combined 77 home runs this season. Allow that total to
register: 77 home runs for a pair of shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   Compare their total with those of the top two home run-hitting
shortstops when Ernie Banks was, like they, an unusually powerful
shortstop. In 1955, when Banks hit 44 home runs, Johnny Logan was
second among shortstops with 13 for a total of 57. In 1958, Banks
hit 47 and the next highest was 17 by Darryl Spencer and Don Zimmer
for a top-two total of 64. The next year it was Banks with 45 and
Woodie Held with 29 for 74, and in 1960 Banks had 41 and Ron Hansen
22 for 63.
</P>
<P>
   Shame in South Florida
</P>
<P>
   With all of the positive elements of the season, baseball
nevertheless suffered a large black eye with the unprecedented
dismantling and deterioration of the World Series champion Florida
Marlins. It was an act officials should realize they should never
have allowed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins wound up with a worse record than the two expansion
teams, neither of which lost 100 games, as did the Marlins, whose
108 losses were the most ever for a team that won the World Series
the year before. Their total exceeded the previous low-water mark
for a defending champion (Cincinnati Reds, 1991) by a whopping 20
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as many members of the championship team wound up back in
the playoffs as finished the season with the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players remained with the emasculated Marlins while five
were on teams that reached the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou and Jay Powell are with Houston, Kevin Brown is with
San Diego and Felix Heredia is with the Chicago Cubs. Ed Vosberg is
with the Padres but has been on the disabled list all year.
</P>
<P>
   Others who came close to the playoffs were Robb Nen with San
Francisco and Al Leiter and Dennis Cook with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland to Denver, Unless . . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies hope to wrap up Jim Leyland as their new
manager this week as well as hire a vice president for player
personnel who eventually would replace Bob Gebhard as general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland, who left the Marlins last week, presumably would accept
the Rockies' job, at a salary of $1.5 million or more a season,
unless a more appealing vacancy develops first. That vacancy almost
certainly would have to be in Cleveland, an ideal location for
Leyland, who grew up in Ohio and lives in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But for Leyland to get that job, Mike Hargrove would have to be
fired, and the only way he most likely would be fired is if the
impatient Indians do not reach, or win, the World Series. Even then
the Indians might find it difficult to jettison a manager who led
them to the post-season for four consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, the Orioles continue to search for a general
manager but will retain Manager Ray Miller because he was the
choice of the owner, Peter Angelos, who was not satisfied with two
successive post-season appearances under Davey Johnson, who remains
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles will try to figure out what to do with the team that
had a record payroll and finished so far out of first its people
couldn't see the pinstripes on the Yankees' backs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
