<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HOPE TO MOVE RIVALRY WITH DOLPHINS INTO NEW PHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a Jets-Dolphins clash with fascinating elements that can
become part of their eclectic history: the mud bowl for the 1982
conference title, the faked spike that began a downward spiral for
the Jets, the almost-1,000-yard passing duel between Ken O'Brien
and Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a division game and because these are teams whose
franchises have been defined by glamour quarterbacks, Joe Namath
and Marino, their meetings are never ordinary. So, although
Sunay's 1 p.m. confrontation at the Meadowlands is merely Game 4
for both clubs, it has become a statement game for the Jets and a
testing of Super Bowl aspirations for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jets, this game is a chance to bring them up to .500
after an 0-2 start. If they win, their 2-2 mark will be better than
last year's similar start because the 1998 ledger would include a
pair of division victories.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dolphins? Well, this is Year 3 of the Jimmy Johnson
regime, and he has had success quickly wherever he has been _ at
the University of Miami, which captured a national title in 1987,
and in Dallas, where the Cowboys won Super Bowls in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   This matchup has all the earmarks of a statement game for the
Jets, even though coach Bill Parcells contends it's too early to
call it that.
</P>
<P>
   Statement games are the ones that tell whether a team is ready
for the next step. Usually, they also come at a point in the season
when fortunes can change dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the 1994 debacle with Miami that left the Jets'
franchise in ruins? Marino faking the spike, freezing the rookie
cornerback Aaron Glenn, then tossing the winning touchdown over his
head to Mark Ingram? Only eight Jets remain from that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even think of those days anymore,'' running back
Richie Anderson said. ``Look at Fred Baxter,'' he said, pointing to
the tight end. ``He's one of the guys who are left from '94, and
I'm sure he doesn't even remember those days. Johnson wasn't there
in '94 and Parcells wasn't there in '94.''
</P>
<P>
   But the facts remain: after that loss to Miami, the Jets went
into 4-33 slide that ended only when Parcells took over last year.
On the other hand, Marino hasn't lost to the Jets from that moment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a grid myth has evolved about the main
protagonists: Marino always beats the Jets. Like most myths, it
contains a kernel of truth preceded by a lot of baloney.
</P>
<P>
   During his glory years, when Marino reached (and lost) his only
Super Bowl, he and the Dolphins had their hands full with the Jets.
Entering the 1994 season, for example, Marino's won-lost record
over the Jets was merely 10-9. Since then, it has swelled to 17-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we different, are they different?'' linebacker Mo Lewis
asked. ``Sure, look at the teams. The Jets and Dolphins are two
different teams compared to 1994. They were a Dan Marino passing
team then. Now they've still got Marino, but it's a Jimmy Johnson
team. And we're a Bill Parcells-coached team now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Parcells' Giants played the Dolphins only once, and
lost. At New England, Parcells' Patriots were 4-4. The Jets lost
their two games against Miami last season, giving Parcells-coached
teams a 4-7 record against the Dolphins. Meanwhile, the
Johnson-coached Dolphins are 4-0 over the Jets. Including the
Cowboy years, his overall record against the Jets is 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Johnson is one coach Parcells respects. Parcells is
also wary of the talent Johnson has assembled on the Dolphins;
their conference-best defense; their quarterback who, Parcells
believes, can still throw better than most. He has asked his
players to deliver a peak performance for the second game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Just two Sundays ago, the Jets were 0-2. Although they were
facing a struggling Colts team, the Jets' season would have crashed
with a loss. Parcells whipped them through practice that week and
stressed not only the significance of a victory, but also the
position it would put them in for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   His intensity has worked on them this past week. The Jets'
workouts were so good, said the coach, that he had to cut back. He
didn't want to get them at a fever pitch too early. On Thursday, he
shortened practice.
</P>
<P>
   No, Parcells said, he wasn't concerned about motivating players
for two must games in a row. After all, these are the Dolphins they
are facing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation helps; the players understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Marino remains in control for the Dolphins, new Jets are
trying to start their own tradition. Quarterback Vinny Testaverde
gets a second straight start.
</P>
<P>
   And Keyshawn Johnson, the Jets' wide receiver, is trying to
create his own legend against Miami. In four games against them he
has snared 19 passes, with 2 touchdowns, for 263 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' cornerback Sam Madison, a second-year player, has
already made their matchup personal. Johnson, Madison said,
``thinks he's the world's best football player. He thinks he's
better than Jerry Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said: ``I don't even remember playing against him. I'm
shaking. I'm scared of Sam Madison.''
</P>
<P>
   The talking is louder and trashier these days. The intensity is
the same. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
