<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSIES-FUTURE _ WASHINGTON _ As we race into the next century
of faxes, e-mail and instant worldwide newscasting, America's
diplomatic system is still grounded in the horse-and-buggy era. The
terrorist bombings of two remote U.S. embassies in East Africa
offers a reminder that the United States has a visible and often
vulnerable presence in almost every nation, at a cost of more than
$2 billion a year. Many of these outposts date from the Cold War
era, when the United States was fighting a propaganda war for the
hearts and minds of even the tiniest nation. But is that necessary
now? After budget cuts, the U.S. State Department has made some
reductions, but U.S. domestic agencies have created more and more
overseas postings. Some experts, including government auditors, are
looking for ways to reshape the embassy system. Among the ideas:
setting up regional embassies to serve several countries, hiring
private contractors to gather information normally collected by
diplomats, and far greater use of high tech communications.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSIES-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ It has been several years and
millions of dollars in the making. But will the new U.S. embassy in
Rusia be the embassy of the future, or harken back to the old
Soviet Union days? (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSIES-DATA _ WASHINGTON _ Information for graphics with
comparative data on on the number of embassies and outposts,
diplomatic postings abroad and the cost per year. A list of of U.S.
domestic agencies and their overseas postings, according to a
recent GAO study. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
