<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 JEROME DEMPSEY, ACTOR, 69 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jerome Dempsey, an actor who worked in theater, film
and television, died on Aug. 26 at his home in New York. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   A versatile artist who took on a wide variety of roles, Dempsey
began his career in Toledo, Ohio, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to New York, he joined the Actors Studio and by the
1960s had won roles in ``The Deputy,'' ``Spofford'' and ``The
Love-Suicide at Schofield Barracks,'' among other plays.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Lincoln Center theater company under Jules
Irving, he appeared in ``A Cry of Players,'' ``King Lear'' and
``The Crucible.'' He also worked with the Yale Repertory Theater
under Robert Brustein's direction.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Dempsey played Dr. Van Helsing in ``Dracula'' opposite
Frank Langella in the title role, winning a Drama Desk award for
his performance. He also appeared in ``Trelawney of the Wells''
with Meryl Streep, Mandy Patinkin and John Lithgow, in ``The
Threepenny Opera'' with Raul Julia and in ``The Mystery of Edwin
Drood'' with Betty Buckley, Cleo Laine and George Rose.
</P>
<P>
   His film credits include ``Network,'' ``Brewster's Millions''
and ``Tune in Tomorrow.'' Television viewers saw him in productions
including ``Gore Vidal's Lincoln'' and ``The Kennedys of
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a sister, Joan Devers of Sylvania, Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
