<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVING SANDWICHES LEADS TO CREW TRYOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sarah Buckley, a college all-American in sailing, sought out the
world of America's Cup yacht racing in a most circuitous way. Her
entree into the sport meant making sandwiches for the America True
crew, handing out team water bottles to sailors and arranging
tables for a promotional party. But the payoff has been handsome, a
chance this weekend to try out for the group's America's Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth it even if I don't make the team,'' the 23-year-old
Buckley said about her self-paid trip to America True headquarters
in San Francisco. ``It's a fantastic thing to be around people who
really know how to do things well. I'm thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley is one of about 150 sailors who responded to a recent
public call for tryouts from Dawn Riley, a founder of the America
True yacht-racing syndicate. Of those, about 40 sailors _ 30 men
and 10 women _ were asked by the team to fly out to San Francisco
at their own expense. For Buckley, the trip from her home in Lake
Forest, Ill., is likely to cost as much as $700.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very high pressure deal,'' Riley said during a
telephone interview from San Francisco last week. ``You get
yourself out here, we'll be sailing with you for about four hours,
we'll interview you, and tell you to keep in touch. Then we'll send
you a letter when we make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The process is unique among America's Cup racing. Team members
are usually culled from the highest ranks of sailing. Crew members
are tapped at grand prix events internationally, and bidding wars
for the most elite sailors are common. But Riley sees value in
undervalued sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent pool has definitely diminished while at the same
time requirements for crew are exploding,'' she said. ``There is a
legitimate need out there to bring in new sailors.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire for fresh faces arises at a time when a record six
U.S. challenger teams are fishing from the same American pool of
experience. In most other cup years, the United States fielded only
defense teams, which drew two or three syndicates at the most.
</P>
<P>
   Riley gained her first foothold into America's Cup as the only
woman on Bill Koch's 1992 America3 team. She became involved again
in 1995 when the Koch group put out a public call for talent, and
received 650 resumes. In the end, 32 women were selected.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said that she has about three or four slots to fill, but
she may be looking again in the spring. Interested sailors can
inquire on the team's web site: www.americatrue.org.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for Winds of Autumn
</P>
<P>
   Autumn is prime time for setting new sailing records. Indeed, a
top team of French and New Zealand ocean racers has been waiting
all summer for the fresh winds of fall. Their sights are set on a
nine-day trans-Atlantic passage established last July 7 by
Christophe Auguin of France. But at 147 feet, the new team's yacht
is more than twice as big as Auguin's 60-foot sailboat, and far
more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million carbon fiber yacht, Mari-Cha III, is owned by
Robert Miller, an American entrepreneur who lives in England. It is
being made ready for its oceanic voyage at Chelsea Pier in New York
City. The traditional route for Atlantic Ocean record attempts
begins at Sandy Hook, N.J., and ends at the Lizard, a point of rock
off southwest England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stand by at Sandy Hook as soon as the weather begins
to look right,'' said Andre Luthy, first mate on Mari-Cha. ``At
this time of year, we shouldn't have to wait too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The current record, while unofficial because it wasn't properly
registered with the World Sailing Speed Record Council, stands at 9
days 22 hours 59 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Boat-Show Season Bows In
</P>
<P>
   Fall also ushers in the annual boat-show season for power and
sail. Among the new designs likely to appear at one or more of the
numerous shows both east and west are the F-28 series of family
cruising trimarans built by Corsair Marine; the Predator 3000
Walkaround, a new 30-foot fishing catamaran with twin
225-horsepower engines produced by Cobra Sportfishing Boats; and
the Sou'wester 61, a new aft-cockpit, pilothouse version of the
Hinckley Company's classic Sou'wester 59 sailing sloop.
</P>
<P>
   Coming exhibitions on the East Coast include the United States
Sailboat Show Oct. 9-12 in Annapolis, Md., and the Long Island
In-Water Boat Show this weekend and next at Tobay Beach Marina near
Jones Beach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
