<SLUG> BC-EVIDENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proof of conspiracy or just a hoax?
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two slips of paper are yellowing and brittle. They measure
3-by-4 inches. One is the ripped-out corner of a page from the 1963
Dallas telephone directory. The other has what look like dollar
amounts next to some words. Both appear to have the name ``Raul''
written on them.
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI agent Donald Wilson announced in March that he had
removed the papers from James Earl Ray's abandoned car in Atlanta
30 years ago and kept them secret. Last month, he turned the
potential evidence over to the Justice Department, which has
reopened a limited investigation into the 1968 Memphis slaying of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Federal investigators are examining
the papers to determine their authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The two slips of paper could be a significant development in the
assassinations of King and President Kennedy for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --This would be the first trace of the mysterious ``Raul.'' Ray,
who died in April while serving a 99-year sentence, recanted his
1969 guilty plea and insisted he had been set up by a smuggler he
knew only as ``Raul.'' Officials have maintained that Raul did not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   --The killings of King and Kennedy could be linked. A telephone
number at the top of one of the papers is the same as that of Jack
Ruby's Vegas Club. Ruby killed Lee Harvey Oswald, who was arrested
in Kennedy's assassination. Like Ray, Oswald claimed he had been
set up.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the papers fell out of Ray's 1965 white Ford Mustang
when he opened the passenger door, which was slightly jammed. The
papers were caught between the door and the frame and fell to the
ground. Thinking he had disturbed the crime scene, Wilson said he
panicked and stepped on the papers. He later put them in his pocket
when no one was looking.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he got home, Wilson said, that he realized what
he had found.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI discounted Wilson's account this year, calling it a
fabrication. FBI officials also said Wilson was not on record as
one of the agents assigned to retrieve Ray's car from a housing
project parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, then a rookie agent, counters that he was asked to tag
along by a senior agent whose name he can't recall. He did not turn
in the papers sooner, Wilson said, because he didn't think he could
trust the FBI, which he considered a racist organization. He quit
the bureau after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he believes Ray had a passenger on the trip from
Memphis to Atlanta and that the papers probably belonged to that
person.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials will not discuss the case or give a
timetable for when a report may be issued.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
