<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGES-COX     10-03 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devestating effects of Hurricane Georges linger
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSS POINT, Miss. _ For Billie Poole, the moment came when her
7-year-old grandson called from his flood-ruined home and told her,
``Grandma, I don't have a single toy left.''
</P>
<P>
   For her husband, Alex, it came as he watched 23 years of
memories being hauled out the front door. The new carpet had turned
fishy brown; the hardwood floor lay buckled and jumbled in the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suddenly realized that we're homeless,'' said Alex Poole,
56, whose brick home was filled by Hurricane Georges with three
feet of bayou water. ``We've got no place to stay of our own, and
that's a hard thought after living in a place for 23 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges, which slammed into the Gulf Coast last
Monday, hammering the area with rain, wind and floods, has long
since departed. But the effects remain _ visible not only in the
broken houses, ruined furniture and sand-covered roads, but in
lives that will never be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   From Mississippi to Florida, residents were measuring the
devastation, painting lines on garage posts and boathouse pilings
to show how high the waters had risen from the latest catastrophe
to roar ashore from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, the last storm to leave such an imprint was
Camille, which devastated the coast in 1969, killing hundreds. In
Alabama and Florida, the touchstones are Frederic in 1979, Opal in
1995 and Danny in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes are part of life for coastal residents. Some accept
them, file insurance claims, rebuild and go about their lives
again.
</P>
<P>
   But for others, like the Pooles, the toll starts to mount. They
weigh the costs, the work, the financial hardship. Against these
they balance the joy of living near the ocean, of owning a boat, of
seeing suntanned children grow up catching fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised our three boys here and now they've grown up and
moved away,'' Billie Poole said. ``I send them pictures telling
them, `Here's the place that was your playground growing up.' But
this is hard. Maybe it's God telling us it's time to think about
moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   The glittering casinos of Biloxi and Gulfport heard no such
message.
</P>
<P>
   The towns that withered in the 1950s and 1960s have blossomed in
the '90s as the Las Vegas of the Gulf Coast. The waterfronts gleam
with high-rise hotels and gaudy casinos that draw streams of eager
gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   The gamblers can rest easy.
</P>
<P>
   Georges made landfall just to the east. The Gulf Coast's
gambling mecca was already bustling again by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty miles to the east, in Pascagoula, Georges struck with the
full force of its 110-mph winds. Gusts were reported as high as 172
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Pascagoula's skyline is dotted not with casinos, but with
cranes, silos and smokestacks. Prosperity here comes from weekly
paychecks, not from tourists dropping thousands on slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say Georges doesn't compare to Camille, which killed
hundreds with winds that topped 150 mph. But what Georges lacked in
wind, it made up for with a 10-foot storm surge and more than 10
inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Williams knows exactly how high the water rose. An
attorney with a gorgeous home looking onto Mississippi Sound, his
home is 13.5 feet above the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the line of flotsam and debris that shows how high the
water came ... ,'' said Williams, pointing to what resembles a
bathtub ring around his home's foundation. ``We were very
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles to the east, in a community called Orange Grove, Ira
Bang wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Bang works at the Ingalls Shipyard, which dominates the
Pascagoula waterfront. He likes country living. Hunting dogs,
fishing boats and pick-ups with gun racks are as common here as
commuters are in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bang's mobile home lies down a rural road off U.S. 90 on the
banks of Bayou Cumbest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to get in there,'' he said late last week.
``I'm guessing it's all under water.''
</P>
<P>
   At a small cemetery a few miles from his home, floodwaters
opened dozens of graves. Caskets lay stranded like beached boats.
The grave of Bang's great-grandfather was untouched, but that was
small comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous about going back down to my house to see what's
left,'' he said. ``I've got $8,000 in insurance on my contents and
$8,000 on my structure, and that won't cover it if it's all ruined.
But we'll make it through.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of miles away, Gary and Darlene Tucker were less
optimistic. Their home is in a low-lying area, but it had never
flooded before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have flood insurance,'' said Darlene Tucker, as she
helped clean out her mother's nearby home, which also flooded.
``All my tables are upside down in my house and my couches are
floating. We've lived here 25 years and we never dreamed this could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's mother, Faye Floore, 67, has flood insurance on her
home, but her husband has none on the two rental homes and the
nearby catfish restaurant he owns. All were flooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to ever get back to where you were,'' Floore
said. ``Not at this age.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles east, where the Dog River cuts inland from Mobile
Bay, Rufus and Emily Williams also faced a life-changing crisis
just when they wanted to enjoy their golden years.
</P>
<P>
   Georges pushed three feet of water into their home. They put
downstairs stuff up on counters and shelves, but the water came
higher than they ever imagined as Georges blew the waters of Mobile
Bay inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here 32 years and this is the highest we've seen,
higher than Camille,'' said Rufus Williams, a retired maintenance
supervisor. ``I had the doors sand-bagged and I thought we wouldn't
have to worry. But when we got in here, everything inside the house
was just floating.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had just paid the premium on his flood insurance and
can rebuild. But the future is clouded with uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what will happen now,'' he said. ``I'm not sure I
can ever feel comfortable in this house again.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty miles to the south, a secluded gem called Dauphin Island
is home to miles of single-family cottages.
</P>
<P>
   Georges devastated the narrow spit, washing tons of sand over
roads and sweeping more than a dozen houses off their stilts. They
lay helter-skelter in the aftermath, smashed by waves that carried
them inland like toys in a bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert and Ulli Kastenhuber moved to the area to work for
DeGussa Chemical Corp., which is based in Hubert's native Germany
and has a plant in Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to live in a suburb,'' Hubert Kastenhuber said.
``We said to ourselves that once in our lifetime we have a chance
to live right on the beach, so let's take that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple had lived for more than a year in a neat, modern
cottage right on the Gulf. Last year Hurricane Danny shook them a
little, washing waves up near their house.
</P>
<P>
   Georges, however, picked the house up, washing it across the
road where it landed in a broken heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can serve you tea or coffee,'' Ulli Kastenhuber said,
opening a kitchen cabinet in which various glasses and foodstuffs
sat undisturbed. The rest of the house lay in ruins. The couple
picked through the debris, salvaging keepsakes and what furniture
they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even look over there,'' Ulli Kastenhuber said, nodding
toward the spot where the house once stood. ``I don't know if I
want to live on that same spot again. I'm too sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Mobile Bay in the resort towns of Gulf Shores and Orange
Beach, Ala., the damage fell far short of that on Dauphin Island.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit were beachfront structures. Dozens of oceanfront
condominiums and hotels were left with sagging decks, broken
seawalls and crumbled parking lots. At least one sprawling condo
complex, the Marlin Key, was undermined so badly it cracked and
fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   In Pensacola and Navarre Beaches, a few dozen miles to the east,
in Florida, a few homes had foundations washed out or roofs ripped
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opal left three feet of sand in this house, and it left all
our belongings scattered across the island,'' said Frank Winn, an
attorney who owns two beachfront homes. ``We lost one of the roofs
in this one, but it doesn't compare. I was afraid we'd see the same
thing this time, but I was pleasantly surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Winn said he won't move, even though he's been hit three times
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't get my wife off this beach with a stick of
dynamite,'' he said. ``She loves it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
