u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-COX     10-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Countdown to liftoff begins for Glenn
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Columbus two weeks ago, the football frenzy that
envelopes fall Saturdays at Ohio State University broke momentarily
to let rabid Buckeyes unleash their appreciation for one of Ohio's
favorite sons (who is not an OSU alumnus).
</P>
<P>
   The marching band spelled out G-L-E-N-N across the field as Sen.
John Glenn and his wife, Annie, strode out. ``You had a standing
ovation by 90,000 people, that's pretty moving,'' Glenn said.
``That was heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, it's all heavy for Glenn: the emotion of leaving
behind 24 years in the U.S. Senate, the stream of requests for
appearances and autographs, and the thickening astronaut training
schedule that dictates how much time he spends on the other two.
</P>
<P>
   This week begins the last long training push toward liftoff,
with Glenn going to the Kennedy Space Center in Cape Canaveral,
Fla., for a series of launch-site training sessions that include a
countdown test in which the crew members for the space shuttle
Discovery will practice their launch day routine, right down to
strapping into their shuttle seats. The launch is set for Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The training for Glenn, a temporary astronaut assigned for
specific scientific study and the lowest-ranking crew member, began
last February. He has split his time between space work and his
Senate duties, but steadily through the year the requirements for
NASA training have taken more and more of his days.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, Glenn, 77, has spent more than 60 percent of his
time working at the Johnson Space Center in Houston on
crew-coordination skills and other shuttle requirements. And the
percentage has kept climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general terms, beginning Oct. 1 the crew dedicates 100
percent of their time to mission preparation,'' said Steve
Williams, who heads this flight's training program at Johnson Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The previous training focus on habitability in the shuttle,
wearing the launch suit and introductory science has given way to
the integration of those things into the cooperative duties of the
rest of the crew. In recent months they've spent time perfecting
crew coordination during such things as converting the shuttle's
interior into a laboratory, which begins moments after orbit is
achieved, and then stowing the science equipment for return to
earth, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   They also have begun training in high fidelity simulators that
use a wealth of computers to recreate every experience of being on
the shuttle, with the significant exception of weightlessness. Even
the windows are filled with monitors that display moving space and
earth scenes that are precisely what the astronauts will see.
</P>
<P>
   During those sessions, astronauts in the simulator communicate
with the same ground control that will work with them during the
flight. Using computers, the support team can create malfunctions
and other unscheduled problems to sharpen the crew's readiness.
</P>
<P>
   For Glenn's flight, the crew's longest stint in the simulators
was Sept. 16 when they spent 16 hours sealed inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew goes into the simulator, and they're there for the
duration,'' Williams said. ``Not only are they practicing the big
events like a (satellite) rendezvous, but they're also going
through timeline activities which includes normal meal times and
things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, following the lengthy simulator run, the crew goes in for
a debriefing to discuss the training session. Even with time
programmed for sleep inside the simulator, those days get long.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn, the geriatric astronaut, said neither long simulator
days nor physically challenging emergency exit procedures have
dulled his enthusiasm or made him doubt his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of our training so far, I think there hasn't been a
single time, in any of our egress training and things like that,
there hasn't been a single time that I haven't been able to perform
just like everybody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then he added: ``The one area that I realize I'm not as
young as I used to be, and that is I wish I'd started flexibility
training about 20 years ago ... I found where some of the people
there are going through a hatch, for instance, bend over and go
through a hatch more easily than I do ... but I do it on my hands
and knees. And that's fine. It doesn't hold anybody else up.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, too, said Glenn is keeping pace, adding that although
the next four weeks will be busy, the essentials of preparing Glenn
to return to space has been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, from where we are... we're fine-tuning. The crew is
trained. They're ready to go. The senator is ready to go,''
Williams said. ``As a matter of fact, if for some reason they had
to launch tomorrow I think everybody would feel very comfortable
with their capabilities and the fact that they're trained.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
