<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981003.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOWALSKI-COX     10-03 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOWALSKI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reopening the King assassination case
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's casual Friday at the Justice Department, and
Barry Kowalski is wearing a white cotton shirt, patterned tie, blue
jeans and cowboy boots. As he walks to his office, it becomes
obvious he's somewhat bowlegged. It's fitting for this former
Marine who fancies himself a cowboy. Not just a horse lover, he
truly believes in honor and the code of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Although he refuses to talk about the case, the lead
investigator for the Justice Department's recently reopened probe
into the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. says he's
not cowed by this latest high-profile assignment. As the federal
prosecutor given the job of winning convictions in 1993 against
four Los Angeles police officers accused of denying Rodney King his
civil rights, Kowalski is used to performing under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot less daunting than whether a city is going to
burn again,'' he said. ``If we had lost, there would have been
another riot. It made you need to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He won. Although two officers were acquitted, the other two were
sentenced to 30 months in prison. Los Angeles didn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faces a different challenge. In August, Attorney General
Janet Reno opened a limited investigation into the Rev. King's
death and made it a civil rights issue by putting Kowalski in
charge. He is a special counsel for the criminal section of the
Justice Department's civil rights division.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Reno asked Kowalski to investigate two
developments: a 1993 allegation by former Memphis restaurant owner
Loyd Jowers that a mobster paid him $100,000 to hire a hit man to
kill King, and the recent claim by ex-FBI agent Donald Wilson that
he took two pieces of paper with the name ``Raul'' on them from
James Earl Ray's abandoned car 30 years ago in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who died in April while serving a 99-year-sentence,
recanted his admission of guilt within days of making it in 1969
and claimed that he had been set up by a smuggler he only knew as
Raul.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jowers' attorney said no federal officials had
contacted him or his client recently, Wilson relinquished the
documents to Kowalski's lieutenants 2 1/2 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reopened the case at the urging of King's family, who last
year announced their belief in Ray's innocence. They tried in vain
to obtain a trial for him.
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski, who turned 54 on the day Reno announced the
investigation, has prosecuted some of the most prominent racial
violence cases in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of joining the Justice Department in 1981,
Kowalski won convictions against two Ku Klux Klan members who had
abducted and hanged Michael Donald in Mobile, Ala. The next year,
Kowalski suffered his only major defeat when he failed to convict
an avowed white racist who had been charged in the 1980 wounding of
Vernon Jordan, then head of the Urban League, in Fort Wayne, Ind.
(The man now admits to the shooting.)
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski ``was very vigorous in his effort, and he was obviously
very bright,'' said defense attorney J. Frank Kimbrough, who faced
him in that trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski was back on the winning side in 1988 after securing the
convictions of two neo-Nazis in the 1984 machine-gun murder of
Denver talk show host Alan Berg. The next year, he helped to
convict 23 Dallas skinheads who had been harassing
African-Americans and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's God's work,'' Kowalski said of his fight against hate
crimes. ``God made somebody a certain color, a certain way. God
didn't intend for that person to suffer because of that. When
someone gets hurt because of that, that is one of the most heinous
crimes. It's despicable. And when someone has power by virtue of
the authority the state has granted to him and someone gets hurt,
that's the second-worst thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning at all costs?
</P>
<P>
   But some attorneys who have battled Kowalski say he can get
carried away. Harland Braun defended Los Angeles police Officer
Theodore Briseno, who was acquitted in the Rodney King case. Braun
objected to Kowalski's closing argument, saying he unduly pressured
the jury by telling them the world was watching to see how they
would act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kowalski crossed over the line and attempted to use race in a
very dangerous and incendiary way,'' Braun said. ``I thought he was
unethical. Just because he's wearing the white hat in most of these
cases, it doesn't mean the end justifies the means.''
</P>
<P>
   Kowalski was ``trying to inflame passions,'' said Ira Salzman,
attorney for another of the Los Angeles police officers. Salzman
said Kowalski and his team had a ``win-at-any-cost attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They may well be right,'' Kowalski said. ``I made mistakes
during the trial, but I always did everything I could to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   To Kowalski, that zeal comes from a sense of morality he has
held since his youth in the Virginia suburbs of Washington. The son
of a West Point graduate and two-term Democratic congressman,
Kowalski remembers going to an all-black nightclub in the early
1960s to watch Otis Redding and James Brown perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently,'' he said, ``we'd be the only white guys there.
But we'd be welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   After an undistinguished academic career at Brown University, he
went to work in 1966 as a junior political aide in the office of
Vice President Hubert Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1967, he had joined the Marine Corps, even though he
was opposed to the escalating war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined up because I thought it was unfair that poor guys had
to go but rich guys didn't,'' he said, seated in his cramped
fifth-floor office, a Marine Corps recruitment poster tacked to the
wall. ``I didn't want to go to school. I was sick of school. I had
political ambitions, and I thought I would be better situated to
fight against the war as a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   He served a year in Vietnam, as a lieutenant with an infantry
platoon, an executive officer with a rifle company and an adviser
to a South Vietnamese army pacification program.
</P>
<P>
   Out of his officers' school class, he was told, about
one-thirdfinished their tours unharmed, one-third were killed and
another third were wounded seriously enough to be shipped home
early. He was in the fortunate third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shot at almost every day,'' he said. ``I never fired
my weapon. As a platoon leader, you're not supposed to. I didn't
want to kill anybody. I didn't want to take a life if I didn't have
to. By the same token, I wouldn't have hesitated to shoot someone
trying to kill me. I was not beyond pulling the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   He still thinks about the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I gave orders that caused someone to die,'' he said.
``What weighs on me more are the mistakes I made that caused my men
to die. That still bothers me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon discharge in 1970, Kowalski went to the Catholic University
Law School in Washington, where he made law review. While still in
school, he got a job with the Interior Department's Office of
Endangered Species. He also worked on George McGovern's failed 1972
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion at that point became the environment and
wildlife,'' he said. ``I was disinterested in politics. I became
cynical. With what I saw in the war, what I learned from my dad and
from working on the McGovern campaign, I decided politics wasn't
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense is not for him
</P>
<P>
   After graduation in 1973, he joined a Washington firm that
spcialized in antitrust law. The job bored him, and he lasted six
months. Then came a nine-month stint as a Washington prosecutor
working with juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he joined the faculty at Antioch School of Law. He held
that job until he joined the Justice Department in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter was getting ready for college,'' he said. ``The
school looked like it was going under. I'm probably the only guy
who came to the government for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a one-year break when he taught law in Wyoming, he's
been working civil rights cases with the Justice Department.
``Things that need vindication are very challenging,'' Kowalski
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has not considered work as a defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to represent someone who's guilty for money,''
he said. ``I'd represent someone who is indigent and can't afford
an attorney. There's a lot of difficulty ethically being a defense
attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe himself, he says he's ``someone who wants to
be a champion for a cause. At the same time, I'm constantly worried
about not having accomplished my job well enough. I'm a worrier.''
</P>
<P>
   A hyperkinetic and slight man, he constantly tears off a piece
of tape from a dispenser on his desk and plays with it as he talks.
Yet he claims to have slowed down in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate pressure,'' he said. ``I accept it as part of what
comes with the job. But it makes me worried. It makes me run
scared. I always run scared. It's useful to have that feeling, but
it doesn't feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   If not a change of pace, these last few years have brought him a
better quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced after graduating from law school, Kowalski only
remarried four years ago. He not only has two young grandchildren,
thanks to his 30-year-old daughter, but also a 2-year-old daughter
from his current marriage. He takes her riding on Moon, his
15-year-old paint horse he keeps at a friend's Virginia farm.
</P>
<P>
   Horses have been a part of Kowalski's life for years. He even
rode Moon to the outdoor altar on his wedding day. His wedding
photograph shows him in a black cowboy outfit that makes him look
like Robert Duvall in ``Lonesome Dove.'' The resemblance was not by
chance, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a work schedule that often has him on the road, he
doesn't miss his bachelor days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have to call home every day than be alone for the
dry spells, especially since my wife's an angel and tolerates all
my bad habits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But domestic tranquillity hasn't made him soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who accomplish things in life have to believe that what
they're doing is the most important thing in the world,'' Kowalski
said. ``I get obsessed with a case when I'm working on it. This is
the only thing I'm working on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
