</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This time, La Nina spells trouble
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as Hurricane Georges faded last week, weather experts
suggested that more bad news may be on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   A weather phenomenon known as La Nina _ the reversal of El Nino
_ is developing and could create conditions favorable for frequent
and dangerous Caribbean hurricanes like Georges, say environmental
officials with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Georges is a typical storm for this time of year,''
said Peter Usher, chief of the U.N. Environmental Program's
atmosphere unit. ``But La Nina is now developing, and an important
feature is that it often enhances normal seasonal weather events,
and this is what could be happening in the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   La Nina, a ``cold water event,'' occurs as a result of the
direct reversal of conditions that lead to the more widely known El
Nino, which is caused by abnormal warming in the central and
eastern equatorial stretch of the Pacific. La Nina, which is
Spanish for ``little girl,'' is the result of a below-normal drop
in Pacific temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Climate scientists met in Boulder, Colo., in July for the first
conference ever on La Nina.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the results of the conference last week, Usher said
that if La Nina ``develops how we think it might, then the concern
is that the frequency of storms like Georges might increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Massive flooding spawned by Georges along the Gulf Coast may be
part of a pattern around the world attributed to La Nina. In recent
months, Usher said, many countries, such as China and Bangladesh,
have experienced torrential rainfall that meteorologists blame on
La Nina.
</P>
<P>
   Usher also noted that last week the board of directors of the
United Nations Foundation, the charity established by Ted Turner,
approved $650,000 for a project to reduce the impact of
environmental emergencies by focusing on early warning and
preparedness efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In another development related to Georges, National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration officials said the agency sent its three
hurricane tracking aircraft into the eye of Georges while it
hovered over Cuba. It was a rare move because hurricane aircraft
almost never fly over land, where the storms can spawn tornadoes.
They usually fly through hurricanes over the open sea.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center near Miami requested that the
aircraft fly into Cuban airspace so the storm's exact position
could be determined. Forecasters must know the location of the eye
of the storm so they can accurately predict the hurricane's track.
NOAA is the only federal agency with hurricane tracking capability
that Cuba has authorized to fly in its airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
