<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to Spell Mess  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven National Football League teams finished September without
a victory, the most there have been at the four-week juncture at
any time in the 1990s. One of the seven teams is Philadelphia,
whose situation with running back Charlie Garner is one of the most
awkward in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Garner has asked for a trade. Several teams have been interested
in him, especially Kansas City. During the off season, Garner
signed a four-year, $6.4 million contract, but because of an
injured ankle he has been mainly a backup. He refuses to speak to
reporters, and one Eagle said he barely speaks to teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Garner is said to want out. So, probably, does coach Ray Rhodes,
who is miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Dogfight of the Month
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks-Steelers game in Pittsburgh last week was one of
the most physical and emotional of the season so far. The Seattle
running back Ricky Watters said he was punched, bitten and kicked
almost every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, after an exchange with the Steelers
defensive lineman Kevin Henry, Watters threw a right hook to
Henry's head. The officials did not see it, or Watters would have
been automatically kicked out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown, who felt heat on
and off the field. Brown was one of the best-liked Steelers when he
played linebacker for them for four years. In February 1997,
however, he signed a six-year, $24 million contract and instantly
became hated by Pittsburgh fans.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Brown made a play _ and he made a lot, with 14
tackles and a sack _ he was heavily booed. After the game, Brown,
one of the frankest and most talkative of players in the league,
voiced his opinions about Steelers players, fans and the intensity
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   On what fans said to him as he walked off the field after the
game: ``For the most part, when I came off, fans were cool,'' he
said, though some were obscene. ``How does love turn to hate? You
loved me two years ago, and you hate me now? Does your $45 obligate
you to cuss at me? If you saw me walking down the street, I'd
basically beat your behind if you cussed at me, so I don't want to
hear that garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   On his former teammate Jerome Bettis, who does a dance after a
big run: ``Bettis is going to talk. He's going to do his little
dance. The first time he tried to do it this game, I hugged him and
pushed him back to the huddle. I don't want to see that. He got a
5-yard run. Hey, you're 250 pounds, you're supposed to get a 5-yard
run.''
</P>
<P>
   On another former teammate, tight end Mark Bruener: ``He holds a
lot. You know, that's his blocking style. I give him credit. It
works. So I threw him down. He tried to kick me because he thought
I was going to try and kick him in his face. No way. I wasn't going
to get kicked out of the game. But at the same time, I don't play
that garbage. No matter what it is, I don't take it.''
</P>
<P>
   He Knows His Place
</P>
<P>
   Now that Denver's backup quarterback, Bubby Brister, is 2-0
replacing the injured John Elway (strained right hamstring), is
there a quarterback controversy? ``Hey, this is John Elway's
team,'' Brister said. ``It always has been, and it always will
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
