<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CUSTODY-COMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY IMMIGRANT HAD STROKE IN CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The family of a 53-year-old Haitian man who underwent
emergency surgery hours after being taken into police custody is
asking for an investigation to determine whether he had been beaten
by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Ulrick Charles remained in critical but stable condition
Saturday at Brooklyn Hospital Center, where he was admitted on
Sept. 24. His son, Jean Robert Charles, said at a news conference
Saturday that his father was in a coma. He said his father had been
``in perfect health'' before he was taken into police custody.
</P>
<P>
   The son and two lawyers representing the family could provide no
direct evidence of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Police Commissioner Marilyn Mode on Saturday reiterated
an earlier police statement that Charles' arrest and his condition
were not related. ``The man had a stroke,'' Ms. Mode said. ``He
apparently collapsed and was in some sort of seizure.''
</P>
<P>
   A police statement about the incident said the hospital's
emergency-room physician told investigators that Charles had
extremely high blood pressure and suffered a stroke when a blood
clot formed on his brain. Surgery was necessary to relieve the
pressure on the brain caused by the clot, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Sept. 24, Charles surrendered to officers at
the Brooklyn South Task Force on a warrant that his lawyers said
had been issued for his failure to display a city license in his
automobile shop.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours later, the lawyers said, Charles' family
received a telephone call from hospital officials, informing them
that Charles had undergone surgery to remove a blood clot on his
brain. When relatives arrived at the hospital after the surgery,
the lawyers said, they found Charles unconscious and handcuffed to
a hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was put into police custody perfectly healthy and within 20
minutes he was completely unconscious and needing medical
attention,'' said Eric Poulos, one of the family's lawyers. Michael
Ratner, of the Center for Constitutional Rights, is also
representing the family.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Charles' son questioned whether undue
police force contributed to his father's condition. He said there
were bruises on his father's face. He said his brother, Jean Ulrick
Charles Jr., overheard a police officer telling an emergency-room
worker that the police had used force while handcuffing their
father at the Brooklyn South station house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to indicate that,'' Ms. Mode said. She said the
police were investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of police brutality is particularly sensitive among
Haitian immigrants. On Friday night, the Charles family received
support at Brooklyn Hospital Center from Abner Louima, the Haitian
immigrant who has accused officers in the 70th Precinct of
torturing him last year.
</P>
<P>
   Poulos and Ratner said police officers visited Charles' Brooklyn
automobile-repair shop a few months ago. After the officers
inspected the shop, the lawyers said, they issued a summons for
failing to display the original copy of a city license required to
operate a compressor.
</P>
<P>
   Poulos and Ratner said that Charles did have a license and that
a photocopy of it hung in his shop. They said his son had offered
to run home from the shop and bring back the original, an offer
rejected by the police officers. In the following weeks, the
lawyers said, Charles twice appeared in court, but the case was
postponed both times at the request of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Poulos said Charles apparently missed a third court date, which
caused Brooklyn Criminal Court to issue a bench warrant. When
Charles received the warrant last week, he called the Brooklyn
South station house and arranged to appear on the morning of Sept.
24, Ratner said. Charles arrived with Jean Ulrick Charles Jr. and
was informed that he would need to clear up the matter in court.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Charles was taken to Criminal Court at 9:40
a.m., where he suffered a seizure. On Sept. 25, a letter addressed
to the precinct commanding officer stated that the warrant against
Charles had been vacated because the case had been dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
