<SLUG> BC-FBO-HIGH-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULLBACK WHO STOPS FOR NO ONE, EVEN TEAMMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By GRANT GLICKSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andrew Pinnock, an all-America fullback, says that he
truly cares about his Bloomfield (Conn.) high school teammates. He
just has a funny way of showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to run people over in practice,'' he said. ``I feel
that in order to get everybody pumped up, I need to start off with
a big pop.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is a pop when Pinnock, a 6-foot, 250-pounder, decides to
lower his shoulder and barrel over a defender. After each hit,
those capable of gaining their feet usually plead with him to stop.
But Pinnock, who doubles as a defensive end, refuses to relent. ``I
like my teammates,'' he said, ``but I like the intensity of
practice. It is important that we get ready for our games.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, Bloomfield, the defending Class S
champion, has prepared for its games as well as any team in the
state. The Warhawks has reached five straight state title games,
and last season's 12-0 team boasted Connecticut's top-ranked
offense, scoring 552 points, including 70 points on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomfield (2-0), which took on Avon-Old Farms (1-1) Saturday,
is the favorite to capture the Class S title again this season.
Pinnock is joined by three other Division I prospects: Kevin Moore,
an offensive and defensive back; Daemeon Grier, a 300-pound
defensive lineman; and Darrell Shabazz, a speedy outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a great work ethic,'' said Jack Cochran, who has
compiled a 55-8-2 record since becoming Bloomfield's coach in 1992.
``These kids are hungry and their goal is to be No. 1 in the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cochran, Pinnock could be the team's model for work
ethic, on the field and off. Pinnock has taken great pride in
overcoming a learning disability. And while football has always
come naturally for Pinnock _ he is a powerful runner who has run
the 40-yard dash in 4.59 seconds _ he can usually be found one hour
after practice running through his own regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pinnock joined the track team to work on his speed.
In an effort to help build his body, as a junior he also
participated in a state weight-lifting competition. Bloomfield won
the competition, largely because Pinnock placed first in squats
(550) and second in bench pressing (375) and power clean-and-jerk
(268).
</P>
<P>
   In the classroom, Pinnock's work has been even more determined.
In his sophomore year, Pinnock showed that he no longer belonged in
a special education program. He now takes modified mainstream
courses, and he should have no trouble qualifying for a scholarship
under National Collegiate Athletic Association rules. Kentucky,
Michigan, North Carolina State, Penn State, Tennessee and Syracuse
have all shown interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   Pinnock, one of two children, has held a job _ ranging from
social work for the Northwest Boys and Girls Club to data entry
with Phoenix Home Life, where his mother, Patricia, worked _ since
he was of legal age. He has followed his mother's lead: Patricia
Pinnock has worked double shifts since her children's father
abandoned them when Andrew was in kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid is a great success story,'' Cochran said. ``He
deserves all the recognition that he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinnock, with 5,470 yards rushing and 60 touchdowns, is closing
in on state career records in both. Rashon Spikes, now with North
Carolina State, scored 77 touchdowns for Maloney High from 1992 to
1995, and Kyle McIntosh, now with Syracuse, holds the Connecticut
rushing record with 7,400 yards at Cheshire High from 1991-94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my coach at the beginning of the year that I wasn't
going to put pressure on myself to break those records,'' Pinnock
said. ``That I was going to go out and play hard and let the
records take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only concern that I have now,'' he continued, ``is leading
this team back to a championship and taking care of business in
school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
