<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX     10-03 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers scouting their future
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell was relating a phone
conversation he just had with team scout John Gill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's up in Moose Jaw today,'' Waddell said. ``He's going to go
watch Kootenay play tonight. But he's staying in Prince Albert.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Albert?
</P>
<P>
   ``To give you a reference point, it's about two hours north of
Saskatoon.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say if Gill would be departing on the noon balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League has not returned to Atlanta quite
yet. The extent of the Thrashers' participation this season will be
preparing scouting reports on amateur players from Moose Jaw,
Prince Albert and other remote Canadian outposts, and evaluating
lesser NHL players in more accessible cities. It is from those
talent pools that Waddell and his scouting staff will stock the
Thrashers' first roster in expansion and entry drafts next June.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell will meet with his staff this week to share his
philosophy on scouting. ``I'm not impressed with guys who tell me
they know 1,000 players,'' he said. ``We all know 1,000 players.
I'd rather know a lot about fewer players than a little about a lot
of players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I send somebody to scout the Red Wings, I don't need him to
come back with scouting reports on Steve Yzerman and Niklas
Lidstrom. We need to focus on the bottom half of rosters. If you go
to a game and focus on 10 players on each team, you can pick up on
tendencies a lot easier than if you're trying to watch every guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, assistant general manager Les Jackson, NHL scout Murray
Oliver and two part-time scouts will concentrate mostly on NHL
games, with plans to see about 400 this season. Waddell himself
expects to attend 125 games.
</P>
<P>
   Nine other full- and part-timers will focus on Canadian
amateurs, U.S. collegians and Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   With Atlanta's rookie draft picks likely spending at least a
year in the minor leagues, the team's roster for the 1999-2000
season mostly will be made up of third- and fourth-line veterans
from existing teams. In the expansion draft, each team can protect
15 players (one goalie, five defensemen and nine forwards) or 12
(two goalies, three defensemen, seven forwards) on its 24-man
roster. First- and second-year players are excluded.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will take special interest in how Washington,
Florida, Carolina and Tampa Bay fare in the newly formed Southeast
Division, Atlanta's future home. For now, it appears the weakest of
the six divisions. ``I'd like to know going in if it's going to be
a black-and-blue division or a highly skilled division,'' Waddell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the expansion Nashville Predators also will be of
interest to Waddell. The Predators traded several expansion draft
picks for future amateur picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really building for four, five years out,'' he said.
``We want to be competitive right away. I'm sure they do, too, but
I don't know if we could (have the same philosophy).''
</P>
<P>
   And, no, Waddell won't hire a coach soon. He said about a dozen
qualified candidates have contacted him _ as well as 20 others _
but added, ``I won't even start dealing with it until after
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   There are too many games to see.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
