<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Predictions for Eastern Confrence hockey
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREDICTED FINISH
</P>
<P>
   Northeast
</P>
<P>
   1. Boston
</P>
<P>
   2. Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   3. Montreal
</P>
<P>
   4. Toronto
</P>
<P>
   5. Ottawa
</P>
<P>
   Southeast
</P>
<P>
   1. Washington
</P>
<P>
   2. Florida
</P>
<P>
   3. Carolina
</P>
<P>
   4. Tampa Bay
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic
</P>
<P>
   1. Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   2. New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   3. Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   4. N.Y. Rangers
</P>
<P>
   5. N.Y. Islanders
</P>
<P>
   THREE FOR THE CUP
</P>
<P>
   1. Philadelphia: An upgrade in goal (John Vanbiesbrouck) and a
motivated Eric Lindros (playing for a long-term contract) might be
just the thing to push the talented Flyers over the top _ if coach
Roger Nielson doesn't get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   2. Buffalo: The Sabres failed to adequately improve their
offense. But coach Lindy Ruff has been able to squeeze the most out
of his players, and goalie Dominik Hasek has carried teams before.
Just ask the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   3. New Jersey: Players say they enjoy the looser atmosphere with
Jacques Lemaire gone. The question is whether new coach Robbie
Ftorek can match his success. Having Martin Brodeur and Bobby Holik
helps.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE HUNT
</P>
<P>
   1. Washington: The Capitals overachieved to reach the finals. To
take the next step, they need to come up with another scorer than
Peter Bondra (52 goals) and hope goalie Olaf Kolzig's 1997-98
season (2.20 goals-against average) wasn't a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   2. Boston: Pat Burns is one of the league's best coaches. The
Bruins have young talented forwards in Jason Allison, Sergei
Samsonov and Joe Thornton. And Byron Dafoe has solidified the
goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK OUT BELOW
</P>
<P>
   1. Pittsburgh: The retired Mario Lemieux cannot collect deferred
salary. Team ownership and finances are a mess. Center Ron Francis
signed with Carolina as a free agent. Petr Nedved, who sat out last
season with contract problems, is threatening to do it again unless
traded. Defenseman Darius Kasparaitis could be lost for the season
with a torn knee ligament. And Jaromir Jagr may not be able to hold
the pieces together.
</P>
<P>
   2. N.Y. Islanders: GM-coach Mike Milbury inquired about the
Thrashers GM job, that's how much he wanted to stay. Last year's 30
wins may look good by the end of the year to the cash-strapped,
goal-starved team.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Well-traveled goalie Sean Burke, on signing with Florida, which
lost Vanbiesbrouck and failed to land Mike Richter or Felix Potvin
as a replacement: ``I look at the situation and see Florida as a
team that underachieved last year, and I personally underachieved
and maybe that's a good situation.'' Huh? ... Potvin has been at
the center of more trade rumors than any other player since Toronto
signed Curtis Joseph as its starter. ... Most creative offseason
maneuver goes to the Islanders' legal counsel, which claimed the
team was ``constructively evicted'' from ``uninhabitable'' Nassau
Coliseum. After moving training camp to Lake Placid for 17 days,
county officials obtained a restraining order, temporarily tying
the team to the aforementioned slum. ... The early massive
rationalization award goes to new Florida coach Terry Murray, who
was hired by his brother, GM Bryan Murray: ``Coaches and GMs are
tied together no matter what the relationship is, whether it's a
brother relationship or not.'' ... If commissioner Gary Bettman
wants the league to go global, here's his poster child: Devils
rookie center Scott Gomez was born in Anchorage, Alaska, to parents
of Mexican and Colombian descent and is the first Hispanic to go in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
