<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-ADVANCE-COX     10-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out with the old ...
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As players grumble about messing with tradition and coaches
whine about their clutch-and-mug defensive systems being
sterilized, NHL commissioner Gary Bettman focuses on something he
deems far more important: The red light behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman wants to see it flash more often, signalling a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses have gone over the edge,'' Bettman said. ``We had to
do something to not only stop the trend but go in the other
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL heads into the season, which opens Friday, seemingly
going in different directions at once. Fan base remains strong,
four expansion franchises have committed a combined $320 million in
signup fees and a new five-year, $600 million television contract
with Disney is in place _ assuring that every player in some way,
shape or form is a Mighty Duck.
</P>
<P>
   However, the league also saw its already anemic TV ratings slip
last season, salaries have skyrocketed to where they are outpacing
revenues and up to 20 of 26 teams claim to have lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman, however, views things through a rose-colored goalie's
mask. He believes things will work themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing perceptions of declining interest, the commissioner
and his lieutentants concluded the problems center on goal scoring.
Or lack thereof. Last year's average of 5.3 goals per game was down
a full goal from two years earlier, three goals from a high of 8.3
in 1981-82, and represented the lowest output since a 5.1 average
in 1955-56.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is a redesigned playing surface and new rules. The
goal lines have been moved from 11 to 13 feet from the end boards,
creating more space behind the nets for skating and playmaking. The
goal crease was shrunk, creating more freedom in front and
potentially cutting down on goals that had been disallowed for
being in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   New restrictions on a goaltender's equipment also will be
enforced to prevent them from getting an edge. Example: an
oversized jersey that hangs below the armpits and assists in a
save.
</P>
<P>
   And the league is increasing the number of whistles on the ice.
Each team will play 20 regular-season games with two referees
instead of one, the intent being to increase the flow of the game
by cracking down on neutral zone obstruction penalties and cheap
shots behind the play.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe this is an experiment, as evidenced by the fact no
commitment for the playoffs has been made. But the league is
calling it a ``phase-in process,'' giving more officials adequate
time to be trained.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said goal-scoring is up slightly in the preseason and he
expects the trend to continue. But not all are thrilled. Even
Anaheim forward Paul Kariya, whom the rules are meant to benefit,
said, ``I've always said the game is terrific the way it is. If the
game is (officiated properly) and referees are given the mandate to
call hooking and holding, the games will open up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rules aside, this season won't be short of changes. The phasing
in of four new teams _ Nashville this season, Atlanta in 1999-2000,
Minnesota and Columbus the year after _ led to restructuring of the
two conferences into six divisions. Detroit, seeking its third
straight Stanley Cup, will start the year without head coach Scotty
Bowman, who is uncertain of returning because of health concerns.
The Red Wings face strong challenges from Dallas, Philadelphia and
Colorado, among others.
</P>
<P>
   As long as everybody scores more, Bettman will be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league, from a whole variety of standpoints, has never
been stronger,'' he said. ``We don't think we've made radical
changes. We just needed to tweak some things. All sports leagues do
it. We're the guardians of this game and we have to monitor it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
