<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ARENA _ Update on fatal accident Saturday night in which two
workers were killed at the construction site of new Hawks and
Thrashers arena. Questions to OSHA will include what might have
gone wrong and when the site will reopen. (Stanford/Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES _ A special report on the aftermath of Hurricane Georges
on the Gulf Coast. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   LA-NINA _ Hurricane Georges has come and gone but more bad news
about the weather may be on the horizon. A weather phenomenon known
as El Nina, the reversal of El Nino, is developing and could create
conditions favorable for frequent and dangerous Caribbean
hurricanes like Georges, say environmental officials with the
United Nations. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ DAYTON _ The countdown begins. The pre-launch activities
put the Discovery astronauts through everything short of the
launch. We'll update Glenn's training, try to find out how the
networks will handle so many big news events at the same time, and
include some information on what a hot ticket this is becoming and
whether lawmakers will flock to Flosrida for the launch.
(Montgomery/Marcano, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NASA _ Like John Glenn, NASA is playing time travel. The
77-year-old former astronaut's return to space links the national
space agency with its whiz-bang past, in the same month it
celebrates its 40th anniversary. But while NASA's first two decades
were a whirlwind of giant leaps _ it went from its first manned
flight to stepping on the moon in just eight years _ the second
half of the agency's life has mostly been a comfortable routine of
workmanlike space shuttle missions. That's about to change. NASA
has big plans. It's mulling a new breed of spaceship, with the
emphasis on utility and cost-effectiveness. In the works: reusable
rockets that operate at a fraction of the cost, can take off in the
kind of weather that would scrub a shuttle lunch, and turn around
in a remarkable seven days. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NASABOX _ Highlights of NASA's 40 years. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   ROCKETS _ Giant graphic/copy block showing the half-dozen new
ideas for rockets; most art available from NASA via Internet.
</P>
<P>
   KOWALSKI _ It's casual Friday at the Justice Department, and
Barry Kowalski comes to greet you wearing a white cotton twill
shirt with a patterned tie, blue jeans and cowboy boots. As you
follow him to his office at a frenetic pace, you notice he's
bowlegged. It's fitting for this former Marine and Vietnam veteran
who fancies himself a cowboy, not just because he owns and rides
horses but also because he believes in honor and the code of the
West and protecting the defenseless. Although he refuses to talk
about the case, the lead investigator for the Justice Department's
reopened probe into the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr. is not sweating this latest high-profile assignment. As
the federal prosecutor assigned to win convictions against the Los
Angeles police officers who beat Rodney King, Kowalski is used to
performing under pressure. ``This is a lot less daunting,'' he
said, ``than whether the city is going to burn again. If we lost,
there would have been another riot. It made you need to win.'' A
profile of the relatively unknown Kowalski. (ABrice, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EVIDENCE _ Former FBI agent Donald Wilson has turned over to the
Justice Department the two slips of paper he says he retrieved from
James Earl Ray's abandoned car in Atlanta 30 years ago. One slip of
paper has a list that looks like a payment schedule next to such
words as ``hospital'' and ``Canada.'' It also says ``before 4-15''
at the bottom along with a word that could be ``Raul.'' King was
killed April 4. The other paper is the torn corner of a 1963 Dallas
phone book with a phone number at the top that a cross-directory
shows belonged to Jack Ruby and the Vegas Club. Clearly written
next to the phone number is the word ``Raul.'' Only a handful of
people have seen the two documents, which have never been
reporoduced in any publication. We have copies that will be shown
in a grafic that highlights and explains the significant portions
of the two documents and also shows the 1963 directory listing for
Ruby as well as a handwriting sample from Ray. (Atlanta
Journal-Constiution).
</P>
<P>
   GANG _ In what authorities warn is a growing menace, prison
gangs, fueled by racial and geographic animosities, are coming of
age in Austin and most other major Texas cities. In the past few
years, some prison gangs have begun recruiting members of youth
street gangs as soldiers in a growing crime network designed to
gain control of Texas' illegal drug markets. Their MO: murders,
shootings, beatings and home-invasion robberies. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman). 75. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GRANADO _ Henry Granado has been in and out of prison. But each
time parole officials released him, they had no idea he was a
prison gang member. That will change under new rules proposed to
crack down on gangs' growing influence outside of prison. (Ward,
Austin American-Statesman). 17. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
