<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Southern celebrates 100th game with win
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ Georgia Southern celebrated its 100th game at
Paulson Stadium Saturday by routing Virginia Military 63-7 before a
crowd of 9,687.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern (5-0, 3-0 Southern Conference), ranked third in
Division I-AA, opened a 35-7 halftime lead and rested most of its
frontline players in the second half. When this one finally grinded
to a halt with reserves playing most of the fourth quarter, the
Eagles had amassed 605 yards of total offense and completed their
5-0 start since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we got good contributions from all three facets:
offense, defense and special teams,'' said Johnson, after his
Eagles had pushed the school record at Paulson to 89-11. ''We made
some mistakes and got a lot of penalties, but were able to overcome
them.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth straight game in which Georgia Southern has
scored over 40 points. Against an opponent it whipped 49-0 a year
ago, the contributors were more than a precious few.
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Greg Hill, sitting out most of the second
half, completed 8-of-11 pass attempts for 94 yards and a touchdown
and rushed for 66 yards and another touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Adrian Peterson, averaging 169.3 yards rushing entering
the game, gained 122 yards on 16 carries and scored two touchdowns
before leaving in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Backup fullbacks Jevon Sullivan and Carl Small combined for 157
yards and 3 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Senior slotback Corey Joyner caught a 16-yard scoring pass, and
later raced 64 yards for a touchdown on a punt return.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to come out focused, because these are the hardest
kind of teams to get up for,'' Joyner said. ''Everybody expects you
to blow them out. It's a credit to the maturity of this team that
we came out and played well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 63 points tied the second highest total in school history.
The Eagles were up 35-7 at intermission, and could easily have
equalled that total in the second half _ before settling for 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to play a full four quarters,'' Hill said. ''We've
been scoring most of our points in the first half, and averaging
only 17 in the second half -- which is the same amount our
opponents have averaged in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   VMI actually put together a 14-play, 85 yard drive for a
touchdown in the first period, but could muster little afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really pleased with our defense in the second,'' Johnson
said. ''I think we allowed them only two first downs and 25
yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
