<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLFEATURE-COX     10-03 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLFEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buddy, can you spare a nickel?
 &HT;    By Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With so many offenses around the NFL increasingly reliant on
three-wide-receiver sets, the ``nickel'' cornerback, a position
once relegated to spare-part status, has taken on starter's
significance.
</P>
<P>
   Woe to the secondary that does not possess a solid nickel
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of spread offenses is spreading secondaries
thinner than ever before. It is no surprise that six of the top
10-rated offenses are those that use three wide receivers 45
percent to 60 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy, can you spare a nickel back? Most teams can't. But in the
chess games played out every Sunday afternoon, the quality of the
nickel defender often means the difference between checking an
offense or being checkmated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pardon the pun, but good nickel players aren't exactly a dime
a dozen out there,'' San Francisco secondary coach Jim Mora Jr.
said. ``With as much as we're playing the nickel coverages, you're
going to be exposed if you don't have one. Everybody's looking for
that third corner. It's a high priority all over the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's San Francisco-Atlanta game offered a good example.
On 20 of their 41 snaps in the first half, the 49ers had either
three or four wide receivers on the field, and they averaged 13.0
yards per play. Steve Young completed 14 of 15 passes for 203 yards
and three touchdowns, and five San Francisco running plays netted
57 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Third-year cornerback Juran Bolden, who the coaches apparently
thought was good enough to cover Jerry Rice in the game, wasn't
even good enough to be on the roster just two days later. Despite
permitting a pair of scores to Rice, both on long passes, Bolden
was claimed on waivers by Green Bay, another team seeking nickel
help.
</P>
<P>
   Because they don't have a capable third cornerback _ veteran
Terry McDaniel couldn't run anymore and fourth-rounder Roosevelt
Blackmon of Morris Brown struggled through most of camp _ the
Packers have been scrambling their third-down coverages.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal nickel defender, most coordinators agreed, would be a
cornerback. He could line up on the slot receiver or permit one of
the starting corners to move inside on long-yardage situations.
``That third corner is the luxury everyone wants,'' Indianapolis
secondary coach George Catavolos said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the coming Monday night game, one of the most compelling
matchups of the season to this point, Green Bay and Minnesota will
use safeties as nickel players because neither team has a third
cornerback good enough.
</P>
<P>
   If the Packers deploy in their usual nickel scheme, strong
safety LeRoy Butler will move into the slot to cover Cris Carter,
and 13-year backup safety Mike Prior becomes the extra defensive
back. For the Vikes, strong safety Robert Griffith plays against
the slot receiver _ probably Derrick Mayes _ and backup free safety
Torrian Gray is the extra defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to force the defense to put someone on the field
who can't cover us in our three-wide-receiver offense,'' Minnesota
offensive coordinator Brian Billick said. ``It gives us a chance to
stretch a defense and find some seams. It creates opportunities in
the running game, too. The teams that have three great wideouts
have an advantage, because there simply are not that many defenses
with three great corners.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few teams with three superior cornerbacks is Kansas
City. Neither magician nor alchemist, third corner Mark McMillian
nonetheless has turned his nickel position behind Dale Carter and
James Hasty into gold. McMillian is one of the few defenders in the
NFL whose salary ($1.25 million for 1998) is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   A starter in Philadelphia and New Orleans from 1993 to 1996, the
seventh-year veteran initially found his new role difficult to
accept. But he led the NFL with eight interceptions last season and
was on the field more than 60 percent of the snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I feel like a starter,'' McMillian said. ``There's
certainly no stigma anymore to the nickel job. Not many people can
do what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
