<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LEMANS-COX     10-03 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Le Mans here gets top drivers
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Game day in the heart of football country coupled with
major-league baseball playoffs makes an auto race named after a
foreign place seem like the underdog of the year in Georgia. But it
helps if that place is the home of the most famous and largest
sports-car race in the world, the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   And like the French Le Mans, Saturday's Petit Le Mans at Road
Atlanta in Braselton is more than just a one-day affair. It'll be a
week of sports cars, pomp, ceremony and then sports-car racing.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jarry, mayor of Le Mans, France, will be the honorary
starter _ Atlanta mayor Bill Campbell did the same at Le Mans _ and
Francois Fillon, former minister, deputy of the Sarthe and
president of the regional council of Loire in France, is the grand
marshal.
</P>
<P>
   The Petit Le Mans is 1,000 miles or 10 hours, whichever comes
first. Start time is 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The field of 40, largest ever for a sports-car race, boasts the
best in the world, including the 1998 Le Mans-winning No. 26
Porsche, driven by Yannick Dalmas of France, the BMW team and
factory-supported Ferrari teams.
</P>
<P>
   Team Panoz will field three cars, the two GT1s that ran at Le
Mans and the new, hybrid Panoz Q9 that's a combination of Ford and
an electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason for the big turnout of heavy hitters, Team
Panoz operations manager Jim Selwa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Petit Le Mans is an opportunity to qualify for (the) 24
Hours of Le Mans field. This is a big deal for a lot of the
teams,'' Selwa said. ``You wouldn't see the likes of the Porsches,
Ferraris, BMWs or Mercedes if it wasn't a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Split into two organizations _ Professional Sports Car Racing,
sanctioning body for the Petit Le Mans, and United States Road
Racing Championships, owned by NASCAR's Bill France _ sports-car
racing has been diluted on the track and in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest crowds at Road Atlanta in recent years have been for
AMA motorcycle races, totaling about 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Selwa said Road Atlanta officials are hoping for more than
40,000 fans Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While most prerace inspections happen in private, the Petit Le
Mans inspections will be a public, almost carnival-style affair at
Lenox Square on Tuesday and Wednesday. Inspections will be in the
northwest corner of the mall, 10 a.m.-4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PETIT LE MANS
</P>
<P>
   -- When: Saturday, 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: Road Atlanta, Braselton.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tickets: Four-day ticket, $55-$65; daily tickets $10-$40. To
order call 800-849-7223 or 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   -- Info: 770-967-6143, http://www.roadatlanta.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
