<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 10/3/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. -- Oct. 3, 1998 --
CLINTON-STARR-RDP, 10-3 -- Former Pesident Gerald R. Ford, who
pardoned President Richard M. Nixon, says that President Clinton
should be rebuked in the well of the House, where he would stand
and listen while Republicans and Democrats denounced his conduct.
``Imagine a president receiving not an ovation from the people's
representatives, but a harshly worded rebuke as rendered by members
of both parties,'' Ford wrote in an Op-Ed article in Sunday's New
York Times. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MODENA, N.Y. -- Oct. 3, 1998 -- BAIT-VENDING-2, 10-3 --
Daniel Bartholomew, a Hudson Valley farmer turned worm tycoon has
quickly become the country's second-largest operator of bait
machines, in background. Doling out live worms, grubs, crayfish,
tadpoles, even minnows 24 hours a day, the machines are becoming
increasingly popular amongst fishermen because bait shops are
increasingly hard to find and are sometimes closed at the odd hours
when the fish are biting. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WEEHAWKEN, N.J. -- Oct. 3, 1998 -- BAIT-VENDING-1, 10-3
-- Mike Pitely gets live bait from a machine on the gas dock at a
marina on the New Jersey waterfront on the Hudson River. In the
closing years of the millennium, the ancient art of angling is
going through some changes, none more startling than the advent of
vending machines for live worms, grubs, crayfish, tadpoles, even
minnows. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) IDAHO SPRINGS, Colo. -- Oct. 3, 1998 --
COLORADO-MINING-2, 10-3 -- Colorado School of Mines students
receiving hands-on experience in an old gold and silver mine
operated by the school. With more and more jobs going offshore,
enrollments at the nation's mining schools have plummeted, to 1,040
today, from 3,070 two decades ago. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GOLDEN, Colo. -- Oct. 3, 1998 -- COLORADO-MINING-1, 10-3
-- Jeff Keller, president of a Golden paving company, would like to
open a mine, but opposition has slowed the rezoning process for
Keller, who feels the site is sheltered from public view, noise and
dust problems. In the kind of battle waged routinely in the West
today, neighbors from a subdivision two miles away are mobilizing
to oppose the mine. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DALLAS -- Oct. 3, 1998 -- APOCALYPTIC-RAPTURE, 10-3 --
Marcy Berry reviewing a book from the ``Left Behind'' series at a
Family Christian Bookstore. The series, by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B.
Jenkins, is among best-selling religious books. The ``Left Behind''
phenomenon, a controversial interpretation of the Bible embraced by
many evangelical and fundamentalist Christians, scholars say, is
one indication of the public's fixation on the approaching
millennium and the widespread anticipation that the year 2000
portends some earth-shattering event. (Mark Graham/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) XIAN, China -- Oct. 3, 1998 -- CHINA-POVERTY, 10-3 -- Ma
Mingyuan, 50, lost his house, which was dilapidated but did not
cost him anything, when his neighborhood in Xian was bulldozed to
make way for apartment buildings. He was offered one of the
apartments but could not afford the rent. Today Ma has neither a
job nor health care, nor even a home, beyond a lean-to fashioned
from blankets and a sheet of tin. ``What I earn is enough for food,
but nothing else,'' he says. (Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TUZLA, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- BOSNIA-NATO-TROOPS-3, 10-3
-- Col. Tom Bostick at the Task Force Eagle base in Tuzla. American
troops stay on base when not on patrol in Bosnia. The United States
is spending $34 million to buff up its camps, extending and
resurfacing the runway at the air base that is U.S. headquarters in
Tuzla and replacing sprawling tent cities with wood and tin
buildings -- using a Vietnam-era design that can last 10 years.
(Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ZVORNIK, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- BOSNIA-NATO-TROOPS-2, 10-3
-- In the Bosnian Serb city of Zvornik, where American troops feel
unwelcome, cold stares at a patrol. NATO's mission in Bosnia,
originally scheduled to last only a year, has no end in sight. No
one in the Clinton administration will say so flatly, for fear of
angering an already irritated Congress, but the evidence is clear.
NATO has made no final decisions on the future size or shape of the
force in Bosnia, known as the Stabilization Force, or SFOR. (Staton
R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CAMP DOBOL, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Oct. 3, 1998 --
BOSNIA-NATO-TROOPS-1, 10-3 -- American soldiers talking at Camp
Dobol, along the line of separation between the Serbian and
Muslim-Croat areas of Bosnia. Three years after the Dayton peace
accords, NATO patrols in Bosnia have become routine. The troops
have separated the warring armies, stockpiled their arms, opened
roads and rebuilt bridges, made it safer for the people of Bosnia
to get on with their lives. What they have not yet done is to
figure out how to leave. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
