<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-REPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT DECRIES LACK OF RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Five days after speedway developer Bruton Smith
said NASCAR Winston Cup racing has gotten monotonous, seven-time
series champion Dale Earnhardt called for the sanctioning body to
rethink its 5-and-5 aerodynamic rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not racing good now. We're playing follow-the-leader,''
said Earnhardt, who will start 36th in today's UAW-GM Quality 500
at Charlotte Motor Speedway. ``Everybody is real loose around other
cars. They've got to give everybody across the board some \Rrear\S
spoiler back and some \Rfront\S valence so we can drive the cars in
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-and-5 rule was introduced by NASCAR at the beginning of
the season in an effort to reduce speeds by taking away aerodynamic
downforce from the rear and front ends of the 3,400-pound cars.
That has made the cars less stable through the corners, forcing
drivers to lift off the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of dominating performances by the new Ford Taurus
early in the season, the rules were adjusted in March. The Taurus
and Chevrolet Monte Carlo currently compete with a 4.75-inch-high
rear spoiler and 5-inch front valence on all tracks 1 mile or
longer (with the exception of the restrictor plate races run at
Daytona International Speedway and Talladega Superspeedway).
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR allows the Pontiac Grand Prix to compete with a
6.50-inch-high rear spoiler and 4.5-inch front valence height at
all tracks of one mile or longer (with the exception of Daytona and
Talladega).
</P>
<P>
   As confusing as it gets for the fans, Earnhardt said it is plain
frustrating for the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not run in the corner with somebody behind me,'' said
Earnhardt, a five-time winner on CMS' 1.5-mile trioval. ``I'll let
'em by and then race behind them and then try to get back by them
later. You just can't race. They took the racing out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose Speedway Motorsports Inc. empire includes CMS and
Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, bemoaned the fact that even
championship points leaders Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin rarely race
side-by-side any more because of the rules. CMS added 12,000 seats
since last year's fall race here to increase capacity to 147,000.
Approximately 10,000 seats remained unsold for today's race, and
TBS' live telecast will be blacked out within a 50-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually the fans will get bored watching single-file runs
around these racetracks and they'll quit coming,'' said Earnhardt,
driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy. ``If NASCAR
wants to hurt the show, that's what they'll do.'' McLaughlin wins
BGN race Mike ``Magic Shoes'' McLaughlin stretched his fuel mileage
over the last 93 laps/139.5 miles en route to a strategic victory
in the NASCAR Busch Grand National Series All Pro Bumper to Bumper
300.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin made his second and last pit stop during a caution
period on lap 107 of the 200-lapper. As series points leader Dale
Earnhardt Jr. and runner-up Matt Kenseth raced up front, McLaughlin
patiently remained within the top five. McLaughlin took the lead
for the second and last time on lap 178, after both Earnhardt and
Kenseth pitted for four tires and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up track position to get fuel mileage. But we were
catching up to the leaders, despite all that,'' said McLaughlin,
driver of the No. 34 Goulds Pumps Chevy. ``The boys in the pits won
it. They made the right calls. I even questioned them when they
left me out for track position, and they said we could make it on
fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's second career victory, and second of the season,
came at the expense of Kenseth, who finished 24.074 seconds behind.
Points leader Earnhardt was third, but retained his 97-point
advantage over Kenseth with three races remaining. McLaughlin's
winning average speed was 145.376 mph. Another Gordon streak Gordon
will have to hustle to keep a personal streak going during today's
race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has a 199-point lead over Martin, will be gunning
for his 15th consecutive top-five finish. But he qualified the No.
24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevy in 26th, the first time he has
started outside the top 10 since a 17th-place effort at Texas Motor
Speedway in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely proud of 14 straight top-fives,'' said Gordon,
who is gunning for his third Cup title in four years. ``I'm amazed
at it and don't want it to end. If it ends, I hope it's because I
finish sixth. But the deciding factor for this championship is if
something breaks on my car or Mark's car, or if we get caught up in
a wreck or cause a wreck. That's the deciding factor _ not whether
we finish fifth or sixth.'' Mayfield tops practice Jeremy Mayfield,
Martin and Ernie Irvan were the only drivers to exceed the 176-mph
barrier during yesterday's Winston Cup ``Happy Hour'' final
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield topped the speed chart at 176.800 mph in the No. 12
Mobil 1 Ford. Martin's best lap was 176.621 mph in the No. 6
Valvoline Ford. Gordon was 33rd overall after a best lap of 172.557
mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
