<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-KANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES RALLY PAST JAYHAWKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum was quick yesterday
to attempt the positive spin on Texas A&AMP;M's come-from-behind 24-21
victory over lightly regarded Kansas in the Aggies' Big 12 opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would liked to have come out of here firing on all
cylinders, thinking you've got everything all oiled up and ready to
go,'' Slocum said. ``But sometimes when you do that, the other side
is you think you're in great shape. When you play like this and
still get a win, you don't have any trouble motivating your
players. They know we've still got a lot to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Slocum also admitted that the 18th-ranked Aggies may be in
for another dizzying experience next week against unbeaten Nebraska
if they don't solve some lingering problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't play like we've played today, this year, particularly
on offense, and stay on the field with Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Randy McCown deftly engineered an 11-play, 75-yard
fourth-quarter scoring march that lifted A&AMP;M over the two-touchdown
underdog Jayhawks (2-3, 0-3). Dante Hall's 3-yard touchdown run _
his third of a 177-yard afternoon _ came with 3:24 to play. A&AMP;M's
defense, which had given up consecutive KU scoring drives of 87 and
83 yards, righted itself to stop the Jayhawks on fourth down at
their own 48 with 2:15 left.
</P>
<P>
   But all agreed that such heroics should not have been necessary
after the Aggies jumped to an early 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we could have put the game away a little earlier, but
things didn't happen for us, and we let them get back into the
game,'' said McCown, who went the distance in place of Branndon
Stewart. ``We were fortunate everyone played well and rose up at
the end of the game. It's an ugly win. But it's a win and that's
what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M played well early and late.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dat Nguyen _ him again _ intercepted KU quarterback
Zac Wegner's game-opening pass at the KU 28. His 17-yard return set
up Hall's first TD on an 8-yard sweep two plays later. The Aggies
then came back to go up 14 after an impressive 70-yard drive that
Hall ended with a 1-yard leap.
</P>
<P>
   End of good first impression.
</P>
<P>
   KU responded when Wegner hit Termaine Fulton behind cornerback
Jason Webster for a 58-yard touchdown before the end of the
quarter. Then came a futile second quarter during which A&AMP;M took 19
of 20 snaps inside the KU 50 _ and did not score. Slocum once
disdained a 40-yard field-goal attempt by sophomore Russell Bynum _
after flanker Leroy Hodge dropped a first-down pass at the 12 _ and
the Aggies failed to convert on fourth-and-eight at the KU 23.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M also punted twice from the KU 31, evidencing Slocum's doubt
about his young field-goal kicker, who missed twice (35, 28) last
week. And in the third quarter after Nguyen recovered a muffed punt
at the KU 13, the Aggies failed to score twice from inside the 1
and again from the 3 _ settling for Bynum's 21-yard field goal and
a 17-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job of scheming, blitzing and catching us in
slants in the red zone,'' said Hall, who was stopped short in each
of the three bursts into the line. ``They just did a great job of
putting pressure on us. And we didn't handle it.'' Extra points
Hall (36 carries, 177 yards, 255 all-purpose yards) became the
first Aggies player to gain 100 or more yards this season. His
previous high was 84 against North Texas and his only better game
was 184 yards against Texas Tech as a freshman (1996). ... McCown
netted 15 yards rushing on 13 carries, but gained 24 yards on three
carries in the telling 75-yard TD drive before losing a pair on a
sack. ... A&AMP;M gained a season-high 223 yards rushing, but against a
team that ranked No. 101 against the run with an average yield of
230.5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
