<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee squeezes tight victory from Auburn
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ Had someone taken an air pump and squeezed twice,
the football would've expanded enough to cross the goal line.
That's how close this was. Tennessee's Tee Martin had fumbled.
Auburn had recovered, the ball spotted a silly millimeter from the
end zone. One emphatic surge and Auburn would cut the Vol lead to a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   First-and-goal, a millimeter to go: Auburn inserts Gabe Gross at
quarterback. The titular starter, Ben Leard of Hartwell, Ga., has
had a frightful half. He has completed but one pass, has had a
shovel pass intercepted (!) and returned for a 90-yard touchdown,
had fumbled on a keeper inside the Vol 10. Oh, yeah: Leard has also
been dealt an elbow bruise.
</P>
<P>
   So now comes Gabe Gross, a freshman. (His center, Ben Nowland,
is likewise.) But hey, it's first-and-a-millimeter. From here, Gabe
Kaplan could direct the Sweathogs to a touchdown. One emphatic
surge. That's all.
</P>
<P>
   First down: Gross bobbles the exchange from Nowland and nudges
forward. Second down, two millimeters now. Gross sneaks again.
Touchdown? No ref lifts his arms. The Vol defenders turn and
gesture to their orange-hued backers, seated in the end zone
directly behind. (Georgia fans fondly remember this section of
seating as the Hose Zone.) The traveling Vol Army starts to scream.
Is such a thing possible? A goal-line stand from a millimeter away?
</P>
<P>
   Auburn calls timeout. This is the play it selects for use on
third-and-goal _ a line smash by fullback Tellie Embrey. Embrey
weighs 222 pounds. He gets nothing.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Fourth-and-goal, the Tennessee backers beside themselves
now. Leard returns, tender elbow notwithstanding. This is a Key
Moment. Down 17-3 at home, the nation's No. 3 team poised to
inflict another loss on the once-mighty Tigers, Auburn simply
cannot let itself blow this gimme. Leard takes the snap, turns and
hands again to Embrey. And, to borrow the words the venerable Vol
broadcaster John Ward used to describe another bit of Orange
stonewalling (at Kentucky in 1987):
</P>
<P>
   ''Not. . .even. . .ITALICSclose.ITALICS END''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five minutes of the second quarter and the entire second
half remained, a longish span over which much appeared to happen
but in truth nothing happened. Tennessee's offense crashed,
mustering only four first downs those 35 minutes. Auburn, behind
Gross exclusively, kept drawing near enough to kick field goals but
no closer. The final score, 17-9, tells us: (A.) that Tennessee is
the least imposing No. 3 team in the history of polling, and (B.)
that Auburn has fallen so far as to be unable to pick off a
conspicuously wheezing opponent even at Jordan-Hare.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols are a puzzlement. They beat Florida in OT on a night
they were outgained hugely. They beat Auburn by eight shaky points
after seizing a 14-0 lead in the first five minutes. Martin,
successor to the sainted Peyton Manning, completed a grand total of
five passes. The splendid back Jamal Lewis appeared to hurt his
ankle in the fourth quarter. Even so, the Orange never seemed in
real peril. When the opponent can't score from a millimeter away,
where's the worry?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
