<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-TENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No happy ending for Tennessee-Auburn matchup
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ For Tennessee, it was not a performance that will
gather the confidence or the endorsement of the pollsters. For
Auburn, it was an exercise in frustration that will have the Tigers
thinking what might have been for many weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   The best that can be said of Saturday afternoon's exercise at
Jordan-Hare Stadium is that No. 3 Tennessee beat Auburn 17-9 in a
game that left no one happy.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (4-0) exited the stadium wondering what happened to
its much-vaunted offense. Thanks to a 90-yard interception return
by defensive end Shaun Ellis and a 67-yard touchdown by Jamal
Lewis, the Volunteers led 14-0 with less than five minutes gone in
the game. After that the Tennessee offense was no where to be
found. Jeff Hall would add a field goal at the 2:51 mark in the
first quarter and that would be all the scoring the Vols' machine
could muster.
</P>
<P>
   For Auburn, the afternoon's disasters on offense almost defy
description. In the first half alone, Auburn had the ball at the
Tennessee 11, 10 and 1 and did not score a point.
</P>
<P>
   By the second half the Tigers were being led by a true freshman
at quarterback, Gabe Gross, who took over for the injured Ben
Leard. Gross led Auburn to a pair of field goals and got the Tigers
to the Tennessee 22-yard with two seconds left. His pass to Karsten
Bailey was broken up in the end zone on the final play of the game
and Tennessee manged to cling to the win.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped Auburn to 1-3 for the first time since 1981
with road games against Mississippi State and Florida coming in the
next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is still undefeated but asking a lot of questions
about its offense this morning after its inability to move the
ball. Lewis, the sophomore from Marietta, suffered an ankle sprain
in the second half but it is not known if he'll be at full speed
for next Saturday's nationally-televised game with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
