<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON-UNC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inept offense foils prospect of victory for Clemson
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ With his job prospects hanging very much in
the balance, Clemson head coach Tommy West needed a win, obtained
by any means possible, to quell the calls for his demise. On
Saturday, he might have gotten it were it not for his inept
offensive unit which cost the Tigers a 21-14 verdict to an equally
hapless North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a tragedy of errors between two teams with a
combined record of 1-7 turned out to be a wild finish that put the
Tar Heels in the winner's circle for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers held a 14-7 first-half lead until early in the fourth
quarter, when Carolina (1-3, 1-1 ACC) scored two touchdowns in a
1:02 span to send Clemson (1-4, 0-3) to its fourth straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels forged a 14-14 tie on a four-yard TD run by Rufus
Brown, and took the lead with 10:06 to play following a Clemson
fumble. Redshirt freshman Woodrow Dantzler, who started in place of
the struggling Brandon Streeter at quarterback, lost the ball by
running into into his own offensive lineman on a scramble.
Carolina's Steve Fisher recovered at the 12 for Carolina, and Deon
Dyer caught a 12-yard screen pass from Oscar Davenport on the next
play for the go-ahead touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Streeter, who threw four interceptions in a loss to Wake Forest
last week, came in to take the Tigers all the way down to the
Carolina 2. But on fourth and goal, Travis Zachery took an option
pass and was dropped for a three-yard loss by Jomo Legins with 5:08
to play. Clemson was driving deep in the last 90 seconds when Brian
Wofford fumbled after catching a Streeter pass near the goal line.
A mad scramble for the ball ensued, but it rolled out of the back
of the end zone for a Carolina touchback at the 1:29 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson led 14-7 at halftime despite not completing a pass or
converting a third down. Punter Kevin Laird twice pinned the Tar
Heels deep, with both efforts leading to short, defense-aided
touchdowns. Clemson tied the score at 7-7 when Alex Ardley
intercepted a Davenport pass initially tipped by linebacker Chris
Jones and returned it 26 yards untouched.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were forced to punt three plays and out on their next
series, but Laird got a good roll and Antwan Edwards downed the
ball on the Carolina 2. On first down, Rufus Brown was stripped by
Jones, with Adrian Dingle recovering the fumble at the Tar Heels'
14. Dantzler got a first and goal to the one on a nine-yard option
run, then handed off to Terry Witherspoon for the go-ahead points.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina opened the scoring early in the second period on a
20-yard touchdown pass from Davenport to Na Brown. Davenport, who
started for the first time since tearing a left knee ligament in
the season opener, was lifted for true freshman Ronald Curry. But
when Curry went out after sustaining a pinched nerve in his left
shoulder late in the first quarter, Davenport perservered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
