</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA-BAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspired Alabama overcomes against Florida
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ Eighth-ranked Florida eked out a 16-10
victory over inspired Alabama on Saturday and in the process
absolutely buried its once-mighty reputation as the SEC's most
dominant team _ at least in coach Steve Spurrier's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't play like champions any more. We play like a bunch of
losers,'' Spurrier said. ''That's all you can say about us. We're
not smart enough, we're not tough enough. I don't know what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just an average bunch right now. We can't put a team
away. Can't score once we get down there, take advantage of
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida wide reciever Travis McGriff caught nine passes for 213
yards, the second-best single-game receiving yardage performance in
school history, including the Gators' only touchdown. Kicker Jeff
Chandler converted on field goals of 24 yards twice and a 28-yarder
with 4:01 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida's impotence near the goal line and a mental lapse on
defense enabled Alabama to keep the ending suspenseful until
Florida cornerback Tony George intercepted substitute quarterback
Andrew Zow's first down pass at the Gators 32.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (4-1, 2-1 SEC) appeared to be wrapping up this one with
3:19 to play. The Gators had driven from their 27 to the Bama 26.
On fourth-and-1, tailback Terry Jackson took the handoff and
attempted to squeeze through the middle of the line but was stopped
short of a first down.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson Tide then shocked Florida with a 45-yard Zow to
Calvin Hall pass for a first down at the Gators 34.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought they were going to catch it and score a touchdown,''
Spurrier said. ''We were playing four deep and our defensive back
decided he wanted to play a little shorter than that. We're a very
undisciplined team; they don't play like the coaches ask. We've got
to try to make some changes and do something, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, George stepped in front of sideline pass
intended for Hall and the Gators sat on the final nine seconds.
</P>
<P>
   All that was left for the Gators to do was examine their
futility on offense. The last time Florida was held to 16 points or
less in a victory was a 14-9 win over Florida State in 1991. It was
the Gators' lowest output since a 30-6 loss to Mississippi State in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Florida lost one scoring opportunity on one interception and
lost two fumbles, bringing its five-game total to 12. The Gators
lost just eight through 11 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Florida had first downs at the Alabama 9
and later at the Alabama 12 and had to settle for field goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, a first-and-goal at the Bama 8 died when
Fernando Bryant intercepted Doug Johnson in the end zone. A
first-and-goal at the 4 brought another Gators field goal. A
first-and-goal at the 2 was squandered when Johnson fumbled and
Travis Smith recovered for the Tide.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fourth quarter, Jackson lost a fumble on
first-and-goal at the 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''Me and the older guys on the team were sitting over on the
bench thinking we're pretty sorry now,'' Jackson said. ``We should
be scoring a lot of points easily but we're not. We're down on the
5-yard line and not scoring. High school teams can score from the
5-yard line.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternating Jesse Palmer and Johnson at quarterback, sometimes
on every other play, Spurrier's offense lacked any semblance of
consistency. He said he would try to go with one quarterback next
week against LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just told Doug and Jesse, whoever has the best week of
practice is going to start the (LSU) game and got a chance to go
with it. I'm tried of this zig zaggin' around. When one's
struggling the other one's going in,'' Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was 10-for-20 for 187 yards, Palmer 10-for-19 for 169
yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida defense sacked Alabama quarterbacks eight times and
held the Tide running game to 41 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
