<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No need for trepidation as Georgia Tech takes win
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is without doubt that George O'Leary moved into the
second half at Georgia Tech Saturday afternoon with some degree of
trepidation. Likewise, he was counting on the old tradition that
there's some advantage in a team playing on its own yard. Grant
Field has been home to Georgia Tech football teams since 1913, the
oldest on-campus stadium south of Harvard and Pennsylvania, and
blessed by the addition of Bobby Dodd's name in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on Duke's turf last year, Georgia Tech rode casually
into the fourth quarter on a cushion of 38-11. At the end, the
Yellow Jackets were gasping and O'Leary wondered what had become of
all that stuff about the luck of the Irish. Duke coach Fred
Goldsmith had inserted a fifth-year quarterback who had lettered
only once, and David Green and Corey Thomas connected for four
touchdowns, like Montana and Rice, in harrowing succession. Georgia
Tech was saved by the clock, like a last-minute stay of execution.
O'Leary's team was already working on a three-game losing streak.
That would have been a deadly blow.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blue Devils came out of the box in the third quarter
here Saturday and drove from kickoff to touchdown with offensive
efficiency, you could hear the beat of O'Leary's heart. On this
first Saturday in October, though, the fourth quarter would belong
to Georgia Tech. Philip Rogers caught a 33-yard pass from Joe
Hamilton, Ed Wilder punished Duke defenders on an 11-yard run for
touchdown, and O'Leary felt so giddy, he introduced a new field
goal kicker, and Kai Cornwall, a sophomore from Newport News, Va.,
was true from 33 yards. That was it, Georgia Tech 17, Duke 0 in the
fourth, and the breathing was easier.
</P>
<P>
   As lopsided as the 41-13 score would indicate, Georgia Tech
could not have gone into this game with a bloated ego. Winning at
North Carolina was against a team of undetermined quality. Duke was
not a team to be taken lightly, as O'Leary had insisted and
newspaper headlines had corroborated. Nor did Goldsmith and company
come to this old accumulation of concrete and steel to surrender.
In fact, he was feeling pretty good in the second quarter, and here
the Duke coach takes up the story.
</P>
<P>
   ''We drop a dadgum interception that would have been a
touchdown,'' he said. ``Then we get the ball back and drive down
there. Everything looks fine and we go to the well once too often
on the naked bootleg.''
</P>
<P>
   There, Spencer Romine, the Duke quarterback, fumbled, Matt
Uremovich, redshirt freshman linebacker from New Lenox, Ill.,
picked up the bouncing ball and ran 54 of the most exhilirating
yards of his life for a touchdown. The score became 24-3 instead of
17-10, by Goldsmith calculation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Georgia Tech looked to be just too much for
Duke at this stage of the season. With each new day in the trench,
Hamilton picks it up another notch. ''I think we're beginning to
click,'' he said, and it's there to be seen. Line play, running
backs and receivers _ with an asterisk. Between them, six passes
were dropped Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If so it be, it's not a moment too soon. Georgia Tech now moves
into the killer stretch of the season, N.C. State, Virginia and
Florida State in a row, all conference rivals, but happily, the
latter two on home ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the record, this was the 577th game Georgia Tech has won in
intercollegiate football. Of more immediacy, this broke O'Leary's
personal tie at The Flat. He has moved over the edge, 21 times a
winner, 20 times loser.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
