u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-LEDE-COX     10-03 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech focuses on N.C. State after win over Duke
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three games removed from the Boston College fiasco and facing
the defining three games of its season, Georgia Tech shoved Duke
out of its way 41-13 on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly a win over Duke means in hard to say; the Blue
Devils have now lost an ACC record 21 straight conference games. A
better test awaits the Yellow Jackets (3-1 overall, 2-0 in the ACC)
in the next three weeks: a showdown against giant-killing N.C.
State, followed by home games against No. 10 Virginia and No. 9
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of next week's game at N.C. State's Carter-Finley
Stadium will be 3-0 in the ACC and tied for first place with
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is it,'' Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton said. ``The
conference is won or lost right there, these three games. ... We're
going to show up Saturday and see what N.C. State is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   One man ready to see Hamilton on his way to Carter-Finley
Stadium and beyond is Duke coach Fred Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hamilton needs to get his butt to the NFL,'' Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   The junior quarterback passed for 256 yards and three touchdowns
as the Yellow Jackets won their third straight since being upset by
Boston College 41-31 in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton completed 20 of 32 throws, although six of his passes
were dropped. He threw no interceptions for the third game in a
row. Just one of his last 250 passes have been picked off, dating
to last year's North Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamilton wasn't dropping back to pass, he was burning Duke
on the option. Tech ran it 17 times and got 124 yards. Charlie
Rogers led the running backs this week with 51 yards on eight
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton took the suspense out of the game of the week from the
start. Alternating between run and pass, he opened the game by
taking Tech on a 92-yard drive that ended with Duke's defense
biting on a play-action fake and Hamilton hitting Dez White deep
for a 53-yard touchdown play and a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tech scored on three of its first four possession and never
allowed Duke closer than 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton used another drive of 90-plus yards to take care of any
chance for Duke (2-3, 0-3) to build momentum after the Blue Devils
had cut the lead to 24-13 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   This time Tech rolled 94 yards and scored on a 33-yard swing
pass to Phillip Rogers. The junior had dropped a similar pass in
the first half, but took this one, broke through any would-be
tacklers up the left and stretched into the end zone to give the
Yellow Jackets a 31-13 lead with 14:24 remaining in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach George O'Leary's only real complaints came with the
dropped passes and a lack of domination in the red zone _ Tech
settled for a field goal after a first-and-goal from the 7, and
later for a Brad Chambers' field goal try from 47 yards that
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has now scored more than 40 points three games in a row,
the first time the Jackets have done that since their 1990 UPI
national championship team did so in its last three wins over Wake
Forest, Georgia and Nebraska. Defensively, the Yellow Jackets can
feel good about the last three games too. Other than a pair of long
passes to Richmond Flowers, Tech was able to negate Duke's tandem
of good receivers and limited the Devils to a pair of Sims Lenhardt
field goals, of 45 and 50 yards, in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   For the third game in a row, Tech pulled the quarterback
sandwich, with defenders coming from opposite sides _ one pounding
the quarterback and the other picking up the resulting fumble and
running for the end zone. This week it Delaunta Cameron supplying
the first hit on Romine and Matt Uremovich scooping up the ball at
his feet. He returned it 54 yards, pulling away from one tackler
and scoring for a 24-3 second quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tech forced two turnovers in the first half and converted them
into 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Where last year's Tech defense surrendered four Duke touchdown
passes in the last quarter to make the game close, this one shut
the door on Duke on the way to Tech's eighth win over the Blue
Devils in the last nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew everyone was going to be watching us real close after
the North Carolina win last week,'' Uremovich said. ''And we wanted
to let everyone know it wasn't a fluke. We wanted to show everyone
that we really do have a good defense here.''
</P>
<P>
   The true test, though, is next Saturday, when Tech's defense
will try to figure out what to do with N.C. State quarterback Jamie
Barnette and receiver Torry Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're standing right where we want to be, except for that one
loss,'' senior defensive end Jesse Tarplin said. ''We're headed in
the right direction. Every week we're getting better and better.
... (A win at N.C. State) puts you in the driver's seat. We've got
to concentrate hard and beat N.C. State.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
