<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MOREHOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alcorn State too much for Morehouse to handle
 &HT;    By Seth Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The undersized Morehouse Maroon Tigers gave a good fight but
eventually succumbed to the Alcorn State Braves 27-13 Saturday
before a crowd of 6,500 at B.T. Harvey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn (2-3), a Division I-AA team from the Southwestern
Athletic Conference, outweighed Division II Morehouse (0-6) by an
average of 60 pounds per man. The Maroon Tigers used an array of
different sets on offense and various stunts on defense in an
attempt to neutralize the Braves' size advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assistant coaches did a great job of getting our players
in position to make some plays,'' said Morehouse first-year head
coach Frank Hickson. ``I really hurt for these kids because they
played hard. They came up against a formidable SWAC opponent, but
they hung together. I think they found out today that they can play
with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn head coach Johnny Thomas, also in his first year at the
helm, was impressed by the Maroon Tigers' effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably should have won this game by more than we did, but
you have to give Morehouse credit,'' Thomas said. ``They were
extremely well prepared and they are a good football team. We made
some mistakes and had some penalties that hurt us. Were thankful
for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Alcorn was en route to a blowout. Four minutes
into the contest, the Braves drove 74 yards in eight plays. Running
back Rodney Thomas capped the drive with a 1-yard touchdown to put
Alcorn on top and set the course for a record-setting day for the
senior.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas finished with 32 carries and a school-record 240 yards.
But more impressive is the fact that he missed the better part of
three days of practice because of his class load. The
biology/pre-med major has a 3.2 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be much better than he already is,'' Thomas said.
``He is a great model for the student athlete and he does a
tremendous job for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn led by only one, 7-6, at halftime as Morehouse senior
wide receiver Bruce Randall scored on an 8-yard run. The two-point
conversion failed, but the Maroon Tigers held Alcorn scoreless in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Braves scored 20 unanswered points in the second
half to put the game away. Two third-quarter touchdowns came on
passes of 26 yards to Donald Driver and 37 yards to Rennard
Reynolds from quarterback Damion Ford, who completed 13 of 28
passes for 228 yards, and ran for 51 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and his receivers were able to make some big plays when
they were left in man-to-man coverage when the Maroon Tigers
blitzed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
