<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP-PLAYERS-TEX     10-03 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP-PLAYERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. OCTOBER HAS COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another fall. Another chance for Reggie Jackson to defend his
title.
</P>
<P>
   It's 21 years ago this month that ``Reg-gie!'' earned seemingly
eternal man-of-the-month bragging rights with his unprecedented
World Series heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Three swings that won a game. One moniker that earned him
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. October.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this year's challenge to his reign will come from
back-to-back perfect games by flame-thrower Randy Johnson or more
two-touchdown frolics by footballer-turned-majorette Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Mr. October is safe. But he's also gotta be lonely.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to fill out the calendar _ the definitive millennium
sports chronicle hailing the 12 athletes who best defined a month
during the 20th century. Picked up in the year 2098, this calendar
will provide a snapshot of who we cheered and when we cheered them
back in the good ol' days of McGwire, Jordan and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It's by no means the 12 best or even best-known. Instead, this
log is filled with 12 who _ when viewed in their moment of glorious
triumph _ left no question as to what time of year it was in the
sports year.
</P>
<P>
   MAN FOR ALL SEASONS
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The only man who proved as consistent and predictable as time
itself. As unstoppable as blinking, he didn't define a specific
month during his 2,632 consecutive days on the job, but he did
manage to affix the national spotlight on the everyday chore of
going to work.
</P>
<P>
   MR. JANUARY
</P>
<P>
   Joe Montana
</P>
<P>
   Held a nation's breath by setting up ``The Catch'' with ``The
Pass'' to beat the Cowboys in the 1981 NFC Championship Game,
catapulting him and the 49ers to four Super Bowl victories during
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   MR. FEBRUARY
</P>
<P>
   1980 U.S. Olympic Hockey Team
</P>
<P>
   No matter when or where you see the grainy video footage from
Lake Placid now, you can't help but remember where you were and how
you felt when the underdog amateur Americans slayed the mighty
Russians, then won the gold.
</P>
<P>
   MR. MARCH
</P>
<P>
   John Wooden
</P>
<P>
   Only after his departure did college basketball blossom into
madness. Before, the genius UCLA coach swallowed any suspense by
amassing 10 NCAA men's basketball titles in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   MR. APRIL
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever prowled the greens and azaleas of The Masters
like the Golden Bear. A record six green jackets made his visits to
the Butler's Cabin a rite of spring.
</P>
<P>
   MR. MAY
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky
</P>
<P>
   The most dominant hockey player of all time upstaged Kentucky's
horses and Indy's cars by capping four NHL seasons with Stanley
Cups and another nine with Most Valuable Player awards.
</P>
<P>
   MR. JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan
</P>
<P>
   Six NBA Finals appearances. Six NBA championships. Six NBA
Finals MVP awards. The game-winning shot in what might have been
his final game. Basketball's best ever wore a path to Grant Park
under the summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   MR. JULY
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Borg
</P>
<P>
   Long before the days of oversized titanium racquets and
style-over-substance images, he was the king of Wimbledon's
pristine lawn courts. Using a steely stare and a cruel two-handed
backhand as his fireworks, the stoic Swede won tennis' ultimate
tournament a record six times. (See Martina Navratilova and her
nine Wimbledons in the ``Ms.'' calendar.)
</P>
<P>
   MR. AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Carl Lewis
</P>
<P>
   Whether smoothly striding over 200 meters, taking a baton for a
furious final 100 anchor leg, or soaring into the sand, he captured
10 Olympic medals over 12 years on sultry days and nights dripping
with sweat and patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   MR. SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
</P>
<P>
   Only Jerry Lewis has piled up gaudier numbers than these two
around Labor Day. Their home-run chase was better than any pennant
race, gluing fans to arguably the most memorable month in the
history of America's past-time.
</P>
<P>
   MR. OCTOBER _ Reggie Jackson
</P>
<P>
   Like his trifecta at Yankee Stadium on Oct. 18, 1977, his
14-pitch battle with Dodgers rookie Bob Welch that ended in a
strikeout became a '78 fall classic.
</P>
<P>
   MR. NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Keith Jackson
</P>
<P>
   From growling about ``big uglies'' to jumping out of his ABC
blazer over a ``fumblllllllle!'', no one set the stage for an
autumn college football rivalry like him. Jackson's folksy ``Whoa,
Nellie'' vernacular became as traditional in early winter as Ohio
State-Michigan, Oklahoma-Nebraska, Texas-Texas A&AMP;M and
turkey-dressing.
</P>
<P>
   MR. DECEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Vince Lombardi
</P>
<P>
   The only man more comfortable in knee-deep snow and minus-20
wind chill was Santa Claus himself. The image of the gritty Green
Bay Packers coach in his element _ stalking the ``frozen tundra''
with a rolled-up playsheet _ is as powerful today as when his teams
went 22-2-2 in December games from 1959-67, and won five NFL
championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981003.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      10-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE DENOUNCES LATEST RELEASE OF MATERIAL FROM STARR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House Saturday denounced the latest
disclosures in the Monica S. Lewinsky scandal as ``garbage,'' while
the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee appeared ready to
signal that his panel would complete an impeachment inquiry by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   With the midterm congressional elections only a month away, all
sides in the controversy are struggling for the high ground as an
impeachment inquiry is all but certain to begin in earnest this
week on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his wife retreated to Camp David Saturday
afternoon for a respite from the storm that has consumed the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, White House and Democratic lawyers continued
to examine the 4,610 pages of grand jury testimony, FBI interviews,
and tape transcripts released Friday by the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The release of three thick volumes on Friday means that almost
all of the significant evidence compiled by the independent
counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, during his eight-month investigation of
Clinton's affair with a former White House intern has been made
public.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Joseph Lockhart, Saturday described the
evidence as politically motivated. ``If you take a careful read now
of these two massive gargage dumps, I think serious questions
become clear about some of the conclusions and inferences that the
Starr referral reached that are not backed up by any evidence,''
said Lockhart, who took over as press secretary Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Congress appears to be moving inexorably toward an
impeachment inquiry. Representative Henry Hyde, the Illinois
Republican who is chairman of the Judiciary Committee, is expected
to express his intent to try to finish the inquiry by the end of
1998 when he appears today on television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic proposal that an inquiry end by Nov. 25 has been
rebuffed by Republicans, but Hyde is expected to make a
conciliatory gesture Sunday. He reached out to Democrats on Friday
when he reversed himself and agreed to ask Starr whether he intends
to send Congress more evidence of impeachable offenses on other
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Representative William Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat, led a
bipartisan effort to secure that information from Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats and Republicans expect the GOP-controlled
Judiciary Committee to vote along party lines to begin an
open-ended inquiry to determine whether Clinton should be
impeached. The full House is expected to approve the inquiry as
early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides then expect the committee to do nothing until after
the Nov. 3 election. ``It seems to me that we are going to be
treading water until November,'' said Judiciary Committee member
Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said Republicans need to keep the possibility of
impeachment alive until the election to keep their conservative
base content, but not push so far that they alienate Democrats and
Democratic-leaning independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have a dilemma,'' said Frank, who added that
prolonging the matter until the next Congress in January 1999 would
be unfair to both Clinton and the public.
</P>
<P>
   While Frank and others believe that Democrats no longer are just
playing defense, he cautioned that the political situation is
uncertain. ``The Democrats have a dilemma if the White House starts
to get too cocky,'' said Frank, a supporter of Clinton. ``They
cannot forget in this situation that Bill Clinton did something
wrong. They are entitled to fairness, but not to indignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee staffers Saturday worked behind the scenes
to prepare for tomorrow's historic hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Stratman, a committee spokesman, said he could not
confirm reports that David P. Schippers, the leading committee
investigator, will drop abuse-of-power charges from Starr's list of
11 impeachable offenses, while adding charges related to witness
tampering, obstruction of justice, and making false statements
under oath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
