<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-MEETING-BOS     10-03 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WINS SUPPORT FOR NEW CREDIT FOR HEALTHY ECONOMIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finance officials from the world's seven wealthiest
nations began negotiating a plan Saturday to revive the ailing
global economy, which has left one-quarter of the world in
recession and shows new signs of weakening the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it won support from Britain and France for
one of President Clinton's main ideas, the creation of a new line
of credit for economically sound nations that nonetheless need to
convince jittery investors that they can pay their debts.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan's finance minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, while welcoming
the plan, told reporters that it ``would not be very convincing''
unless Clinton persuades Congress to approve $18 billion for US
commitements to existing International Monetary Fund programs.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, meanwhile, claimed support from six Asian nations for its
proposal to spend $30 billion in aid to help revive other East
Asian economies. US officials helped kill a similar plan last year,
and US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has said that Japan, the
world's second-largest economy, can help the world most by spending
its money to clean up its own debt-ridden banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of plans floating around this town for big
reforms,'' said Paul Krugman, an economist at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology who is skeptical of some US proposals.
``Let's hope it works, but I wouldn't bet on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of meetings in Washington this week, finance
ministers and central bankers from around the world are casting
about for ways to shore up the ``global financial architecture,'' a
sweeping phrase that refers to the rules for global investment and
to several international agencies, including the IMF and World
Bank. Those lending agencies were created to encourage development
and stability, and they have been sharply criticized for their
response to the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the bureaucratic talk, the ministers are trying to
ease a crisis that has played havoc with hundreds of millions of
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that once-robust Asian nations were close to bankruptcy,
investors have pulled billions of dollars from of East Asia in the
past 14 months, leaving companies without cash and people without
jobs. Japan is also in recession. ``We're looking at two years of
negative growth and two years of low, even if it is positive,
growth,'' Mari Pangestu, executive director of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Indonesia, said of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian turmoil has also roiled Latin American markets such as
Brazil, and there are also fresh signs that it will end seven years
of economic expansion in the United States. Gillette Co. of Boston
announced 4,700 job cuts last week, blaming low sales in Asia,
Brazil and Russia. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 2.7
percent last week and is in negative territory for the year. And on
Friday, the government said that US job growth slowed in September.
</P>
<P>
   World finance ministers and central bankers are meeting in
several forums to fashion a response. The so-called G-7 nations met
Saturday, and they will convene an unusual meeting Monday with
officals from 15 emerging market nations. The G-7 major industrial
nations are: the United States, Japan, Britain, France, Italy,
Canada and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, annual meetings begin at the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank. President Clinton has said he will
``personally participate'' in Monday's meeting of industrial and
emerging nations, and he will address the IMF-World Bank meetings
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the table will be several proposals that are already stirring
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a proposal that aides have left vague, is proposing
a new line of credit at the International Monetary Fund to aid
nations that are essentially sound, but which find themselves swept
into the financial panic. US officials have not named countries,
but Brazil might be an example.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the Asian crisis, panicked investors have begun pulling
their money from all emerging markets. Some investors fear that
these nations have borrowed more money than they can repay or have
insufficient reserves to buy up their own currencies to maintain
the value of the currency. A nation might allay these fears merely
by having access to a large credit line, even if it was never
tapped.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton telephoned British Prime Minister Tony Blair and French
President Jacques Chirac to lobby personally for the idea and got a
favorable response, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
Miyazawa told reporters he would also support it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea is politically charged because Clinton, while
pressing allies for the new credit line, has not yet won a
year-long effort to win $18 billion from Congress to shore up the
IMF's reserves.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress aiming to adjourn for the year on Friday, Clinton
used his weekly radio speech Saturday to press lawmakers again for
the money.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has also proposed a debt-restructuring plan
for Asian nations and companies. Some nations owe so much to
lenders that they cannot spend much money to spur their own
economies. Under the plan, which is still in development, the
United States and other nations would recruit bankers and global
agencies to change the terms of the loans or to accept stock in
companies that borrowed the money in return for forgiving part of
the debt.
</P>
<P>
   However, a coalition of creditors warned Saturday that it would
oppose any effort to extend the idea to include so-called
``emergency debt standstill'' provisions, under which nations can
suspend payments on their debts while negotiating new terms with
lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday An even more controversial idea, proposed by France and
Japan in vague language, would allow countries in times of crisis
to restrict the flow of money by investors into or out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Known as capital controls, the idea is opposed by bankers and by
the United States. But others say it could force investors to lend
money or buy stocks in foreign nations more wisely, as they would
not be able to remove their money quickly if economic conditions
worsened.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, capital flowed into the factories, banks and other
companies in emerging Asian nations at the rate of $100 billion a
year. Within months of the Asian panic, it flowed out at the same
rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to avoid the conclusion that a system of totally
unfettered global capital markets exposes most countries,
especially small and medium-sized countries, to the risk of serious
financial disruption,'' said Moeen Qureshi, a former prime minister
of Pakistan and former World Bank vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
