<SLUG> BC-REDSOX-COMMENTARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BOSTON'S TEAM, THE SCRIPT IS ALWAYS THE SAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the end, they are always the Red Sox. Good turns
into bad. Victory dissolves into defeat. Joy gives way to sadness.
We go to the theater and enjoy the performances, but the script
never changes. Hamlet dies in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Time to bring the storm windows up from the cellar and peel the
tarp off the cordwood, sports fans. Boston's baseball summer is
over. Mo Vaughn's Red Sox career might be over. The Olde Towne Team
is not going to win the World Series. Again.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox lost Game 4 of their American League Division Series
against the Indians, 2-1, at Fenway Park Saturday afternoon/last
night. It was an excruciating defeat that gave the Tribe a 3-1 win
in the best-of-five series and sent the Sox home for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial Boston starter Pete Schourek pitched 5 1/3 stellar
innings of two-hit baseball, and got one run of support when
wonderboy Nomar Garciaparra homered in the fourth. Schourek looked
like he'd go down in New England sports history alongside Gary
Waslewski and David and Gerald Henderson. He was the surprise hero.
</P>
<P>
   But then Sox manager Jimy Williams and pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan started thinking too hard. The manager and coach had been
pressured by fans and media to bring back ace Pedro Martinez on
three days' rest but said they would not deviate from their
season-long plan. They said they would not panic. They looked like
geniuses when Schourek delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Then they panicked. The did something they did not do all
season. Leading, 1-0, after seven, the Sox summoned closer Tom
Gordon to start the eighth. Gordon is a one-inning specialist who
saved 46 games this season, including 43 straight leading into the
playoffs. Before you could say ``Jim Burton,'' Gordon gave up two
hits and a two-run double to David Justice with one out in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox threatened in the bottom of the eighth when Vaughn hit a
one-out double off the wall. Donnie Sadler ran for Mo. After Nomar
grounded to third and Mike Stanley walked, Troy O'Leary (1 for 16
in the series) popped weakly to center.
</P>
<P>
   There was good and bad karma before the game. Folks hanging
around the batting cage were not inspired when Vaughn took his turn
and said to coach Jim Rice, ``Come on, man. It's the last hurrah.''
But things turned for the better when Johnny Pesky and Charlie
Wagner threw out ceremonial first pitches. Pesky has been part of
the Red Sox for more than a half-century but was taken out of
uniform and banished from the clubhouse by the current regime.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek needed only seven pitches to get through the first
inning. The first two Cleveland batters hit fly balls to the
warning track, then Justice grounded to first and Schourek got a
big hand.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway was deadly quiet in the second when Schourek surrendered
a double and a walk before getting out of the inning with a nifty
strikeout (Richie Sexson, swinging) and a hard ground out by Sandy
Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth were rocking-chair innings for Schourek.
Then he got a lead when Garciaparra homered on the first pitch of
the bottom of the fourth. The 411-foot (over the Sox bullpen) homer
staked Schourek to a 1-0 lead and gave Nomar 11 RBIs in the
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe got the call to warm up in the bullpen when Schourek
walked Sexson and Alomar with one out in the fifth. After Enrique
Wilson flied to right, Schourek worked the count to 3-2 on Kenny
Lofton, then got the dangerous Cleveland leadoff hitter to fly to
center.
</P>
<P>
   Justice doubled with one out in the sixth, and that was it for
Schourek. Lowe came on and got Manny Ramirez and Jim Thome to end
the threat. At that point, three Cleveland baserunners had reached
third but none had scored. Lowe retired five straight batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had a golden chance to add to the lead in the bottom of
the sixth, but third base coach Wendall Kim inexplicably sent John
Valentin around third on Mike Stanley's single to left. Justice's
throw was on the mark, and Valentin was out by 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   On to the seventh. And the eighth. And the ninth. And the
winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
