<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SAINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HOPE TO AVOID FALL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was supposed to be Octoberfest. Instead, it was Octobermess.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Patriots went 4-0 in September, but when
October arrived, they turned into pumpkins. A 1-3 month included
losses to Denver, the Jets, and Green Bay, and the Patriots skidded
again in early November, losing to NFC Central teams Minnesota and
Tampa Bay. They hit their low point of the season, at 6-5, with a
27-7 loss to the Buccaneers on a warm Florida day.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what happened to begin their October skid isn't quite
clear. They had beaten doormat teams to accumulate their undefeated
record, but when the mettle hit, they weren't ready.
</P>
<P>
   As this year's first October game arrives Sunday in the
Superdome _ the site of a pretty lousy Jan. 26 in 1997 when the
Patriots bowed in the Super Bowl _ New England vows to avoid the
dips that marked its 10-6 season a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team has a better idea of what we're trying to do
than the team last year at this time,'' said free safety Willie
Clay. ``We're comfortable in our defense. We know what needs to be
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some adjustments we needed to make during the bye week
and I think we've done that. I think it's going to be tough to go
into a losing streak. You never know in this game, but I think it
would surprise everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Trounced by the NFC Central last season (1-3), the Patriots must
avoid the same fate against the NFC West this season. They begin
with the 3-0 Saints. The surprising 3-0 Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you looked at the schedule and saw the Saints on it,
you'd think, `Well, here's an easy win,''' said quarterback Drew
Bledsoe. ``But that's not the case anymore. They're a team worthy
of being 3-0. They're playing great and that program is really
turning around.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll's team is certainly doing everything it can to
avoid the fall this time around. Carroll has made certain there
were no New Orleans-type distractions. With a schedule that had
players tied up in meetings until 9:15 p.m. last night, followed by
a 10:15 bed check, it was virtually impossible for any of them to
sneak down to Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a New Orleans flavor of their own. A few
members of the coaching staff worked for Jim Mora on the Saints'
staff for many years. Tight ends coach Carl Smith (1986-96) was
Mora's offensive coordinator, Steve Sidwell was defensive
coordinator (1986-94), and Steve Walters was receivers coach
(1986-96).
</P>
<P>
   What that means is anyone's guess, but the staff can certainly
help with noise management, which they see as a potential problem
in this game. The Patriots didn't handle the crowd noise very well
in Denver in a 27-21 loss the first week of the season, taking all
three of their second-half timeouts in the third quarter to ruin
their chances of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Since that game, the Patriots have implemented a game plan for
noise. They have practiced amid leaf blowers and worked on their
hand signals to call in plays from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe also will wear a wristband that lists the lengthier
plays. That will help him save time in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll hopes his team can do what it did in an exhibition game
in Mexico City back on Aug. 17. More than 106,000 screaming fans
were rooting for the Dallas Cowboys that day, but the Patriots
quieted the crowd with strong, sustained drives and early points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought what we did in Mexico was great,'' said Carroll.
``We dealt with the noise and we put an end to it. It's all about
dealing with enthusiastic fans by going out and executing our
plays, and the goal is to quiet that crowd as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As for X's and O's, Carroll knows that if Saints coach Mike
Ditka had his way, ``He'd start a fistfight at the line of
scrimmage.'' Indeed, it is said that most games are won or lost
precisely at that spot. The Patriots' offensive line has to win the
battle against a very active New Orleans group that has already
sacked the quarterback 12 times. New England will have to open
holes for rookie Robert Edwards, who is still looking for that
first breakthrough game.
</P>
<P>
   Run blocking will be a key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've made the kind of progress that would
establish that we are on our way,'' said Carroll. ``I think we are
in the process. I still feel positive that we are going to be
effective with our offense in the long run. At this time, I don't
think we're playing with any dominant side to our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe expects to get blitzed but hopes that his line, as well
as the backs, will be able to pick them up. If the blitzes do come,
you might see a big day from Ben Coates, who may be somewhat alone
in the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Patriots will be without end Ferric Collons,
one of their top run stoppers, who has an ankle injury. Chris
Sullivan will start, with relief from second-year man Brandon
Mitchell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
