<HEADLINE>
DENVER STADIUM VOTE A GOING CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL head coaches whose jobs are in jeopardy should be trying to
move their voting residence to Colorado in time for the Nov. 3
election. That day, Denver voters will decide whether to pass a
ballot initiative that would extend a sales tax already in effect,
with the money earmarked to finance a new stadium. If it fails,
Broncos coach Mike Shanahan could end up on the open market after
the season.
</P>
<P>
   When Shanahan signed his new contract worth $2.4 million a
season in August, it included an out clause that allows him to
leave if owner Pat Bowlen sells the team. On the surface that might
seem absurd, but word is that Bowlen is considering selling if the
voters reject the stadium proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen would then try to make a bid for the eventual expansion
franchise into Los Angeles, a market that some think could cost its
investors a $1 billion franchise fee.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's unlikely that the vote will fail and Bowlen will
sell out, if that did occur, you might well find more than the
usual suspects among the unemployed head coaches because of a
headlong rush to land Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   With both Shanahan and Green Bay's Mike Holmgren on the market,
how long would Seattle owner Paul Allen, for instance, stick with
Dennis Erickson if his club slides backward again?
</P>
<P>
   How long would Baltimore, Buffalo, Washington, Philadelphia,
Arizona, Chicago, St. Louis, Cleveland, and even Tennessee stick
with their present coaches if they thought could land a marquee
coach like Holmgren or Shanahan?
</P>
<P>
   How long? Not long.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a owners meeting scheduled for Oct. 27 in
Kansas City to discuss preliminary requirements for the next
expansion franchise, and pitches will be made from representatives
of Houston and several from Los Angeles, nothing will be done.
Among the presenters will be former Hollywood mogul  &UR; Michael
Ovitz &LR; . Ovitz has added  &UR; Shaquille O'Neal  &LR; and  &UR; Jerry West  &LR; to his
group trying to build a new stadium in Carson, Calif. The so-called
Hacienda would be a stadium and mall project designed to lure a
team back to the second-biggest TV market in the country. Problem
is, Ovitz has one of several competing proposals in LA, including
one to refurbish the Coliseum, and none have either public money or
political support behind them. In contrast, Houston businessman
 &UR; Robert McNair  &LR; already has a stadium plan and public funding
approved to raise $300 million-$400 million to build both a
football stadium and an arena for the Houston Rockets.  &UR; Leigh
Steinberg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been asked to be a consultant by every LA
group but Ovitz's, is thus convinced that Southern California is
not yet ready to compete. ``We are so far away from being
effectively able to compete for a franchise,'' Steinberg said.
``We're not ready as a region. We have no political figure behind
any plan. Not the governor or the mayor or the head of the Board of
Supervisors. In every successful situation like this, there has
always been a political center of support. No one has that in LA.
As long as  &UR; Mark Ridley Thomas  &LR; and the Coliseum remain alive as a
prospect, all other plans are out of it because no politician wants
to fight the inner city.'' ... Despite the denials of Eagles owner
 &UR; Jeff Lurie &LR; , &UR;  &LR; don't be surprised if  &UR; Don Shula  &LR; surfaces as the
Philadelphia coach next season if  &UR; Ray Rhodes  &LR; can't get things
back on track. One well-placed NFL source said he had spoken
several times with Shula recently and ``he really wants to get back
in football. Don't ask me why but he does, and Lurie is the kind of
guy who would love to have a Hall of Fame coach to hang around
with.'' ... At one point during last Sunday's game with the Colts,
New Orleans's 270-pound defensive end  &UR; Joe Johnson  &LR; found himself
called upon to cover running back  &UR; Marshall Faulk  &LR; as the Saints
launched a zone blitz at  &UR; Peyton Manning &LR; . Manning picked it up and
got the ball to Faulk for a 78-yard touchdown. Johnson was
unaffected. ``I had him,'' Johnson said when he came to the
sidelines. ``I had him! He was just faster than I was.'' ...  &UR; Brett
Favre  &LR; is more than the most valuable player of the NFL. He's the
most valuable player of the NFL Quarterback Club. Favre accounted
for 21.2 percent of all 1997 merchandise sales from the Club, which
handles merchandising for the bulk of the league's marquee players.
Believe it or not, Dallas running back  &UR; Emmitt Smith  &LR; was second to
Favre, with 12.9 percent of the sales ... Despite the Vikings'
explosive offense, which is second only to Denver in scoring with
129 points, Minnesota wide receiver  &UR; Cris Carter  &LR; expects the
Packers to play the three-wide-receiver sets man-to-man the
majority of the time Monday night. ``They like the challenge of the
man-to-man matchup,'' Carter said. ``They play very physical and
they have a lot of confidence in their man-to-man.'' Asked about
the emergence of rookie  &UR; Randy Moss &LR; , Carter said, ``I think he is
the most natural receiver I've ever seen without any work, at the
early stages of his career. You have to realize he's only 21 and I
don't believe he's been involved with a very sophisticated passing
attack. But he's very, very natural as far as his movements to the
ball, his route running. He's a tremendous athlete, not just
jumping for the ball but unbelievably fluid going to the ball, very
comfortable in a crowd and very, very tough. He has unbelievable
drive inside of him to be a good player.'' Carter has taken the
once-troubled rookie under his wing since Moss was drafted with the
21st pick in the first round, far below where he had been rated.
Carter started his career with similar problems and can relate to
some of what Moss is facing. ``I came out of a situation that was
very similar to Randy and I know how people judged me and I didn't
want to do that to him,'' Carter said. ``I gave him the benefit of
the doubt. The one thing Randy understands is I tell him, `If you
can't tell me the truth, I'd rather you not tell me anything.'
That's the basis of our relationship. So there are certain things I
don't talk to him about. I don't force myself on him, especially as
far as social issues are concerned. I'm not his chaperone. He has
to realize that his past is not a myth. It's not something the
media has created. It's something he brought on himself. He
realizes that. All he can control is what's going on today and what
is going to happen in the future. If he wants people to stop asking
about the past, then he needs to continue to make good decisions on
a daily basis.'' ... The Colts signed  &UR; Ironhead Heyward  &LR; to a
one-year, $850,000 contract _ a long way from the four-year, $4.5
million deal with St. Louis that was terminated when he was
released Sept. 2 after refusing to report to camp at a weight coach
 &UR; Dick Vermeil  &LR; felt was reasonable. Heyward was over 300 pounds in
the Rams' mini-camp but was down to 262 last week in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Vermeil, he cut nearly 40 minutes from his daily
practice schedule at the insistence of his players, but there was
never a threatened mutiny, as reported in some corners. St. Louis
is now practicing two hours a day instead of nearly three ...
Here's Moss's assessment of the Chicago Bears, who once were his
favorite team: ``I favor the '85 Bears. They were my favorite team.
There was a lot of excitement. The '98 Bears, I'm not as excited
about them.'' ... The 0-4 Bears are believed to be the first NFL
team in history to lead at halftime in four straight games and win
none of them. ``Other teams are looking at us and saying, `Hey,
they can't play in the second half,''' said defensive end  &UR; Mark
Thomas &LR; . ``I think we should just stay out (on the field) at the
half.'' It couldn't hurt. The Bears have been outscored, 44-0, in
the third quarter ... Saints coach  &UR; Mike Ditka  &LR; says he has stuck
to his promise not to return to his profane former self, and that
applies even on the golf course. ``I went through a whole summer of
it and did real well,'' Ditka said. ``For the first time in my
life. It's just not that important. I did it for years and I'm
saying to myself, `You sound stupid.' Not only that, I think you
offend people around you. I'm going to give that up for good.'' The
way he's done that on the sidelines, he says, is simply to
recognize that every blown play is not his players' fault. ``I
think I'm starting to understand there are good players on both
teams,'' he said. ``We can't make good plays every play. They can't
make good plays every play. It's got to be a little give and
take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
