<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-REFEREES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO REFS NOT NECESSARILY BETTER THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ruins captain Ray Bourque regards the National Hockey League's
new rules as a mixed bag. Bourque, who enters his 20th season, has
seen changes over the years. Of the newest edicts, he likes the
smaller crease very much, thinks the jury is still out on the extra
2 feet behind the net, and believes the two-referee system is
flat-out awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, not at all,'' said Bourque. ``I think the one
ref calls a great game. If they keep calling things through the
whole three periods, I think they do a fine job. Even if it's one
or two refs, I don't know if they'll ref any different once it
comes to crunch time. That you won't see in exhibition or even
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two refs, it seems like there's too much called. You've
got to be able to do some stuff out there and, not really get away
with it, but there has to be some kind of contact at times where
with some refs, everything is called. I think there are enough
special teams. If you start playing the whole period shorthanded or
on the power play, it's too specialized. The majority of the refs,
they call a pretty good game and it's such a tough job. With two
refs, it's an extra guy out there, an extra body.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers agree with Bourque. Despite beating up on Montreal,
7-1, in a game that included 50 minutes in power plays for the
Flyers and a total of 88 minutes in penalties, coach Roger Neilson
was furious with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stinking referees want to see who can make the most
calls,'' he said. ``No, I don't like this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Flyers GM Bob Clarke agreed: ``It's horrible, just horrible. Two
refs isn't going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Flames GM Al Coates thinks the system just needs time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our players adjust to changes, whether it's the goal
crease or a crackdown on obstruction. We just have to be patient
with it,'' said Coates.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Lewis, the league's director of officiating, said the
two-referee system can actually speed up games. The average length
of games with one referee, according to Lewis, has been 2 hours and
44 minutes while the average length with two refs has been 2:36.
</P>
<P>
   As for the experiment of taking out the red line, which was done
when Boston faced Montreal in Providence, Bourque made a face.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a joke,'' said Bourque. ``Leave it alone, leave the
game alone; it's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The league continues to look for ways to increase scoring, which
was down last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are paying attention to defense,'' said Bourque.
``They're taking care of things when they don't have the puck.
That's the way you should play. That's the way coaches should
coach. When you don't have the puck you've got to defend, when you
do have the puck you try to create but then you're playing against
a team that defends well, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want goals, but we'll have to make dramatic changes if
they want more goals or stuff like that and I don't think it will
be good for the game. It would be fine for a while, then they'd get
sick of that, then it will be, `We have to tighten up the game.'''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There is a roster freeze until Monday morning's waiver draft.
When that deadline passes, watch what happens with Vancouver. Word
is that the Islanders will send unsigned veteran forward  &UR; Trevor
Linden  &LR; to the Maple Leafs for goaltender  &UR; Felix Potvin &LR; . The Isles
are then expected to package Potvin and defenseman  &UR; Bryan Berard
 &LR; to the Canucks for disgruntled forward  &UR; Pavel Bure &LR; . The Canucks
are desperate for a No. 1 goalie, Bure has demanded a trade, and
Berard would shore up the Vancouver blue line ... So far, Canucks
coach  &UR; Mike Keenan  &LR; has been less than thrilled with the progress
of talented forward  &UR; Markus Naslund &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was taken No. 16 overall
by Pittsburgh in the 1991 draft. ``He's in a position where he can
either lose a job to the youngsters or he can take a job,'' said
Keenan. ``He has to put some points on the board.'' Naslund, who
played in just two of the Canucks' first six exhibition games, had
no points and four shots. He isn't overjoyed with the situation,
either. ``I want to play, it's no fun sitting around,'' said
Naslund. ``If they're not going to play me here, I'd like to go
somewhere else. I'll wait a bit and see what's going on. I'm only
25. I'm not even close to being the player I want to be. Obviously,
Mike is unhappy with the way I've been performing. I've not felt
good, either, but it's preseason. I'll get going.'' ... Former
Bruins goalie  &UR; Andy Moog &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who retired after playing last season
with the Canadiens, is enjoying his new role as part-owner of the
Fort Worth Brahmas of the Western Professional Hockey League. ``Am
I starting to miss it now that the guys are two weeks into training
camp?'' said Moog. ``Can't say that I do. I don't have a problem
with it. But when the games come, I think there'll be a change, at
least for a little while. When the season starts, I'll probably be
saying, `I should have played, I should have played.' But I think
you can appreciate my position.'' Moog turned down a little less
than $2 million from the Habs to stay on another year. The Canucks
also were interested in his services. New GM  &UR; Brian Burke  &LR; and aide
 &UR; Steve Tambellini  &LR; tried to talk Moog into extending his career.
``I had a long discussion with Brian and an even longer one with
Steve,'' said Moog. ``But what I told them was, `You have a coach
(Keenan) who really falls in love with one goalie. If I was the
guy, I probably would have played 40 out of the first 50 games, and
then where would I have been?'' ... These are hard times for New
Jersey defenseman  &UR; Lyle Odelein &LR; . His 5-month-old daughter,
 &UR; Paulina &LR; , is scheduled to have her fourth and fifth operations
this month to correct a problem that affects her breathing and
ability to take nourishment. The problem is extra cartilage in her
epiglottis. ``It's been tough on us,'' Odelein said. ``My wife gets
two hours sleep a night, getting up to take care of her when her
breathing gets particularly bad. I'm up a couple of times every
night, too, but it's much rougher on Paulina.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If you thought the  &UR; Jason Allison  &LR; saga was long, take a peek at
what is happening in New Jersey with defenseman  &UR; Scott
Niedermayer &LR; . Reports are that Niedermayer has offers on the table
for $9.75 million over three years or $6 million for two.
Niedermayer has said he would take less than the $4.15 million
 &UR; Scott Stevens  &LR; makes and the $3.665 million  &UR; Martin Brodeur
 &LR; makes. It's possible that his next move will be to ask for a
trade. ``Scotty will move on in life,'' said Niedermayer's agent,
 &UR; Don Meehan &LR; . ``He is more brave and independent than I am. He
won't stay in New Jersey for what is being submitted to us now.
Last week, Scott made a bold and progressive move by making a
proposal that would have paid him less than both Scott Stevens and
Martin Brodeur. I'm sure (GM  &UR; Lou Lamoriello &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; felt it was
important that Scott be paid less than both those players. I
thought Lou would accept the proposal by that afternoon but he
didn't and we've withdrawn it. We've now moved to a point where we
have to determine what our options are.'' Those options are: sign
an offer sheet with another club, ask for a trade (which Lamoriello
said he wouldn't do), or play in another league ... Sharks right
wing  &UR; Brantt Myhres &LR; , &UR;  &LR; signed as a free agent, will be out of
hockey indefinitely after entering the league-sponsored program for
substance abuse. ``He needs support and we're here to give it to
him,'' said  &UR; Doug Wilson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Sharks' director of pro
development. ``Our main concern is his well being. Myhres, who has
taken part in the program since the beginning of last season, had
169 penalty minutes in 23 games for the Flyers. After being sent to
the minors March 5, the club sent him home because of his alcohol
dependency. ``We had full knowledge of that before him coming
here,'' said Wilson ... Center  &UR; Doug Gilmour  &LR; said he's looking
forward to playing on the same team as pesky defenseman  &UR; Chris
Chelios &LR; . ``It's going to be good to be on his side,'' said
Gilmour, who signed with the Blackhawks as a free agent in the
offseason. ``I'll save a lot of energy. I don't have to concentrate
on whacking him. I'm pretty excited about that.'' ... Senators star
 &UR; Alexei Yashin  &LR; has donated $1 million to the National Arts Centre
in Ottawa, a gift that will be paid out over five years. Yashin,
who learned to love the arts in his native Russia, said his
decision has been met with differing reactions, particularly in his
home country. ``They say, `He makes so much money, he doesn't know
what to do with it. He throws the money around,''' said Yashin.
``This hurt. Those who were negative don't know about my life in
Canada. They just see it from where they are. They don't really
understand why it was done, and what kind of connection I have with
the Canadian people and expecially with the people in Ottawa.''
Yashin is hoping some of his donation will be used to bring Russian
artists over to perform in Canada ... Hope  &UR; Eric Fichaud  &LR; has
invested in a good suitcase. The 22-year-old goalie, who was taken
No. 16 overall by Toronto in the 1994 draft, has changed teams
again. His rights were dealt from the Leafs to the Islanders on
April 6, 1995. After some called him the goalie of the future in
New York, the Oilers picked up Fichaud via trade in the offseason
and last week sent him to the Nashville Predators.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how the addition of strong
personality  &UR; Brett Hull  &LR; works in Dallas. The captain,  &UR; Derian
Hatcher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is no shrinking violet. ``He can be outspoken as long as
he plays our game,'' said Hatcher, when asked about Hull's
loquacious nature. ``I don't care what he says to the media. It's
what he does on the ice. If he's not buying into our system, then
yeah, there's going to be some problems, but he knows that.'' ...
It appears that reports of  &UR; Darius Kasparaitis's  &LR; season being over
are premature. The feisty Penguins defenseman, who tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee, was expected to miss
up to six months, but he could be back as early as a month after
deciding against surgery. ``I felt pretty strong about it,'' said
Kasparaitis. ``I knew what surgery would mean to me. I figure I
should try to play that way. Nobody knows if it's torn or if it's
not. If something happens, it happens.'' He is in the midst of
aggressive rehabilitation, and if all goes well, he will receive
clearance to skate ... Phoenix captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk &LR; , who
secured &UR;  &LR; an $11 million bump in his contract, notched a 138-yard
hole-in-one at the Ridge Club. His playing partner was none other
than  &UR; Bobby Orr &LR; , &UR;  &LR; which most people would consider better than a
hole-in-one. ``I was beginning to wonder if I'd ever get one,''
said Tkachuk, a 5-handicapper. ``I mean, I played every day this
summer. It was bound to happen someday.'' ... Looks like Devils
forward  &UR; Jason Arnott &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who suffered a finger injury during a
fishing accident over the summer, will miss at least the first two
games of the regular season. He has been cleared to practice and is
due to be reevaluated Oct. 14. ``I can't really take a slapshot
yet,'' said Arnott. ``When you're out there, you really want to
shoot it but the pain lets you know.'' ... Former Boston University
defenseman  &UR; Tom Poti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now with the Oilers, has impressed coach
 &UR; Ron Low &LR; . ``Tom Poti's had a tremendous training camp,'' said Low.
``We've heard all about his offensive attributes and we've seen
them all, but what I liked about him is the way he played in his
own end of the rink. I don't think there's much doubt that Tom Poti
is going to make our hockey club. He certainly stepped up and did a
job that makes you think that he can play here right now.'' So far,
he's been teamed with  &UR; Roman Hamrlik &LR; . ``He's very talented, lots
of skill,'' said Hamrlik. ``I like playing with him. He's a smart
guy, kind of European style. He likes to pass the puck, likes to
rush, lots of talent.'' ... The Bruins will hold their annual open
practice for season ticket-holders and Corner Club members Thursday
at the FleetCenter from 11 a.m.-1 p.m. The doors open at 10:30
a.m., and invitations must be presented to gain admission ... Six
days to opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
