<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-LEAFMA     10-03 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ONFOOTBALL-LEAFMANNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG QUARTERBACKS CAN SNAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Wuerffel understands well the essence of the problem that
led Ryan Leaf to lose his mind a week ago and Peyton Manning's
father, Archie, to concede recently that even he was unprepared for
the amount of obsession surrounding his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy to expect coming in that you'll do well because
you did well in college,'' said Wuerffel, the New Orleans Saints'
starting quarterback and former Heisman Trophy winner. ``But you
don't have a concept of what it takes to do well in this league. As
far as the pass rush and the competition, it's like playing
Florida-Florida State every weekend. The rush is just phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but for Manning and Leaf, who will oppose each
other for real Sunday for the first time, it has been more like
Florida-Framingham State.
</P>
<P>
   Manning has yet to find a way to lead the Colts to a victory, in
large measure because he has thrown 11 interceptions and only three
touchdown passes, while Leaf's Chargers are 2-2 but know they have
been fortunate in their victories because their young quarterback
has eight interceptions, a turnover-to-touchdown ratio of 11-1, and
enters Sunday's game at the Hoosier Dome with a quarterback rating
of 32.1. That number is so stunningly low as to give meaning to an
otherwise meaningless statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their similar travails, something separates the No.
1-drafted Manning from the No. 2-selected Leaf: their public
reaction to adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Manning has remained unfailingly polite and outwardly unbowed.
Leaf, on the other hand, had a videotaped meltdown the day after a
horrendous 1-for-15 performance against Kansas City. And after a
petulant three days acting like a spoiled 8-year-old, Leaf played
so badly against the Giants last Sunday that he (a) was benched and
(b) had his public service announcement for the Make-A-Wish
Foundation booed when it was shown on the scoreboard screen at San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   That both quarterbacks have struggled was predictable. But
nobody is prepared for the kind of failure that can befall a rookie
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize the gulf that exists between college
football and the NFL,'' said Colts president Bill Polian. ``It's
the Pacific Ocean. It's as different as night and day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average fan's perception is the game is similar to the
best college football, but the worst NFL team would beat the
college champion by five touchdowns. These kids who played
quarterback, even in the best programs, faced maybe three or four
guys on defense who will play in the NFL. Now everyone they face is
good enough to play in the NFL. It causes them a lot of problems
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as predictable as the interceptions and the confusion were
the reactions of Manning and Leaf. Manning has suffered in silence;
Leaf erupted with the kind of emotional display that can come back
to haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me Peyton was involved in something like that, I
would have been flabbergasted,'' said Manning's agent, former
Boston College and NFL lineman Tom Condon. ``I knew this would be
difficult for him on the field and he's not happy about it, but if
there was ever a more unflappable guy, I haven't met him. He and
Ryan are very different in makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton has such a strong belief in his abilities that he looks
at adversity and doesn't get mad at it. He looks to overcome it. He
has an absolute confidence things will get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father told me when he signed with me that Peyton wouldn't
take much babysitting, and he hasn't. He's struggled, but he knows
it does no good to get mad about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf has always been a more emotional person. In good times that
makes him appealing. But when those emotions turn red hot during
turbulent days, eruptions like the ones that have occurred lead his
own fans to boo him.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout and the added pressure that can create for an
already struggling young quarterback is a concern to Chargers
general manager Bobby Beathard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with him on a couple of occasions the last two weeks,
not in a stern way but to let him know we were still in his
corner,'' Beathard said. ``This was a tough situation he brought on
himself, but I tried to assure him we were not coming out against
him, to get it off his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He denied that it bothered him. I told him, `If it didn't
distract you, you wouldn't be doing these things.' He's not used to
having games like that. You try to prepare them for how difficult
it's going to be, but in the back of their minds they believe
they're not going to have as tough a time as they end up having and
they're embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both us and the Colts expected there would be problems
on the field and, frankly, I'd agree with Tom that it was more
likely an incident like this would happen with Ryan than Peyton
because Peyton's environment was one where he was more prepared for
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people of San Diego love Ryan. They didn't boo him.
They booed his actions, and he's responsible for them. He
understands that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The action on the field can cause some young players to act up
off the field, and it can cause others to sink into themselves.
When Leaf publicly questioned his own fitness to play after being
benched last weekend, some saw that as a sign that the pressures
had gotten to him.
</P>
<P>
   But Leigh Steinberg, Leaf's agent, has been through this process
with a number of NFL quarterbacks _ Drew Bledsoe, Warren Moon, Troy
Aikman, Tony Eason, Steve Bartkowski, Kordell Stewart _ so none of
this surprised him. What it has done, he hopes, is teach his client
a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan sort of set himself up for a fall by playing better than
any rookie quarterback has a right to,'' Steinberg said. ``Then he
had about as bad a game as you can have and he followed it with a
bad week, but this is a long voyage and the boat has just left the
dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rookie year for a quarterback tends to be a rugged
experience. It's not always pretty to watch. They'll do things that
make you wonder how they ever got drafted in the first place. You
have to keep that in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan is going through something that is not an elegant part of
the process, but it's the only way to get better. The fact is, 20
or 30 years ago these guys wouldn't even be playing. They'd be
sitting behind some veteran, which until the recent addition of the
salary cap was considered the best way to develop a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's done differently, and Ryan has to learn from it.
There were some lessons I thought he already understood, but he
just snapped. He suffered a self-inflicted wound because he'd
played badly for the first time and felt as if the world was
against him. He felt cornered as the week went on and he didn't
react well, but he's apologized for it and learned from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget these are young kids. It's pretty dramatic to be
booed on the first play of a game. I think some of the comparisons
with Peyton have been overblown, but there's no question Ryan is a
more emotional, opinionated, and instinctive person. He'll never be
a button-downed quarterback. He's not going to fit into a Steve
Young or Warren Moon mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one in football doubts he'll be successful. He has
tremendous self-confidence and ability. We all know that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Polian, Manning is just as confident in his quiet
way, and it is beginning to show. Although his team has yet to win
and he has yet to have a day free of interceptions, Manning is
showing Polian the things he once saw in a young Jim Kelly and a
young Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peyton has a historical perspective on what's happening to him
this season,'' Polian said. ``He got that from his dad and his own
study. He understands his problems are par for the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``But unless you've seen him every week you can't see the
tremendous strides he's made. He's come miles from that first game
with Miami. His decision-making has been magnificent. Last week he
had three interceptions but two were tipped and the third was a
timing route where the receiver slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played much better and he feels that himself. He's
awfully upset that we can't win but he understands he's getting
better. This is the third time I've gone through this with a young
quarterback and I know he'll succeed big in the long run. There's
not a person in this organization that doesn't believe that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Ryan are very different, but without question they'll
both be great quarterbacks. When they play together this time it
won't mean much. But one day they'll play against each other for
the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they do, there is much growing _ and some grimacing _ to
go through. They will suffer loudly or quietly, but suffer they
will.
</P>
<P>
   And suffering right along with them will be Tom Condon, Leigh
Steinberg, Bill Polian, and Bobby Beathard, four guys trying to
keep two young quarterbacks afloat until they learn how to swim
with the NFL sharks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
