<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD REPLAYS TAKE ON LIFE OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Bird wants us to close the book on his storied playing
career, but he's the only one who figures to do that. Unless his
image becomes something monumentally different _ and three years of
coaching may not be enough _ he's going to be remembered for what
he did in those short shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's legacy, of course, is planted in Boston, with many, many
branches in many, many buildings throughout the NBA. He mentions
that his favorite game was Game 3 of the 1985 Cleveland series, but
there is no team he tortured more than the poor Atlanta Hawks and
there is no team he enjoyed playing against more than the 76ers
when there actually was a real Boston-Philadelphia rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of Bird stories still in circulation in every
NBA venue. He liked to play in the HemisFair in San Antonio because
of all the servicemen in the balcony. For some reason, he enjoyed
the old Memorial Coliseum in Portland. He hated the Silverdome.
</P>
<P>
   We asked four veteran NBA executives to recall their favorite
Bird story or anecdote. The only qualifier was that they had to
have witnessed Bird at his best. As you might expect, they didn't
have to think very long.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Kasten, Atlanta Hawks: ``I have many, many great Bird
stories, and I hate all of them. I don't know if there is any team,
anywhere, that he killed more thoroughly or consistently as ours.
He had his career point game against us (60 in New Orleans). In
what has to be the greatest game in our franchise history (Game 7,
1988 Eastern Conference semifinals, a k a The Shootout), we not
only didn't win the game, he beat us. I have no favorite story.
They're all bad. It was just extraordinary the way he played
against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought, is he the greatest passer? Probably not. Is
he the greatest rebounder? Maybe not. Is he the greatest shooter?
Probably not. But he was the greatest package of all those skills.
I'd love to be able to say kind things about him, since we still
have to compete against him. But the pain endures. And now he's
beating us as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   (Kasten also is the man who said, ``I rushed out and bought
Newsweek'' when told that Bird was on the cover of Time in 1985.)
</P>
<P>
   Pat Williams, former Philadelphia and Orlando GM: ``I have three
Bird stories that I will always remember. The first was when he was
still in college and his team was playing Rutgers in the (1978) NIT
in Piscataway, N.J. (a 57-56 Rutgers victory). I drove down with
the late Jack McMahon (talent scout/assistant coach) and we saw him
and we didn't think too much of him. We left the game, and on the
way back we were debating: Is he a Steve Mix kind of player? Or a
Steve Kuberski? I hope those scouting reports are either locked up
or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second is Game 7 of the 1981 Eastern Conference Finals. I
spent most of the game in a broom closet; I couldn't bear to watch.
I peek out every now and then and I see him make the winning shot.
He comes down the floor and drills it. That's his whole career. No
one else in the building can swallow or breathe, and he drills it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My final one is when the Celtics made their first visit to
Orlando. I had this radio show at a restaurant and I asked the
Celtics if Larry might want to come on. The next thing I see, he's
coming into the place and he sat down and did an hour, live. Then I
go to the arena and he's shooting before the game and my son is his
ballboy. Then Larry challenged him to a game of HORSE and a
photographer got a picture, which was on the front page the next
day. My son is now a junior in college and it's still the highlight
of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Checketts, former Utah Jazz president: ``There was one
night when we were playing the Celtics in the Salt Palace and, of
course, Larry was out there shooting before the game. All of a
sudden, about an hour before the game, in walks the Chief (Robert
Parish). He's walking the way he always walks with that stride, and
he's wearing a topcoat. Bird sees him and says something, but
Parish ignores him. Then when Parish gets under the basket, Bird
stops and goes over to him and lets him have it. He grabs him by
the coat and says, ``Do you know what time it is? We got a game in
an hour. Go get dressed.'' (Checketts did say Bird may have used
some adjectives and nouns not fit for a family publication.) So
after the game, I told this story to Frank Layden. And then I said,
`And we depend on Adrian Dantley for this?' He was something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry St. Jean, former assistant coach, Milwaukee Bucks: ``The
thing I will always remember is his banter during the game, which
most people weren't privileged to hear. There was a game in the old
Mecca where he was hitting everything and he'd go by our bench and
say, `Anyone there who can guard me?' But the one feeling that
always came over me every time we came into the Garden was hearing
that ball banging on the floor two hours before the game and
knowing it was him out there shooting. It was a lock.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bird was toasted, honored and praised all over Springfield
Friday and even got  &UR; Wilt Chamberlain's  &LR; vote for his first forward
on his dream team. ``He is the consummate pro,'' Chamberlain said.
``He learned his basketball the proper way. Now, not to slight
someone, but you take a guy like  &UR; Dominique Wilkins &LR; . He has the
great physical attributes that you don't see in Larry Bird, but
Larry Bird does everything better. The brain, when it is used in
the right way, is also a talent.'' ... And then there is  &UR; Bill
Walton's  &LR; take on Bird's mind: ``He coached every game he played
in. Sometimes the coaches agreed with him. And sometimes the
coaches were a couple days late.'' As for Bird as coach, Walton
said, ``Look at all the coaches who are in the Hall of Fame:  &UR; Lenny
Wilkens &LR; , &UR; Red Holzman &LR; , &UR; Jack Ramsay &LR; , &UR; Chuck Daly &LR; . With these guys,
it's not about hype. Or self-promotion. It's not about fancy
clothes. Larry is like that, and so is  &UR; Phil Jackson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who will be
in the Hall of Fame someday as a coach. Larry infuses light, hope,
exuberance, and spirit, and the Indiana Pacers were broken in
spirit before he got there.'' ...  &UR; Alex Hannum &LR; , &UR;  &LR; former
Philadelphia and St. Louis coach, had the privilege of coaching
both  &UR; Larry Brown  &LR; and  &UR; Doug Moe  &LR; in the ABA. He said he always
thought Brown would be a coach someday. ``He really knew the
game,'' Hannum said. And Moe? ``I would never have guessed that he
would become a coach. He was in another world half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said one of the regrets from his NBA playing career is
that he didn't get to play for  &UR; Red Auerbach &LR; . But he said he came
close. ``When the Hawks moved to Atlanta, I thought I had a chance
of getting traded to Boston,'' he said. ``I was salivating just
thinking about the possibilities.'' However, by that time, Auerbach
had given up the coaching duties to  &UR; Bill Russell  &LR; ... Speaking of
Russell, while he was winning a gold medal in Melbourne in 1956,
the Celtics, who had drafted him, were 16-8 with  &UR; Arnie Risen
 &LR; manning the middle. Risen said the credit he gets for tutoring
Russell during the 1956-57 season is overstated. ``It has been
exaggerated,'' he said. ``The whole thing back then was that we
were a team and everyone helped everyone out. I know Bill has said
that I helped him a lot and I'm grateful for that.'' Risen was one
of Auerbach's first late-career guys who were brought in to help
win a title. He had wanted to retire and go into the construction
business, but Auerbach talked him into coming to Boston, where
Risen helped the Celtics win their first title. Auerbach always
liked to bring in a so-called ``over-the-hill'' guy to help win a
title, be it Risen,  &UR; Bailey Howell &LR; , &UR; Don Nelson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; or Walton ...
Hannum on his call to Chamberlain to present him for his
enshrinement: ``Wilt never answers the phone and he likes the night
life. So you can't call him in the morning. I called about 9 and he
actually picked up the phone and said he'd do it. I thought that
was the end of it. Then, three hours later, Wilt calls back. `What
did I say to you, anyway?''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
