<SLUG> BC-IMF-WORLDBANK-MEET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC LEADERS DIFFER IN STRATEGY ON CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; first three grafs are new, refinements
throughout.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finance ministers of the world's largest industrial
nations agreed Saturday night to explore President Clinton's
proposal on Friday to change the strategy of the International
Monetary Fund and allow it to intervene earlier in propping up
economies that are at risk of being swept into the global financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came in a vaguely worded communique issued
after an all-day meeting here as financial leaders from the major
economies, as well as from many of the most shell-shocked, gathered
for several days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House indicated earlier in the day that Clinton's
proposal had already been agreed to by Prime Minister Tony Blair of
Britain and President Jacques Chirac of France, but diplomats said
there were still reservations from Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is facing unusual challenges from Europe,
Japan and emerging-market nations, each of which is arriving with
different and even contradictory strategies for stabilizing the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The clash of approaches, which began to play out as Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin sat down Saturday morning with Japan's
Finance Minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, reflects the extraordinary
tension and the behind-the-scenes power struggles under way as the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank open their annual
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   After months of market plunges, currency devaluations, bank
failures and bankruptcies across the globe, governments are
searching desperately for some kind of coordinated approach that
can halt some of the most virulent economic turmoil in half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   But it will not be easy, officials concede. As the meetings
opened, Miyazawa announced a $30 billion Japanese program to aid
stricken countries throughout Asia. The program includes government
loans, the purchase of bonds issued by Asian countries and
guarantees that private bank loans will be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   While Southeast Asian countries immediately hailed the move, the
administration's response was lukewarm. Rubin had said on Friday,
even before the announcement, that Japan's action was
``constructive,'' but that getting its own banks in order and its
huge economy restarted was ``by vast multiples more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa, a former prime minister who has 40 years of experience
dealing with the United States, shot back Saturday that Clinton's
proposals for new strategies for how the IMF could choke off crises
before they start ``would not be very convincing unless the United
States' commitments to the IMF are lived up to.'' He was referring
to the refusal by Congress so far to approve $18 billion in new
money for the fund, an issue that Senate and House conferees will
debate as the meetings go on here next week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
