<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-UNIFICATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS-HOLYFIELD? AFRAID NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCASVILLE, Conn. _ Sometimes braggarts don't know just how
right they can be.
</P>
<P>
   Several days before Lennox Lewis was to defend his portion of
the heavyweight title against No. 1 contender Zeljko Mavrovic, the
brash World Boxing Council champion predicted what the fallout
would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will actually say, `Why are you ducking Lennox
Lewis?''' the multi-passported, English-Jamaican-Canadian boxer
hooted in the general direction of his American alter ego, World
Boxing Association-International Boxing Federation champion Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Lewis huff and puff his way through 12 desultory
and disappointing rounds with the unknown Mavrovic, Holyfield is
probably asking himself the same question.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it wouldn't be out of fear Lewis struck into him after
going the distance with a man who never once fought a rated
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it wouldn't be out of fear Lewis struck into him in
his previous outing, either. That night, Shannon Briggs nearly
knocked Lewis senseless in the first round of a fight the champion
eventually won after Briggs nearly passed out on his own, falling
in exhaustion without being hit after missing with a wild left hand
in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, has Holyfield not agreed to accept $25 million to
fight Lewis and unify the heavyweight title for the first time
since Riddick Bowe won it from Holyfield six years ago?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because he knows he doesn't need Lewis to cement his
place in history and he's grown weary of hearing a guy who has
managed to avoid every big name of his era talk as if every
heavyweight since Jack Johnson has lived in fear of having to face
him.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe it's simply that he knows Lewis isn't worth
the $10 million he wants for the chance to hit Holyfield and the
lottery on the same night. If you care to dispute this latter fact,
consider this. Holyfield fought the nondescript Vaughn Bean two
weeks ago and drew 41,357 to the Georgia Dome (which, admittedly,
is in Holyfield's hometown of Atlanta). Lewis fought the equally
nondescript Mavrovic in the first heavyweight title fight in New
England in 33 years and barely drew 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's performance led Showtime's Jay Larkin to comment, ``In
every big fight he's had by his standards, he hasn't delivered.
Holyfield has been just the opposite. If Lewis was half as
successful in the ring as his lawyers have been in court, he'd be
an all-time great.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest names on Lennox Lewis's record are Ray Mercer, who
I thought he lost to, and a washed-up Razor Ruddock. Evander has
fought Mike Tyson twice, Riddick Bowe three times, Michael Moorer
twice, George Foreman, Larry Holmes. How do you compare the two if
you have half a brain?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's that big an event any more. My only
interest in it is it's something Evander wants to do, but I don't
think it will be made too soon now.''
</P>
<P>
   As even Lewis's trainer, Emanuel Steward, conceded before the
Mavrovic debacle, ``I think most of the public views Evander as the
champion. He's been a household name since the 1984 Olympics. He's
been involved in highly visible fights. After doing what he did to
the monster (Tyson) _ destroying him _ the public has accepted him
as the champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox needs to be a totally dominant factor to make the
fight. Then the public might acknowledge him and pressure
Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that a groundswell for Holyfield to fight
Lewis resulted from the performance against Mavrovic.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Steward both talked endlessly of the need for Lewis to
destroy Mavrovic and anyone else he had to face thereafter to force
Holyfield's hand because they believe Holyfield's promoter, Don
King, wants no part of a unification fight _ because if Holyfield
loses, King loses control of the most valuable championship in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   It is their opinion that King fears what Lewis might do to
Holyfield, whom he would outweigh by at least 25 pounds. It is
their opinion that because Lewis is 34-1 with 27 knockouts and
stands 6 feet 5 inches and 243 pounds, there is ample reason for
small heavyweights such as the 217-pound Holyfield to cower at the
sight of him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is, until the fighting starts. Once that happened
last weekend, no one passed the knowledge of such fears along to
the 214-pound Mavrovic. He stood up to the best Lewis could throw
without buckling or backing down. Mavrovic ended up with a
five-stitch cut on his chin and some scrapes and bruises on his
face, but his eyes were open at the end and his mind was clear
despite being hit by 219 of Lewis's power punches, including a
half-dozen right uppercuts that landed flush and did little damage.
</P>
<P>
   That Lewis is a physical specimen worthy of the NFL is obvious.
Unfortunately for him, he doesn't move as well as most people his
size in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   His large feet often trip over themselves when forced to pursue
or retreat.
</P>
<P>
   After a few rounds, his jab often goes unused, out of laziness
or general apathy, in favor of a clubbing right hand that gives him
all the grace of a man swinging a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   His chest, though chiseled, tends to heave after a half-dozen
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Lewis is a fearsome heavyweight who keeps
insisting that Holyfield is afraid of him, a claim that even
Lewis's promoter had a hard time making after the Mavrovic fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Evander was watching the fight tonight and saw
weaknesses in Lennox,'' said Dino Duva, who once promoted
Holyfield. ``Whatever it takes to get Evander to push King to make
the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   What is feared most by Lewis, Holyfield, and officials at both
HBO (which pays Lewis) and Showtime (which pays Holyfield) is that
each champion was so underwhelming in his most recent outing that
the public may have already lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   An angry HBO Sports senior vice president Lou DiBella said,
``It's obvious these guys can't get up for these kind of fights.
It's time to make Holyfield-Lewis before one of these guys loses a
fight they shouldn't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   As DiBella mumbled, Lewis sat with a bemused look on his face at
a postfight press grilling when he was asked what happened to his
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really make a statement tonight,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis may have been wrong there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's planned relicensing hearing was set back again last week
and a court fight appears to be brewing as early as Monday over the
battery of psychological tests he was given at Massachusetts
General Hospital. The tests were given at the insistence of the
Nevada State Athletic Commission, which said it would not restore
Tyson's license without an independent evaluation of his mental
state. At the time, the commission told Tyson's attorneys they
would need the results by Sept. 28, but in a letter written by Dr.
 &UR; Ronald Schouten  &LR; on Sept. 24 to commission doctor  &UR; Flip
Homansky &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Schouten said his understanding was that the results
were not due until Sept. 30. Regardless, they have yet to be
received because Tyson's lawyers are now trying to block the public
release of the evaluation. Schouten said in his letter that he
believed public release was ``unnecessary for the purpose of the
Commission's determination of his fitness to return to the ring ...
More importantly we believe this would be harmful to Mr. Tyson and
contrary to his best clinical interests.'' But when the lawyers
from the Nevada Attorney General's office said any such material
would become public record because the commission is a public
agency, Tyson agreed to submit the test results and evaluation. But
now his attorneys may seek a stay Sunday to argue the matter in
front of the Nevada Supreme Court. The consequence of this is that
a new Oct. 19 hearing date has been postponed and if enough time
passes Tyson would be unlikely to receive his license in time to
fight before the end of the year _ unless he leaves the country or
goes to a state that does not have a commission. But to leave the
country, Tyson would need the permission of Indiana Superior Court
Judge  &UR; Patricia Gifford &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who remains in control of his parole
status. Yet it is likely that Tyson will try to find some way to
fight by Dec. 31 because he recently made a deal with the Internal
Revenue Service for back taxes in which the IRS agreed not to seize
any of his personal property if he signed to fight before the end
of the year. While all this was swirling around Tyson, there were
two more troubling developments. This week Playboy will release an
obscenity-laden interview in which Tyson says of Holyfield ``I
wanted to kill him, bite him. I was just enraged and angry.'' He
goes on to say, ``My life is doomed the way it is.'' Earlier in the
week, the New York Post carried a story in which a photographer
claimed Tyson had to be restrained by bodyguards from going after
him when he tried to take his picture on a New York City street
only days before Tyson allegedly kicked a man and punched another
following a fender-bender accident in Maryland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
