<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMF-WORLDBANK-MEET-1S     10-03 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-WORLDBANK-MEET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: next week.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton will take the unusual step of taking part directly on
Monday in a crucial meeting of finance ministers and central
bankers from 22 countries. And on Tuesday, he will speak to the
entire IMF, which represents 182 countries, in his second major
speech on the world economy in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The president set the urgent tone of the meetings on Friday,
when he declared that the world was on a ``financial precipice.''
But Clinton, who last spring was resisting advice that he become
far more publicly involved in dealing with the world's financial
chaos, insisted that it was not too late to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to have a worldwide recession if those of us
that enjoy growth will take the initiative and move now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic initiative to stop the financial contagion may come
within days as the fund, the Treasury Department and Brazil's
finance minister, Pedro Malan, put the final touches on a package
of $30 billion or more to stabilize the Brazilian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin met with Malan at the Treasury on Friday, and there was
considerable speculation that the package could be announced as
soon as voting is completed on Sunday in Brazil's election. The
vote is expected to result in the re-election of President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso. Administration officials say they fear that a
financial meltdown in Brazil would take the rest of Latin America
and Mexico with it, and bring the crisis to the United States'
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the cacophony of competing ideas suggests that it
will be extraordinarily difficult to get agreement on a common
agenda from countries facing a varied array of problems _ deep
recession and mass unemployment in Southeast Asia, political
paralysis in Russia and Indonesia, huge bank failures in Japan, an
incipient currency crisis in Brazil, but continued prosperity in
Western Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, for instance, is insisting that there be no
backing away from a decade-long move toward freer and more open
financial markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese and Southeast Asians are talking about
``capital controls'' that would reimpose government regulation to
prevent investors from moving billions in short-term investments
from one country to another with a few taps on the computer
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The French, meanwhile, want to increase the power of the
committee that oversees the monetary fund, while Russia is
threatening to default on its loans unless it is quickly given
billions that the fund suspended when President Boris Yeltsin
dismissed his team of economic reformers and violated the terms of
his accord for Western aid.
</P>
<P>
   A senior fund official said last week that Russia's threats were
``a form of blackmail,'' but the enormous turbulence set off by the
Russian financial debacle last month gives real teeth to Russia's
threats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Rubin are hoping to formulate their own strategies
to calm the financial markets and keep the worst effects of the
recession from hitting American shores, where exports and corporate
profits are already badly affected.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate of those strategies would allow the fund to
begin pre-emptive strikes to bolster the finances of fundamentally
healthy economies where the global economic contagion seems likely
to hit next.
</P>
<P>
   Currently the fund intervenes with billions in emergency aid
only after disaster strikes and investors are fleeing. But by that
time, the country's currency is already under heavy attack, and
putting together a bailout can cost far more and often involves
austerity measures _ from budget cuts to sky-high interest rates _
that lead to soaring unemployment and political backlash.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal will first be debated by the Group
of Seven industrial nations and then, if it gathers much support,
by a meeting of 22 countries, including most of the major emerging
markets.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Japanese official said Saturday that the
president's plan ``seems aimed mostly at Latin America'' and
probably would ``not meet a lot of enthusiasm in Europe and Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, meanwhile, are debating how to respond to calls
from Washington for a lowering of interest rates, a step Japan and
the United States have already taken, though with the most modest
of reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brown, Britain's finance minister, hinted late last week
that London might follow suit. But Germany, traditionally far more
concerned about inflation, has declined to go along. The German
government is playing an unusually small role here as its
Chancellor-elect, Gerhard Schroeder, prepares to assemble an
economic team.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast Asian countries _ which only five years ago were
the subject of a much-discussed World Bank study called ``The East
Asian Miracle'' _ arrived here in shock and confusion about what to
do next. The first country to be hit by trouble, Thailand, is mired
in difficulties, but looks good in comparison to most of the
region's other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia is suffering economic turmoil, and Indonesia's economy
is plunging so deeply into recession that the monetary fund is
backing away from many of its demands on its government.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my country,'' an Indonesian said during a
question-and-answer period at the opening session here, ``IMF means
I'm Finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
