<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-FLOJO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED SENDS RUMORS FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Why did rumors of banned drug use follow Florence Griffith
Joyner to her untimely death last month? Because no woman has come
close to the astounding marks she set during three months in 1988.
Flo-Jo ran the 100 in 10.49 in a qualifying heat in 98-degree
weather at the Olympic trials. Nobody has broken 10.60 since. She
ran 21.34 in the 200 at Seoul. Nobody has broken 21.70 since.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing raises eyebrows like record performances that come from
athletes (such as Irish swimmer Michelle Smith) who've never been
at that level. That's the insidious thing about doping: It calls
every extraordinary feat into question. Nobody said a word about
drugs when US swimmer Mary T. Meagher, in one week in 1981, set two
amazing butterfly records, both of which still stand. If she did it
today, Meagher would be under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   How expansive _ and expensive _ have the Winter Games become?
Salt Lake City recently unveiled a ``lean'' budget of $1.4 billion
for 2002. That's $400 million more than Nagano spent this year and
only $300 million less than Atlanta spent on the larger Summer
Games in 1996. Much of it is a matter of accounting: Nagano didn't
factor in nearly $500 million in construction costs that were
covered by the Japanese government. But Salt Lake's facilities
aren't nearly as lavish as Nagano's _ no Big Hats or M-Waves or
Aqua Wings _ and the figure skating arena (home of the Jazz) and
main stadium (at the University of Utah) were already built. Though
the Games are more than three years away, most of the venues are
already up and running. Still in progress are the second hockey
arena (in Provo), the large ski jump, the biathlon/cross-country
area and the athletes' village ... It won't make up for Nagano, but
 &UR; Todd Eldredge  &LR; got some satisfaction by beating Olympic skating
champ  &UR; Ilya Kulik  &LR; head-to-head at the recent Grand Slam event in
South Carolina.  &UR; Michelle Kwan  &LR; defeated  &UR; Maria Butyrskaya  &LR; for the
women's title in the top-drawer pro-am, which was scored by
international judges. Eldredge and Kulik are having at each other
this weekend in a Daytona Beach pro-am, while Kwan faces  &UR; Nicole
Bobek  &LR; and  &UR; Surya Bonaly &LR; . The blending of Olympic eligibles and
ineligibles, though, is baffling for skating fans. Kwan, Kulik, and
Eldredge, who are all still eligible (i.e. non-professional), are
competing in the US Pro classic later this month ... Next challenge
for US Olympic women's ice hockey coach  &UR; Ben Smith  &LR; will be
directing the makeshift men's team at next month's special world
relegation pool tournament in Austria. The Yanks, who ended up a
pathetic 12th in this year's global championships, have to beat the
likes of Kazakhstan, Austria, and Estonia to stay in the A pool for
next year. Smith, who was just named USOC coach of the year for his
gold-medal job in Nagano and accepted the William French Award last
night from the Boston University Athletic Hall of Fame, has plenty
of international men's experience: He was Olympic assistant in 1988
and national team assistant in 1987 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Though their top ticket prices will be higher than Atlanta's,
the Sydney organizers say they'll keep the average lower with
plenty of cheap seats. Ten thousand tickets to the opening
ceremonies will go for $61; Atlanta's lowest price was $212.
Seventy percent of all tickets will be offered for less than $35
and some (even in gymnastics) for less than $6. The reason: to
preserve domestic tranquility. Three-quarters of the tickets are
going to Australians ... Though they've technically been at war for
45 years, North and South Korea could compete as one country in
Sydney. The South has been pushing the idea hard and the
International Olympic Committee is on board. What the isolationist
North will do is anyone's guess. The two countries formed joint
soccer and table tennis teams earlier in the decade but have gone
their own ways since ...  &UR; Picabo Street  &LR; says she still has
nightmares about her horrific post-Olympic crash that tore up her
right knee and broke her left leg. ``I see it in my head over and
over,'' she says. ``I live it over and over.'' Street is due back
on slopes next month but won't be competing at all this season.
``I'm coming out of a hole,'' she says. ``I'll ski for the winter,
then decide what's next.'' ... Encouraging start for Winchester
bobsledder  &UR; Jim Herberich &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the two-man title (with  &UR; Paul
Wise &LR; ) at the recent world push championships in Monte Carlo. The
World Cup season starts next month in Calgary ... New but familiar
face in the US luge camp belongs to  &UR; Clay Ives &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a two-time
Olympian for Canada who just received dual citizenship and is
looking to switch. The reason: better funding from the Yanks. Until
he qualifies for the national team, though, Ives will be on his own
dollar ... High hopes for the US cyclists at this week's world road
championships in the Netherlands. Best chances ride with  &UR; Bobby
Julich &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was third in the Tour de France, and  &UR; Dede
Demet &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has won two medals. Also on the squad is former champ
 &UR; Lance Armstrong &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has bounced back from testicular cancer.
The Americans won a lone bronze (by  &UR; Cheri Elliott  &LR; in the women's
downhill) at the recent world mountain biking event in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Add sailing to the list of Olympic sports (e.g. rowing and
boxing) that have had to trim numbers to accommodate new additions
(e.g. triathlon and trampolining) to the Sydney program. With the
entries reduced from 450 to 400, countries (except for host
Australia) now have to qualify through world regattas. Mixed
results so far for the Americans, who've earned slots in the
Soling, 49er, Laser, and men's 470 classes but missed out this year
in Finn, Europe, Star, and women's 470. They'll try to qualify this
fall for Mistral and Tornado. Everybody gets three chances ...
Modest expectations for the US riders at the ongoing world
equestrian games in Rome. The Americans, who won two medals last
time, have already missed the podium in team dressage. New
Englanders on the squad include  &UR; Shelly Francis  &LR; (Woodstock, Vt.)
in dressage and  &UR; Kerry Millikin  &LR; (Westport, Mass.) and  &UR; Cindy
Collier  &LR; (Newtown, Conn.) in eventing ... Three members of the US
Olympic men's volleyball team that won the historic triple crown
(1984 Olympics, 1985 World Cup, 1986 World Championships) will be
inducted into the Hall of Fame in Holyoke this month:  &UR; Steve
Timmons &LR; , &UR; Dusty Dvorak &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Craig Buck  &LR; will be joined by  &UR; Paula
Weishoff &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who played on three US Olympic women's squads and won
medals in 1984 and 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
