</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chargers: Stay out of our room
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The San Diego Chargers apparently haven't caught
baseball fever. The NFL club put up a chain and padlocks across the
doors to its locker room at Qualcomm Stadium this weekend, refusing
to let the Padres to use it as a media interview area. Instead, the
Padres are using the less spacious San Diego State locker room to
handle the media crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Padres GM Kevin Towers also took a shot at the Chargers, blaming
them in part for the chewed-up field at Qualcomm Stadium. ``If
there's a scheduling problem with the Chargers, they take
precedence over us. That's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   `The King' returns
</P>
<P>
   ``The King,'' as Jim Leyritz is known around the Padres
clubhouse, got the start at first base Saturday night. Not only had
Leyritz driven in three of the Padres' six runs in the opening two
games, but he provided a right-handed bat against lefty starter
Mike Hampton, and the swing of Stone Mountain native Wally Joyner,
the regular first baseman, is impaired by acute tendinitis in his
left biceps.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz picks up another start this afternoon, this time behind
the plate, as the personal catcher for ex-Yankees teammate and Game
4 pitcher Sterling Hitchcock, who will go against the Astros Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Money games
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros have to deal with Johnson ($6 million this
year) after the season, he's their only everyday player or starting
pitcher facing free agency. The Padres are a totally different
story. They have eight potential free agents, including key players
like pitcher Kevin Brown ($4.8 million), third baseman Ken Caminiti
($3.1 million), outfielder Steve Finley ($3.4 million), catcher
Carlos Hernandez ($650,000) and Joyner ($3.7 million).
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   Walter Cronkite, a straight shooter in his years as CBS News
anchor, threw out the ceremonial first pitch before Game 3. ...
Hitters have been coming to the plate with their theme song blaring
over the stadium PA system for years. Now, Padres closer Trevor
Hoffman has jumped into the act with AC/DC's ``Hells Bells''
playing when he trots in from the bullpen. ... How good are Hoffman
and the Padres at closing out games? During the last two-plus
seasons, they're 174-0 in the regular season when leading after the
eighth inning, including an 85-0 record in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
