<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winning fuels Padres' dreams of new home
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It's that time of year when politics and baseball
step deeper into the media spotlight. Campaigns and playoff
baseball. Rare is it that the two feed off each other, but this
fall finds the Padres on the stump as they seek to play themselves
into the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   By all reports, the future of baseball in San Diego likely rests
with a November referendum on whether to build a downtown ballpark.
If Proposition C meets with the locals favor, Padres' owner John
Moores will get the park he needs to compete with wealthier,
corporate-backed clubs up the interstate in Los Angeles (Fox) and
Anaheim (Disney). If not, the Padres might be headed for northern
Virginia or some other interested outpost.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Padres couldn't have gotten hot at a more
opportune time.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could they have opened their wallets wide enough to buy the
ad campaign being fueled by their winning baseball. A record crowd
in excess of 64,000 showed up at Qualcomm Stadium for Game 3 of the
NL Division Series Saturday night. And the Padres are hoping with
every postseason win comes more votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to help if we keep winning, of course,'' said
Padres outfielder Greg Vaughn. ``Everybody recognizes that. We want
it, yeah. Hopefully, if we play well it'll happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I'm not thinking of a new stadium when I'm
playing. Who knows if I'll be here when it's done. Or who even
knows if I'll be here next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are marketing their plan for a downtown stadium on
the promise of ``family-friendly'' restaurants and shops being
drawn to a trendy Ballpark District. Local neighborhood groups
oppose the 26-block redevelopment project, largely because
residents will be displaced and their contention that any economic
stimulus will be felt by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how the vote will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Padres all speak in favor of a new park. But
pitching ace Kevin Brown is also familiar with what happens when an
owner doesn't get his way. Brown was a member of the world
championship Florida Marlins that were broken up after last season
when south Florida politicians refused to help team owner Wayne
Huizenga build a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody realizes the issue,'' Brown said. ``But I can tell
you, it's not why I walk on the field. I play for my teammates, for
personal pride. A stadium vote is not a driving force. That's out
of my control.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
