<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funk's 1-shot lead looks big to rivals
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ According to the leaderboard, Fred Funk has
a mere one-shot lead at 18-under-par 198 in the Buick Challenge as
he tries to win today for the second time in four years at Callaway
Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   According to PGA Tour habits, that should mean that players such
as Bill Glasson (17 under), J.L. Lewis (15 under) or Steve
Elkington and Steve Flesch (14 under) have a reasonable chance of
catching Funk.
</P>
<P>
   According to local knowledge, none of that stuff matters. His
competitors are speaking as through the place should be called
Funkaway Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all just playing to see who gets second place,''
Glasson said after moving into apparent contention with a 65.
``Honestly, I don't think we'll be able to catch Fred. It's like
it's his home field and the rest of us are on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you could have some hope, said David Duval, who shot a 70
and dropped six shots off the pace, ``if you didn't know Fred was
going to shoot 4 or 5 under every time he plays here.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Funk, as much as he appreciates the praise, he
sensed someone trying to playfully lull him into complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a smokescreen,'' Funk, a Ponte Vedra, Fla.,
resident, said after a 68 that revised the 54-hole tournament
record at 18-under, a shot less than Davis Love III managed last
year. ``There's not one person out here that backs up or concedes
anything to anybody. ... It's great that he (Glasson) thinks that,
but all those guys at 12 or 13 under have a chance if any of the
leaders does a fold job. I need to keep making birdies. ... Billy
already caught me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk, a winner in July at the Deposit Guaranty Classic, has
either owned or shared the lead since Thursday, when he and Jim
Carter shot 63s. Funk led by as many as four shots Saturday, making
seven birdies against three bogeys and nearly hitting exactly his
third-round scoring average of 68.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I made seven birdies,'' he said, ``I made some
boo-boos.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his 72-hole record of 21 under par registered last year,
defending champion Davis Love III said Saturday, ``I think it's in
jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, of Briarcliff, Texas, a 38-year-old Nike Tour graduate
from last year, is 156th on the money list ($142,788) and has
missed the cut in 16 of 28 events.
</P>
<P>
   Carter (69) and Neal Lancaster (66) are at 13-under 203,
followed by Duval and D.A. Weibring (71) at 12 under. Atlanta's
Billy Andrade (67) is seven shots back at 11 under along with Texas
Open winner Hal Sutton (67) and J.P. Hayes (67).
</P>
<P>
   Both Elkington (66) and Glasson have overcome serious medical
problems to contend. Glasson is in only his 10th event of the year
after a third elbow operation. Elkington had two bouts of viral
meningitis this year and sinus problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four knee (operations), three elbows, a few back problems,
sinus, a little skin cancer _ you name it,'' Glasson said. ``I had
kind of a tough night. I think I'm passing around a little flu bug.
I'll try not to breathe on you too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he or anyone else can breathe down Funk's neck today is
the real issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
