<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's Andrade misses mark in Buick tour
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Five dollars short of making the Tour
Championship last year, Atlanta resident Billy Andrade has taken
his current top 30 push to Callaway Gardens and the Buick
Challenge. A member at East Lake Golf Club, which hosts the Tour
Championship Oct. 29-Nov. 1, Andrade stands 41st on the money list
and requires some high finishes over these next four events.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the quest still lives. Andrade shot a second straight 67
Saturday to move to 11-under-par 205. Perhaps not in position to
snare another's winner's check after last month's surprise victory
at the Canadian Open -- Fred Funk has seven shots on him -- but
second place today earns $162,000 and Andrade also likes the venues
the next two weeks at Kingsmill and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing 31st last year and missing the exclusive $4
million event, the 34-year-old Andrade is pumped for a change in
the scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ''After I won (at Canada last month), my thought process was,
'Why don't I knock somebody out this time?''' Andrade said. ''Being
an East Lake member and living in Atlanta, it would be a dream come
true to play in the Tour Championship there.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade ignited his game Friday with a closing 30 on the back
nine for a 67, then came out Saturday and birdied his first four
holes. With a third-round front nine of 32, Andrade had gone
10-under par for the 18-hole stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade has earned $655,431 and probably needs about $925,000 to
make the top 30 list and qualify for the Tour Championship at East
Lake Oct. 29-Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a million dollars is a good goal,'' Andrade said. ''I
think that would be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Pooped Kuchar ready for break
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech amateur Matt Kuchar struggled to a 73 Saturday to
stand at 4-under 212, attributing his inconsistent play mostly to
burnout from trying to balance his schoolwork and college
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really not playing well,'' he said. ''I've been playing
with my 'C' game for a month now. I've got enough for one more day.
I'll probably use everything tomorrow.'' After a solid 67 Friday to
make the cut, Kuchar made bogeys at 15,16 and 17, then birdied 18.
Tired or not, Kuchar led a junior clinic a few hours after his
round. . .Defending champion Davis Love said he was losing
concentration at times Saturday during a 2-under 70 that put him at
7-under. ''I'm following up a bad shot with another bad shot,''
Love said. ''Some things seem to be bothering me that don't usually
bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Today's final round will be televised live from 1-4 p.m. on
ESPN. Players will play off the No. 1 and the No. 10 tees in
threesomes. . . . Glen Day shot a 7-under 65 Saturday to move to
10-under, but easily could have been better. He missed a 3-footer
for par at the 17th and another for birdie at the 18th. . . .
Columbus resident Larry Mize shot a 67 and is at 8-under. .
.Pronouncing his play as ''terrible,'' David Duval (70) started
Saturday with a double-bogey on the first hole, three birdies, then
two bogeys. ''I'm not in this golf tournament anymore,'' said the
tour's leading moneywinner.. . Former Marietta resident Bob Tway
(69) is at 9-under, three shots ahead of former Georgia player
Franklin Langham (72).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
