</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McLaughlin wins, barely
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ With nothing to lose, Mike McLaughlin defied
the odds Saturday and won the Busch Grand National Bumper To Bumper
Auto Parts 300, running the final 94 laps under green at Charlotte
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin won it riding away, taking the checkered flag 24.074
seconds ahead of Matt Kenseth. And after rolling into victory lane,
he climbed atop his Monte Carlo and executed a swan dive into the
arms of his pit crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys in the pits won it,'' McLaughlin said. ``I don't know
how we made it on fuel. I even questioned them when they left me
out there for track position. They had a different strategy (than I
did) and it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth could hardly believe it. When he made his final stop, he
asked his crew if McLaughlin could go all the way without stopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know what they told me? He said, `No way. He'll be 25 laps
short of making it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
