<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tracking down battle for fifth in Winston Cup
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ With the Winston Cup championship all but
decided between Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin, eyes have turned to
the battle for fifth place in the Winston Cup standings, where only
46 points separate Bobby Labonte, Jeremy Mayfield and Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte holds the position, 40 points ahead of Mayfield, who
leads Jeff Burton by six. ``This really is a big race, a
springboard for all of us,'' said Mayfield, who has four top 10
finishes in the last six races. ``We've been right in the middle of
things all year, from leading the points (12 races ago at Pocono)
to where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's run since Pocono has been one of inconsistency. He
finished 18th, 30th, 18th, 42nd and 31st after falling from the
lead, and has gone seventh, eighth, 20th, fifth, 22nd and third in
the last six races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked over and there and seen the Winston Cup
championship ring on Rusty's finger,'' Mayfield said. ``I know what
it means. I think we can win Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   This track, however, hasn't been good to Mayfield. In four fall
outings here, his best finish is 27th, a year ago. Labonte's best
is a second last year and Burton's was 11th two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be good,'' Mayfield said. ``So is Rusty
(Wallace). We're working together like we always have. We always
qualify decent and run somewhere toward the front until something
happens, but we've learned a lot about Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're been working on getting both cars in the top five and
keeping them there in the points. Rusty is fourth and I think we've
got a good shot at getting there before the season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace already has discovered something that will help him. A
broken spark plug wire. Those are the kind of things that hindered
him earlier when he was No. 1 on the points list. A blown engine at
Bristol, a wreck California and another engine failure at Pocono,
which, ironically, came on the day Mayfield moved to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me the other day if it was my turn, like Ricky
(Rudd) to extend my streak,'' Wallace said. ``I told 'em I've been
saying that all year long. I hope it. We keep knocking on the door.
Now, we need to knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The darkhorse may be Bobby Labonte. He was second here a year
ago and starts on the outside of the second row today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're run good at Charlotte time and time again it seems
like,'' Labonte said. ``If we finish, we finish good. What we raced
at Charlotte two or three years ago is similar to what we race
there today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
