<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SENIORTENNIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caswell-Herr in Nuveen Tour final
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS AND CHART
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Connors brought out the crowd Saturday
afternoon, and a pair of local heroes, Howard Herr and Ned Caswell,
sent the fans away happy by advancing to the doubles final of the
BTI Champions event at Atlanta Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Connors defeated Gene Mayer 6-0, 6-4 in the opening match before
a crowd of 2,162, setting up a 1 p.m. final today against the
winner of the late Mats Wilander-Mikael Pernfors match.
</P>
<P>
   Connors has won four of the seven Nuveen Tour events he's
entered this year, and two of his failures came after he withdrew
because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm hitting as well as I ever have,'' said Connors,
who is coming off a victory over John McEnroe in last week's final
in Dallas. ``Even though tennis isn't the most important thing in
my life anymore, it's still kind of what I do and as long as I do
I'm going to do it the absolute best that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's more intriguing match was the 6-3, 6-4 victory of
Herr and Caswell over second-seeded Gene Mayer and Mansour Bahrami
in the doubles semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Herr, the tennis director at the Falls of Autry Mill in
Alpharetta, and Caswell, a Roswell native who is a teaching pro in
Chattanooga, won a local qualifying tournament last month to get in
as wildcards. They beat Andres Gomez and Tim Wilkison in the first
round Thursday, and each had a small but vocal band of local
followers on hand Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get to play week in and week out, so if we're ever
going to win one of these, it's got to be now,'' Caswell said.
``We're not playing just to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Caswell and Herr each played for a few years on the ATP Tour.
Each is a two-time national men's 30-and-over clay court singles
champion, and Caswell has won the national 30 clays six straight
times in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've played at that level _ I mean Ned's beaten Pete
Sampras _ you go out there ready to play,'' Herr said. ``That
doesn't mean you think you're gonna win, but we know we can play
with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Caswell, ``We definitely didn't come in thinking we had no
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, a two-time former French Open doubles champion, and
Bahrami, who made the 1989 French doubles final, were more
light-hearted about the match, though it was clear they didn't want
to lose. Bahrami clowned with the crowd, and Caswell said it was a
distraction but didn't annoy him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've if he'd aced me with that underhand serve,''
Caswell said. ``I didn't see that coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Herr and Caswell are the second local qualifiers ever to make a
Nuveen Tour doubles final. The others are Mike Fedderly and Greg
Nuehart. No local qualifiers have ever won in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
