<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HURRICANE-RELIEF-4     10-03 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HURRICANE-RELIEF-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TIME OF NEED, UNITY PULSES TO A LATIN BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They came from all over Latin New York, looking to
glimpse a star, to dance, to help.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians obliged by giving speeches, as did radio deejays and
actors _ Jimmy Smits showed up, mingled with the crowd and talked
about his family. Musicians played, and by the end of the day,
``Ayuda a Los Pueblos'' (Help for the Towns) at Hostos Community
College in the Bronx had collected nearly $500,000 for the Hispanic
Federation to help residents of Puerto Rico and the Dominican
Republic still reeling from Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came back from the Dominican Republic, and between the
airport and Santo Domingo, there isn't a tree standing,'' said
Guillermo Linares, the city councilman from Washington Heights.
``We traveled in helicopter, and it's total destruction. When
people heard the helicopter coming, they ran to us thinking it's
food.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the audience echoed his observations. Nearly everyone
had a friend or relative on the islands, and had heard about the
shortages of water and food, the utter devastation.
</P>
<P>
   So a string of performers from New York and the Caribbean came
to sing and play for the crowd, which totaled about 3,000. The
Barrio Boyzz shuffled and sang, and by the time salsa legend Celia
Cruz showed up, people were ready for her form of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a party,'' said Milly Quezada, a merengue singer.
``First we have all these people, Puerto Ricans and Dominicans
coming together.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not a sad people. We're here to maintain solidarity
with the people in the islands, earn some money to help them. But
we're also here to help people have a good time. There's enough
misery around.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Miranda, the event's producer and the outgoing president of
the Hispanic Federation, said work began six days ago. ``We were
here at 3:30 a.m. working,'' he said. ``But it's for the good.
There are 100,000 people in need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here all share a sense of belonging,'' he said.
``The great thing about being bicultural is that you can love the
United States and love where you come from also.''
</P>
<P>
   As the string of performers filed on and off, they were met
backstage by reporters and friends. Radio and television crews were
interviewing the musicians and politicians, and the Hispanic
Federation was showing off the large checks that had been brought
by corporations. Anheuser-Busch, for example, gave $25,000;
Heineken gave $50,000. Money was also raised by the $10 admission
charge, and by a telethon that was part of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Louie Marrero, one of the Barrio Boyzz, looked a bit awestruck.
``It's an honor to perform,'' he said. ``We like to give back to
the community. Puerto Rican, Dominican, it doesn't matter, we're
all Latinos, and we thank God that we're all able to be responsible
and that we can help make a difference.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jimmy Smits was answering questions, then he headed out to talk
to the people outside, standing in line, waiting to pay their money
to enter. ``I have an aunt in Puerto Rico who lost part of her
house,'' Smits said. ``And where my family lives the phones were
out. We all have stories like that, and people are suffering.
That's why I'm here, to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the audience, people were dancing. They danced to
Fulanito, a local merengue group, and they danced to Oro Solido,
which performed its hit ``Baile de Beeper.'' They danced to Frankie
Negron, a young salsa singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to help,'' said Josefina Salas, who had come to the
show from her home a few blocks away with her sister. ``We donated
at the door, but this is a really good deal, lots of music.'' Ms.
Salas was dancing. ``But we have to be happy. It's a lot worse for
them there than it is for us, and we have to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose ``El Canario'' Alberto and his salsa orchestra showed up to
play, and Johnny Pacheco came out and played flute with them.
Alberto and Pacheco were running through Pacheco's hits from the
1970s and a mother and daughter were running through their dance
routines to the music.
</P>
<P>
   Out came Celia Cruz, to a standing ovation, to sing with
Alberto's orchestra. Dominicans danced to a Cuban woman singing a
Puerto Rican form of salsa played by the Dominican Alberto, just as
Puerto Ricans had danced to merengue, from the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez said he saw a lot of good in the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most obvious thing about this is that government
organizations can't make up for all the destruction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if we can rebuild some houses, send some generators and
some food, that's great. But just as importantly, to bring
communities together, the Puerto Rican and Dominicans that
sometimes are separated by some nuances that aren't always
important. And that unity is a sight to see. Things like this bring
out the best in people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
