<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RANGERS, ONE POSTSEASON SHOWER NOT ENOUGH ANYMORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Their champagne-stained duds haven't even
come back from the dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   And already, the Texas Rangers are done. Flattened like
roadkill. Whisked from the American League playoffs as if they
never belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work so hard during the year, for 181 days,'' said a
somber general manager Doug Melvin, ``and then the playoffs seem to
go by so fast. It just seemed like we didn't even have a chance to
enjoy the victories we had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, though, we've just got to find a way not to play the
Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad idea, if a team can get away with it. For the second
time in three seasons, the Rangers were chased from baseball's
postseason by a Yankees team that pitched better, hit better and,
maybe more than anything, handled the bright lights of the playoffs
better.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it appears to be hard to hit when you've got a
baseball-sized lump in your throat.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with three nights of capable, if not dazzling, pitching
of their own, the Rangers couldn't overcome their futilities with
the bat. They never adjusted to umpires' roving strike zones. They
never really grasped what Yankee pitchers were doing to get them
out.
</P>
<P>
   They waved at baiting pitches inches out of the strike zone. And
when Yankee pitchers made the rare mistake, the Rangers only fouled
it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just feels bad,'' club president Tom Schieffer said in a
silent Rangers clubhouse Friday night. ``We've got a good team. I
really thought we had a chance to beat the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we just couldn't get it done. It's a shame, but I feel
like we just didn't get a chance to enjoy the good season we had
for very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast the attitudes. When the Rangers clinched the American
League West on Sept. 25, a rowdy, champagne-hosing celebration
ensued. Their goal, dating to spring training, had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Melvin admitted, it might be time to up the ante.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a reputation as a team that's going to be in
the postseason just about every year, and then build on that,'' he
said. ``Atlanta, Cleveland _ they pretty well have that reputation,
and that's what we want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it gets disappointing to be here, to be in the playoffs,
and not move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the Rangers appeared awed by playing the Yankees will remain
a mystery. Maybe it was the three-hour din that serenaded them at
historic Yankee Stadium. Maybe it was the anticipation of facing
big-name starters David Wells, Andy Pettitte and David Cone
back-to-back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said, ``it was
kind of weird, just the way things transpired, the way we were
dominated offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you can't really explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight being razor sharp, it would be easy to suggest, upon
further review, the Rangers would have been better off trying to
catch the Cleveland Indians in the final week and thus avoid the
Yankees in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But this team had six months to pass the Indians. It responded
with inconsistency. While manager Johnny Oates preached the virtues
of maintaining a steady keel, the Rangers couldn't stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the fire in the team's belly seemed to come from
pitchers Todd Stottlemyre and Rick Helling, from the newcomer
Clayton and from the club's self-appointed sheriff, Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need more of it. They already have enough Eagle
Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to take this ballclub we have now from Day 1,'' said
Melvin, who wheeled the deals that brought Stottlemyre, Clayton,
Todd Zeile and Esteban Loaiza. ``There's no doubt we would have
been much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the remorse, management can't let what happened in
three nights against the Yankees sway the master plan. Two years
ago, when the Rangers bullpen couldn't slam the playoff door
against the Yanks, management made the decision its money would be
best spent on acquiring a closer. That's how John Wetteland became
a Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us, though, argued the money would be better spent on
trying to lure Texas-born starting pitcher Roger Clemens. The
Rangers, instead, went after Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go out after what happened here,'' Melvin agreed,
``and think that we have to trade pitching for hitting, or
something stupid like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The club won't overreact, Melvin promised.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he assured, it will learn from what happened here
during these three Yankee-dominated nights.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to wake up the Eagle Scouts. From here on, one
champagne shower will not be enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
