<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLORADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 15 COLORADO FINALLY SUBDUES OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ When Colorado's Marcus Washington scored on an
interception return with roughly 10 minutes remaining Saturday, the
faint of heart among the home crowd recognized the cue.
</P>
<P>
   They were soon marching out of Memorial Stadium and heading down
the block toward O'Connell's, a renowned local oasis where postgame
sorrows can be properly washed away.
</P>
<P>
   They missed a great finish.
</P>
<P>
   Thundering improbably down the stretch, Oklahoma (2-2, 0-1)
nearly pinned 15th-ranked Colorado (5-0, 2-0) to the mat before
astonished remnants of the original audience of 71,217. Finally,
the Buffaloes survived a 27-25 scare.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the man who ignited it _ sophomore walk-on Patrick
Fletcher _ uttered an abject apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to apologize to my coaches and teammates,'' said
Fletcher, whose interception Washington carried 40 yards for a
27-12 Colorado lead with 10:17 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope,'' said Fletcher, choking back tears, ``that they
don't lose faith in me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely. Exactly 61 seconds after the interception,
De'Mond Parker (26 carries, 134 yards) ripped off a 49-yard scoring
run, and the Sooners' deficit was cut to nine. It stayed there, as
an attempted two-point conversion failed.
</P>
<P>
   But Fletcher, who threw for 130 yards in 10 minutes, was soon
back. Colorado's Mike Moschetti (13-of-25 186 yards, one
interception), drove the Buffaloes to the Sooners' 2-yard line, but
was pressured by Ontei Jones and threw a weak ball toward the goal
line that was intercepted by OU's Corey Ivy at the 2.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing out of his end zone, Fletcher threw for a first down,
then found Jarrail Jackson for 42 yards. When that threat ended in
a missed field goal attempt, OU seemed doomed. But the Sooners got
the ball back at their 31 with 1:41 remaining, and cut it to 27-25
in 36 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher threw first to Parker for 49, then to tight end Jason
Freeman for 25 yards and the score.
</P>
<P>
   The extra-point kick left OU in position to pull of a miracle,
but Colorado covered the ensuing onside kick and ran out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the win,'' Colorado coach Rick Neuheisel
said. ``Unfortunately, it came with a price _ we lost (wide
receiver) Cedric Cormier for the year with an ACL (anterior
cruciate ligament) injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the game, we gave up some big plays because we ran out
of gas because of the humidity. Unfortunately, we were unable to
deliver that knockout punch when we had the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Buffaloes stretched their record to 7-0-1
against the Sooners since 1989, getting three touchdown passes from
Moschetti and 135 yards on the ground from Marlon Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   OU coach John Blake lamented ``the little things, like missed
field goals and extra points _ that's what beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners missed two field-goal attempts, and each team missed
a 35-yard extra-point kick after a celebration penalty. The
Buffaloes also attempted a fake punt in which punter Nick Pietsch
threw the ball when no one was looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called a fake punt, but they lined up in a fake punt
defense,'' Neuheisel said. ``We called off the play and everyone
got the call but the punter.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the afternoon, Fletcher said, ``I thought we were
going to win _ I just wish I hadn't thrown that (interception).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
