<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPING THEY CAN BREAK WINGS' TITLE HOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This might indeed be the Wing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manger Bob Gainey said the task of taking down the
two-time Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings might be so tough
that no team _ even his super-charged roster _ can do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen this in the past where a team has won so
consistently and become so competitive that it took the entire
league to beat it. And I believe Detroit is that way,'' Gainey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that a team like Detroit, a repeat champion,
becomes such a target for every team, that it faces a higher level
of competition every night. And that can wear on a team over an
82-game season.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure, though. With that season scheduled to
begin Saturday night against Buffalo, the Stars are leading the
NHL's push to clip the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   With Detroit going for the first three-peat since the New York
Islanders won four consecutive Stanley Cups from 1980-84 and the
Stars holding the best regular-season record in the NHL the past
two seasons, the Red Wings-Stars axis could decide the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cup could go through Detroit or Dallas or Colorado,''
Phoenix Coyotes general manager Bobby Smith said. ``Dallas has
really improved a great deal in the last two years, so you have to
say they're right up there with \RDetroit\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor takes it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as last season was concerned, yeah, I think the winner
of our series with \RDetroit\S was going to win the Cup,'' he said.
``No disrespect toward Washington, but I think it came down to that
\RWestern Conference finals\S series and we both probably knew
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock maintains a healthy respect for the
Red Wings and said the secret to their success is one that any team
in the league can learn from and even imitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have, more than anything, is a great commitment to
one another and a great commitment to the organization and their
coach,'' Hitchcock said. ``You can see it in their team, especially
at times when the pressure is the highest, they turn inside and
find strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Wings forward Darren McCarty said that helped carry the team
through Stanley Cup hangover last season and should help Detroit as
they pursue a three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to question our team about whether we're going
to be hungry or going to want to play,'' McCarty said. ``We know
what it's like to win. We know what it's like not to win. We want
to keep this winning feeling going.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the league is hoping to find that same strength.
While the Stars have loaded their roster with free-agent talent,
others have taken one or two choice free agents in hopes of
bringing the right element into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Flyers have been trying to put together their
puzzle since being swept by the Red Wings in the 1997 Finals. This
season, the Flyers have reunited goalie John Vanbiesbrouck with
coach Roger Nielsen in hopes of getting a consistent defensive
performance. If the Flyers can do that, and get consistent offense
from Eric Lindros and John LeClair, they may have greater strength
than the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Capitals have added veteran talent to a hot young
goalie in Olaf Kolzig in hopes of proving last season's run to the
Finals wasn't a fluke. The Colorado Avalanche is trying to piece
together its broken dynasty-to-be, hiring rookie NHL coach Bob
Hartley. The Chicago Blackhawks finally spent some money in
acquiring center Doug Gilmour \Rthree years, $18 million\S. The
Toronto Maple Leafs bought goalie Curtis Joseph. The New York
Rangers upped their salaries in the hopes of keeping together a
team that greatly underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there was improvement throughout the NHL and everyone
is trying to take down the Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams have won one. Some outstanding teams have won two
in a row. Very few have won three,'' Red Wings captain Steve
Yzerman said. ``It's a difficult thing to do because everybody's
got to stay healthy, and pucks bounce a lot of strange ways. You
can't control everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have done everything they can to control those
bounces, from hiring sniper Brett Hull for three years at $17
million to buying tough guy Brent Severyn for $425,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to face them sooner or later as far, as I'm
concerned,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``We're thinking
about what we need to do to beat them, whether we can get the home
ice. I don't want to get ahead of ourselves and I don't even like
talking about them, but, yeah, we think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, players and management won't go so far as to say the
Stars have been built to beat the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not specifically,'' Gainey said. ``Our team has been a pretty
good team throughout two seasons, but we had areas that were
exposed in the playoffs. We dedicated our attention to those
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   It's time to see if that ``dedication'' pays off.
Stars vs. Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   Key scoring categories for 1997-98 regular season:
</P>
<P>
   Stars(rank) Category Red Wings(rank)
</P>
<P>
   49-22-11(1st) Record 44-23-15(3rd)
</P>
<P>
   242(T3rd) Goals for 250(2nd)
</P>
<P>
   167(2nd) Goals against 196(7th)
</P>
<P>
   20.0%(1st) Power play 17.6%(6th)
</P>
<P>
   88.0%(2nd) Penalty kill 86.4%(9th)
</P>
<P>
   .911(6th) Goaltender Save % .909(T10th)
</P>
</TEXT>
