<HEADLINE>
A MEMORABLE OVERTIME VICTORY FOR COACH'S HOME DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM N. WALLACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fordham's first home game for its new head coach, Ken
O'Keefe, was a memorable one Saturday as it defeated Princeton,
20-17. The winning points were scored on a 38-yard field goal by
the obscure freshman kicker Brian Colsant that ended the Rams'
first possession in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-yard field goal by Colsant, his first such attempt for the
Rams, had tied the game with 1 minute 37 seconds remaining in the
fourth quarter. Princeton had outplayed Fordham, thanks to its
defense, through three quarters, and the Rams gained only 65 yards
in the first half. The Tiger defenders, led by end David Ferrara,
had sacked Fordham quarterback Steve O'Hare 10 times.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the overtime rules, each team takes turns attempting to
score beginning 25 yards from the goal line. The turns cease when
one team fails to match the other's score. Princeton's first turn,
after Colsant's second field goal, ended, as did the game, when
Fordham safety Jon Piela intercepted a pass by John Burnham, the
Tigers' quarterback.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the second overtime game for each team. Princeton (1-2)
lost at Lehigh, 31-24, and Fordham (2-2) lost at Towson, 35-34,
both last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's defeat was the sixth in a row for the Tigers on the
road. The victory was the first for Fordham over Princeton in their
nine-game series, which began in 1907. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burnham blamed himself for the loss, for giving up the
interception. Princeton's intent had been to stay with running
plays to set up its crack place-kicker, Alex Sierk, whose three
field goals had beaten Fordham last season, 9-7. Sierk was expected
to kick a tying field goal that would have extended the overtime
session. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said he saw Fordham change its defensive scheme from
man-to-man pass defense to zone, so he changed the play call, from
run to pass, a pass he thought he could complete. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A mistake at the scrimmage line,'' said Steve Tosches, the
Princeton coach.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe was asked why he turned to freshman Colsant under such
trying conditions rather than staying with the more experienced Dan
Lofrese. ``We wanted to see what he could do,'' the coach said with
an impish smile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' defensive unit was outstanding, giving up only two
big plays: O'Hare's passes to wide receiver Gerry McDermott. The
first, for 24 yards, was for Fordham's first touchdown in the third
period, the second for 54 yards setting up its second touchdown,
which gave the Rams their first lead, 14-10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Tiger linebacker Dan Swingos said: ``We dominated
them. I don't understand what happened, how we lost.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare's retort to that was that the Rams were resilient. He
said, ``It feels great to beat an Ivy League team.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Princeton had scored first, near the end of a sluggish first
half, when Burnham completed a 9-yard pass to wide receiver Danny
Brian with 7 seconds left. Burnham had missed on seven straight
pass attempts earlier. ``I was terrible,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sierk's field goal gave Princeton a 10-0 lead in the third
period, and then Fordham's offense came alive with the first big
pass play to McDermott. The Rams' 14-10 lead lasted for 10 minutes,
and then the Tigers took the lead on a 66-yard drive that ended
with Burnham's 8-yard touchdown pass to Ryan Crowley with 5:13
remaining.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare's pass of 33 yards to Robert Davis brought on Colsant,
the freshman kicker from Vacaville, Calif., and he coolly scored.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   Ken O'Keefe had a 79-10-1 record at Allegheny College, a western
Pennsylvania Division III power. At Fordham he succeeded Nick
Quartaro, who left to become the offensive coordinator at Iowa
State. O'Keefe's staff inherited 14 starters from last year's team,
which won five games, the most for Fordham since joining the
Patriot League in 1989. ... Fordham has two more Ivy opponents
coming up, Penn at home and then Brown away. The Tigers' next foe
will be Brown on Saturday in the new Princeton Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
