<HEADLINE>
BRUINS THRIVE ON PLAYING IT `SAFE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about misnomers. UCLA blocked two punts Saturday using what
assistant coach Nick Aliotti called a ``safe'' alignment.
</P>
<P>
   In scouring film, Aliotti noticed that Washington State's Kareem
Anderson took extra time punting when he did not sense a furious
rush. So, Aliotti figured, why not lull Anderson to sleep with a
passive alignment _ one giving the impression UCLA was setting up a
return _ and then charge hard?
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a safe rush, and he eased up,'' Aliotti said.
</P>
<P>
   DuVal Hicks blocked Anderson's punt in the second quarter, which
Jason Stephens recovered at the Wazu 6. On the ensuing play,
Jermaine Lewis gave the Bruins a 28-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Azziz blocked an Anderson punt in the third quarter, but the
Bruins failed to convert.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA officials believe it's the first time the Bruins have
blocked two punts in a game in at least 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Tod McBride's block at Houston, UCLA has blocked
three punts in its last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``McBride was all individual effort. Today, they were designed
blocks,'' Aliotti said. ``The only two times we (rushed hard), we
blocked them. It worked well.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically well.
</P>
<P>
   High flying: Saturday's most memorable play _ and a sure bet to
make national highlights _ was Cade McNown's 6-yard first-quarter
touchdown run, in which he hurdled Cougars linebacker Steve Gleason
at the goal line and landed squarely on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take it in,'' McNown said. ``They broke when I broke.
I had to take it over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Which didn't thrill his head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those situations, everything's instinctive,'' Bob Toledo
said. ``He got an `A' in gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Late night in Tucson: ABC announced it will carry the Arizona
State-Notre Dame game at 12:30 p.m. on Saturday, pushing the
UCLA-Arizona kickoff to 7:15 p.m. on Fox Sports West.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Starting outside linebacker Michael Wiley did not
play after suffering a sprained right ankle in warmups. In his
place, Santi Hall had four tackles and a sack.
</P>
<P>
   Starting inside linebacker Ramogi Huma aggravated a right hip
injury in the first half. Ryan Nece filled in nicely, with eight
tackles and a forced fumble.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA scored touchdowns on seven of nine trips inside the red
zone (Washington State's 20).
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sailer had his only field-goal attempt blocked, leaving
him without a successful field goal for the third consecutive game.
``He's mad because we keep scoring touchdowns,'' Toledo quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Do-everything linebacker Brendan Ayanbadejo had two tackles, a
sack, a fumble recovery and a pass deflected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
