<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE RED SOX'S HAUNTING HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update)  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the Boston Red Sox, the past is always present. If
it's not Babe Ruth being dealt to the Yankees, it's Bucky Dent's
home run. If it's not why Jim Willoughby wasn't pitching, it's why
Denny Galehouse was.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after Saturday night's 2-1 loss to the Cleveland
Indians that eliminated the Red Sox in their American League
division series, it's why third-base coach Wendell Kim waved John
Valentin to keep running in the sixth inning, only to be thrown out
at the plate by left fielder David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 1-0 lead,'' Kim was saying in the gloom of the Red
Sox clubhouse. ``Justice was going to his right, and he's a
left-handed thrower. It was my decision. It didn't turn out. So
it's basically my fault.'
</P>
<P>
   Had Kim held up Valentin, the Red Sox would have had the bases
loaded with one out. Instead, with two out and runners on first and
third, left-hander Jim Poole struck out left-handed-hitting Troy
O'Leary to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Sox, who haven't won the World Series since 1918,
this was another sad scenario. Just as Friday's 4-3 loss had been
after Nomar Garciaparra's two-run homer in the bottom of the ninth.
Manny Ramirez's homer, his second of the game, minutes earlier off
Dennis Eckersley turned out to be the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the homer that beat us,'' Eckersley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Reggie Jackson's homer,'' somebody said.
</P>
<P>
   That somebody could have been almost anybody in what is known as
the Red Sox nation. In their haunting heritage, Red Sox fans aren't
just fans, they're historians. They'll never forget Bucky Dent's
homer in the 5-4 loss to the Yankees in their 1978 AL East one-game
playoff, but they also remember that Mr. October's homer off Bob
Stanley in the top of the eighth made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   For all their rivalry, that 1978 playoff has been the only
Yankee-Red Sox postseason game in a history that has been hallowed
for the Yankees, haunted for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the possibility of a Yankee-Red Sox duel in this
year's AL Championship Series was so compelling. If it developed,
there would be at least four chances and maybe as many as seven for
another Bucky Dent moment for the Yankees or, finally, for a moment
the Red Sox could cherish.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Red Sox confronted by elimination in Saturday's
fourth game with the Indians, the past again intruded on the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, the Red Sox ace with a 19-7 record and the
winner of the series opener, offered to start on three days' rest
instead of his usual four.
</P>
<P>
   But Red Sox manager, Jimy Williams, preferred to start
left-hander Pete Schourek, who was an erratic 8-9 this season _ 1-3
with the Red Sox after being obtained on Aug. 6 from Houston, where
he had been 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek more than justified Williams' confidence, pitching five
and two-thirds shutout innings before Tom ``Flash'' Gordon, who
hadn't blown a save since April 14, gave up Justice's two-run
double in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice hit a fastball away; he's a good hitter,'' Gordon
said. ``I stayed consistent, fastballs in and out. I wouldn't
second-guess myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's scenario recalled the 1948 one-game pennant
playoff with the Indians when Joe McCarthy, then the Red Sox
manager, started Denny Galehouse, with an 8-7 record, instead of
the 15-game winner Mel Parnell or Ellis Kinder. The Red Sox lost,
8-3.
</P>
<P>
   And every Red Sox historian worth a bowl of New England clam
chowder remembered a somewhat similar situation in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Yankees took the first three games of that big
series here at Fenway in September,'' one of those Red Sox
historians recalled, ``Luis Tiant told Don Zimmer he could pitch
the fourth game on only three days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, then the Red Sox manager and now Joe Torre's bench coach
on the Yankees, preferred to start 22-year-old left-hander Bobby
Sprowl, up from Pawtucket of the International League, who had lost
his debut five days earlier in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sprowl walked four of the first six Yankees, Zimmer
yanked him. The Yankees won, 7-4, and suddenly they were tied for
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, in the seventh game of the World Series,
Red Sox manager, Darrell Johnson, made another haunting decision.
In a 3-3 tie, Johnson used a pinch-hitter for Jim Willoughby, who
had blanked the Cincinnati Reds in the eighth inning, and called in
Jim Burton to open the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds scored one run, the Red Sox lost, 4-3. Ever since, Red
Sox historians have wondered, ``Why did he take out Willoughby?''
</P>
<P>
   And when ESPN suddenly showed a flashback of Bucky Dent's homer
during Friday's game, another of those Red Sox historians reacted
with a growl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anybody got a gun?'' the historian asked.
</P>
<P>
   The historian wasn't laughing, wasn't even smiling. With the Red
Sox, the past is always present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
