<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE LEADS INDIANS BACK INTO ALCS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a while, it was tempting to nickname Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams, ``Jimy Genius.'' Williams' much-questioned
decision to start journeyman Pete Schourek over ace Pedro Martinez
in Boston's win-or-go-home Game 4 had gone that well.
</P>
<P>
   When the veteran left-hander finally departed to a standing
ovation in the sixth inning, he had pitched two-hit shutout
baseball and the Red Sox were leading the Cleveland Indians 1-0 and
seemingly headed back to Jacobs Field for a decisive Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But then something intervened. Long-suffering Red Sox Nation
fans no doubt will chalk it up to fate: This sort of thing has
happened before. But the more objective observer would attribute
the Indians' 2-1 victory to two bad decisions _ one by Williams and
one by his third base coach, Wendell Kim _ plus one big-time play
after another by Cleveland designated hitter-turned-left fielder
David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The first bad decision came in the Red Sox's half of the sixth
inning with Boston leading by a run. John Valentin, who had doubled
to open the inning, tried to score on a one-out single to left by
Mike Stanley. But Justice, who nearly threw out Valentin at second
on the double, nailed him at the plate with a perfect throw to
Sandy Alomar. Kim had sent him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was the right call,'' Williams said of Kim's
decision to send Valentin. ``John got a good break on the ball, but
David Justice just made a perfect throw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be aggressive on that play,'' Valentin agreed,
``because \RJustice\S hasn't been out in left field a lot.''
Justice spent most of the season as the Indians' designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The second questionable move, by Williams, was his decision to
bring in closer Tom Gordon at the beginning of the eighth inning.
Gordon usally comes in to pitch the ninth inning and tries to get
three outs. This was going to be a stretch. Also, he was replacing
middle man Derek Lowe, who had easily retired five consecutive
Cleveland hitters in relief of Schourek and appeared unchallenged
by Indians batters.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon promptly gave up one-out singles to Kenny Lofton and Omar
Vizquel, then surrendered a monster double to center field by
Justice, which drove home both runners giving the Indians their
margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right man in the right spot,'' Williams said of his
early call for Gordon. ``He was a fresh arm and Lowe had done his
job.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it was the Indians who did a job on the Red
Sox. For the second time in four years, Cleveland had eliminated
Boston in division series play.
</P>
<P>
   Justice did most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything you can ask him to do,'' said Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove. ``He made the throw to home plate to throw
out Valentin to prevent a two-run lead, then he came back two
innings later and hit the two-run double to give us the lead. He
showed you why David Justice is David Justice. He is able to do
things like that because he is a tremendous athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice said he wasn't surprised to see Valentin challenging his
arm, calling the Red Sox ``an aggressive club.'' He also wasn't
surprised to see Gordon enter early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great stuff. He's only showing that he's human,''
Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice reveled in his moment, which included a champagne shower
in the cramped visitors' clubhouse in the bowels of Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the fact that we are moving on'' to the American
League Championship Series against the New York Yankees, he said.
``So many good players who have played this game never got
champagne poured over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Justice, a world champion with Atlanta in 1995,
felt the spray of Verdi Spumante again.
</P>
</TEXT>
