<HEADLINE>
COLUMBIA MAKES A LITTLE HISTORY OUT WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORAGA, Calif. _ When freshman tailback Jonathan Reese crossed
the goal line for Columbia's first score Saturday afternoon against
St. Mary's early in the second quarter, he displayed the jubilation
to be expected of a player scoring his first collegiate touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The play _ a 15-yard screen pass from reserve quarterback Ted
Schroeder with 8 minutes 55 seconds left in the first half _ was
also a historic one, of sorts, in the Lions' 20-17 victory. It was
Columbia's first score on the West Coast since halfback Al Barabas
ran for a touchdown on the deception play that victimized Stanford
in the 1934 Rose Bowl, a stunning 7-0 upset victory for the Lions.
Of course, Saturday's contest against St. Mary's was also
Columbia's first game in the Pacific time zone since that New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a limited athletic budget that is the norm in the Ivy
League, Columbia's football team had not ventured west of the
Mississippi River since that bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a long away trip,'' deadpanned Ray Tellier,
Columbia's head coach. ``Instead of getting on a bus for five and a
half hours, we got on a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Columbia (2-1) made its return engagement to
California a successful one as junior tailback Kirby Mack bulldozed
into the end zone from a yard out with 15 seconds to go to give the
Lions a dramatic victory.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's had taken the lead on a 47-yard touchdown pass from
reserve quarterback Joe Lilley to wide receiver Bruce Rhode with
6:04 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Columbia's last hope had faded with 3:40 to go
when Schroeder's fourth-down pass from the St. Mary's 37-yard line
fell incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   But on the following series, St. Mary's (0-5) elected to make a
quick kick on third and 17 from its 30-yard line. Lilley's mediocre
punt gave the Lions possession of the ball at their 47-yard line
with 2:37 left. A 15-yard personal foul penalty on St. Mary's
linebacker Danny Wilcox for hitting a scrambling Schroeder out of
bounds moved the ball to the 18. Five plays later, with the 4,967
fans in St. Mary's Stadium on their feet, Mack hit paydirt on third
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definition of a good call is one that works,'' said Mike
Rasmussen, St. Mary's head coach, referring to the decision to make
a quick kick. ``It's my responsibility, and in hindsight, I wish I
had it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilley said: ``There's no excuse. I just missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia generated 317 yards of total offense despite losing its
starting quarterback, Paris Childress, early in the second quarter
with a severely sprained right foot. Schroeder directed a
ball-control offense that produced 179 yards rushing and two
fourth-quarter touchdowns, both by Mack. The first one came on a
3-yard run with 9:44 to go that gave Columbia a 13-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although they moved the ball well, the Lions were unable to
generate any scoring in the first half aside from Reese's
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's scored just before halftime on a 5-yard pass from the
junior quarterback Chad Thomas to the senior flanker Marc Kleiman.
That play capped a 12-play, 90-yard drive and gave St. Mary's a 7-6
lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
