A8352 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX     10-03 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAZORBACKS STUMBLE ONTO THE RIGHT NUTT FOR THE JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Sometimes, the best hires are the ones you
don't make.
</P>
<P>
   When searching for its fifth coach of the decade, a coach to
restore some glory and glitter to a stumbling program, Arkansas set
its sights on Mississippi's Tommy Tuberville, Tulane's Tommy
Bowden, Southern Mississippi's Jeff Bower and Florida assistant
Bobby Stoops. Tuberville was the favorite, who waffled when the
search committee couldn't agree on an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Nutt, a native son with limited head coaching experience
(Division I-AA Murray State and Boise State), said he wanted the
job. He waited patiently for two days while Razorbacks fans spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Frank Broyles had trouble making phone calls;
there were too many incoming calls, the majority demanding that
they wanted a Nutt for a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night here in War Memorial Stadium, the No. 22
Razorbacks went to 4-0 with a scintillating 27-20 victory against
Kentucky. In the second half, Arkansas' defense made the big plays,
and junior quarterback Clint Stoerner snapped out of his trance to
outduel Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, this team would have rolled it up and took it on
home,'' Arkansas defensive back Jeromy Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Nutt and his assistants made all the right moves in the second
half. They increased the pressure on Couch and they used Kentucky's
aggressiveness to isolate receivers in one-on-one situations.
</P>
<P>
   And all those Razorbacks who swamped the school with calls,
faxes and e-mails are smugly saying, ``We told you so.'' The
critics thought that Nutt and his staff were too small-time, too
young, too overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas trailed 20-7 with 9:35 left in the third quarter and
was being worn out by Couch and the Wildcats' Air Raid. All the
Razorbacks did was go on a Nolan Richardson-like, 24 Minutes of
Hell 20-point run.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks ``held'' Couch to 499 yards passing. Couch was
47-of-67. His only interception, though, turned the game around.
Junior David Barrett's pick and 62-yard return set up Arkansas'
game-tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Anthony Lucas scored that touchdown by fighting
his way through three defenders to reach the end zone. He played
much of the game with his injured right wrist heavily taped.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas admits that when Nutt was named the coach, his reaction
was, ``Say what?'' Running back Madre Hill said that at the first
team meeting, Nutt won the Razorbacks over with an enthusiastic
rendering of the school fight song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Nutt has come in here and preached to us about playing
as a family, playing together,'' Barrett said. ``And we've got
nowhere to go but up. Winning a game like this does nothing but
prove to us that this does work.''
</P>
<P>
   While favorite son Bill Clinton is playing prevent defense in
Washington, Houston Nutt, the people's choice for football coach,
is reviving the Razorbacks. The past three weeks, the Razorbacks
have exorcised their SMU demon, drubbed Alabama and rallied to beat
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kept hanging in there, hanging in there,'' said the
40-year-old Nutt, whose brother Dennis is a former TCU basketball
standout. ``I just love this team, love what we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this team is growing and coming together because
this team is overcoming adversity. They're learning to trust each
other and play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Southwest Conference, Arkansas football has
faced an uphill battle in the Southeastern Conference. Nutt's
enthusiasm and drive is reducing the incline considerably.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
