<HEADLINE>
GALAXY EXPECTS TO FEEL BURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Careful not to read too much into its destruction of
the Dallas Burn in Thursday's Western Conference semifinal opener,
the Galaxy head to the Cotton Bowl this afternoon with little of
the bravado one might expect.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is coming off a 6-1 romp in the first game of the
best-of-three series, but the team knows a second win, which would
put it one step from Major League Soccer's championship game, won't
come nearly so easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to remember this,'' Galaxy midfielder Danny Pena
said after scoring twice at the Rose Bowl. ``No team likes to be
beaten, whether it's 1-0 or 6-1. I expect they'll come out fired
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been embarrassed,'' added defender Robin Fraser. ``We
expect them to come hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of maybe two chances the Burn has to extend the series
to a third game Wednesday in Pasadena. The other is to sit back,
play tight defense and try to steal a goal on a counterattack.
Those tactics worked a year ago, when the Burn swept L.A. in a
first-round series with two shutouts, but it didn't count for much
Thursday, the Galaxy shredding Dallas' defense for a 3-0 lead by
the 20th minute, then pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has been through this,'' Burn coach Dave Dir said.
``This is the kind of season we have had. This team has come
through a lot of adversity, and this is only one game.... We'll
come to play Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Dallas fell victim to a Galaxy swarm that dictated
terms everywhere on the field. L.A. moved the ball like magicians,
creating opportunities at will, and with its midfield of Pena,
Mauricio Cienfuegos and Martin Machon in particular in superb form,
it cut down nearly every Dallas foray before it started.
</P>
<P>
   ``An abysmal performance from start to finish,'' assessed Burn
goalkeeper Mark Dodd. ``We really owe the Dallas fans an enormous
apology.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the Galaxy's most impressive performances in what
has been a pretty incredible season. It was the eighth time the
Galaxy scored at least five goals in a match, and eight MLS playoff
records _ including goals and margin of victory _ fell before it
was through.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first half of soccer,'' in which L.A. grabbed a 5-0 edge,
``was the best in MLS, I think,'' said Galaxy captain Dan
Calichman.
</P>
<P>
   He might have been the biggest story of the win, seeing an
unscheduled 13{ minutes of action, his first since suffering a
broken leg May 6. He doesn't anticipate another playoff appearance
_ he's not nearly 100 percent yet _ and coach Octavio Zambrano
isn't about to throw him in unless his squad is enjoying another
rout.
</P>
<P>
   That's not something anyone expects.
</P>
<P>
   Says Fraser: ``There's no way it'll happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Dallas) would be dangerous,'' said Zambrano. ``We
have to go there as if (the first game) never happened and take
care of business. They're still a dangerous team, a good team, and
we won't take them lightly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
