r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     10-03 2020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY'S BUDDY STILL THERE FOR HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He looks 20 years older now than he did in 1992, the season
Darryl Strawberry's career began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   But in the chaos of that 99-loss Dodgers season there was one
big boost he got that will help him through the next few months of
his battle to overcome colon cancer. Eric Davis.
</P>
<P>
   That year Strawberry ruptured a disk in his lower back that
robbed him of the majestic home run swing that made him a certain
Hall of Famer. He continued to struggle with the pressures of
playing in his home town, saying yes to every old crony who knew
him from way back when.
</P>
<P>
   It began a spiral downward that included drugs, a failed first
marriage, domestic violence and trouble with the IRS. One of the
only things that kept him from losing it all was Davis, who
Strawberry knew growing up in South Central Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They were buddies, one of those baseball friendships that pass
like a notice on the transaction wire. Strawberry might have been
the greatest high school prospect ever when he graduated from
Crenshaw High in 1980. Davis was a shortstop from Fremont who got a
tryout at Dodger Stadium but never was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   They never played together until 1992. Strawberry had gone on to
stardom with the New York Mets, and Davis, the Cincinnati Reds.
Davis, who had fought his own demons playing for Marge Schott,
became the quiet presence that was always there when things got a
little too hot for Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 season began with great promise, the addition of Davis
to the Dodgers outfield of Strawberry and Brett Butler. In the next
six years, all three would be stricken with cancer. But in that
spring of 1992, the possibilities seemed endless.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was coming off a turbulent first year in Los Angeles.
He had signed as a free agent in December 1990 for a whopping
$20.25 million. In 1991, Strawberry started sluggishly, but the
Dodgers took off, leading Atlanta at the All-Star break by eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Strawberry carried the team with 63 of his
99 RBI, but the Dodgers fell apart, losing to the Braves on the
second to last day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In May of 1992, Strawberry ruptured a disk in his lower back
rounding the bases in Philadelphia. Davis had a ruptured disk in
his neck from previous seasons in Cincinnati. As Strawberry
attempted rehab, he fell back into bad habits with alcohol and
drugs. He became isolated from his teammates. Strawberry and Davis
had adjoining lockers and retreated into their own worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates looked at the two and blamed them for the team's
decline. It only made their friendship stronger. Strawberry and
Davis once invited Rodney King to Dodger Stadium. That drew the
wrath of the LAPD and the two were told not to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was the collapse of 1992 was a result of the
late-season breakdown of 1991. If Mike Piazza had not arrived the
next season, it might have been quite a while longer before the
Dodgers started to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry and Davis ended their Dodgers careers the next year.
Both bounced around. But they stayed in touch. Davis, now with the
Baltimore Orioles, learned he had colon cancer in June 1997 and
came back with a season that should earn him American League
Comeback Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors seem to think Strawberry also will play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was nothing he did,'' Davis told reporters after
the Strawberry story broke. ``I told him that it's nothing that
anybody can control. I couldn't. He can't. I told him not to think,
`Why me?' That's just a waste of time. He's got to face it, accept
it, deal with it. The next step isn't feeling sorry for yourself,
it's getting this thing out of your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Better win now: The Padres have four top players who will become
eligible for free agency once their contracts expire at the end of
the season: 1B Wally Joyner, 3B Ken Caminiti, CF Steve Finley and
RH Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, who'll turn 36 next April, has been hobbled by a
succession of injuries over the last few years and probably will be
allowed to walk to make room for former Angel George Arias, 26, who
batted .308 with 36 homers and a Pacific Coast League-high 119 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who'll turn 34 in March, still is great defensively but
tailed off offensively this season (.249 average, 14 HR, 67 RBI, 12
SB) after going .261 with 28 homers, 92 RBI and 15 steals in 1997,
when he batted mostly leadoff and scored over 100 runs for the
third year in a row. This year, he scored 91. The Padres have no
one to replace him and are expected to try to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner, 36, suffered several injuries this season but still
batted .298 with 12 homers and 80 RBI in only 439 at-bats. Again,
he proved to be a lifesaver defensively. The Padres have no
comparable first-base replacement and hope to re-sign Joyner at a
reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who turns 34 in March, struck out 16 Astros on Tuesday in
the first game of the division playoffs and came back Saturday to
pitch on just three days of rest. He went 18-7 with a 2.38 ERA
during the regular season and made everyone around him better. The
Padres say they have to re-sign him to keep alive hopes of a new
stadium, but he's talking about $12 million a season in a
multi-year deal, way over the team's head.
</P>
<P>
   Nice run falls short: The Giants got rid of Rod Beck last year
because he faltered down the stretch and was rescued by Roberto
Hernandez. They replaced him with Robb Nen, who was 6-1 with 25
saves and a 0.98 ERA in the first half. But Nen was 1-6 with 15
saves in the second half, giving up the Neifi Perez homer Sunday
that deprived the Giants of the wild card. Beck, meanwhile,
finished with a career-high 51 saves, including one Monday in the
playoff clincher against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Robb when we were up there and he said his arm was
dead,'' Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw said. ``He said it was dragging on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the Giants' season, second baseman Jeff Kent was
the key element. The Giants were 77-57 with him in the lineup and
12-17 without him, including seven pivotal games with the
division-champion Padres in July. The Giants lost six of them,
dropping from a tie to 5{ games behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants fell shy of their goal for two million in attendance,
finishing with 1,925,634, and club president Peter Magowan
indicated the club again will lose money _ perhaps as much as $15
million _ this season, meaning the 1999 payroll will remain in the
$40 million range, as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be $80 million,'' Magowan assured. ``My guess is it
will be where it ended up.'' More than half of that will go to four
players: Barry Bonds ($9.7 million), Kent ($5.7 million), Nen ($5
million) and Kirk Rueter ($2.75 million). The club also is likely
to pick up the options on J.T. Snow ($3 million), Charlie Hayes
($1.7 million) and Julian Tavarez ($1.2 million), for a total of
$29 million for seven players.
</P>
<P>
   That means cost-cutting is in order for the remaining 18 spots
on the roster, especially if a name free-agent pitcher or
outfielder is signed. Pitching is the top priority, according to GM
Brian Sabean, who says: ``I'm a firm believer that you never have
enough pitching. But we still had 89 victories without a No. 1 or a
No. 2 pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser (11-10) may not be kept after winning but once
the final six weeks. If he stays, he gets $3.2 million. If not,
it's a $200,000 buyout. ``No decisions have been made,'' Sabean
said. ``We will begin our organizational meetings and go over
everything. There are a lot of things to discuss.'' Injured Osvaldo
Fernandez will be bought out for $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation for next year: Shawn Estes, Kirk Rueter, Mark
Gardner and Russ Ortiz. Starting pitching collapsed in the second
half. After going 37-25 prior to the break, the rotation was a
horrible 22-26 over the final 2{ months. Minus Gardner, it was a
woeful 16-24.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion review: Arizona CF Devon White had 22 homers, 22
stolen bases and 85 RBI, but he is a free agent and will almost
certainly test the market. White makes his home in the Phoenix area
and wants to stay, but the Diamondbacks will offer him only a
one-year deal, or perhaps a deal with a year and an option based on
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   They hope LF Bernard Gilkey's laser eye surgery will improve his
vision enough that he can become the Gilkey of 1996 _ 27 homers and
117 RBI with the New York Mets. He had one extra-base hit, a homer,
in 101 at-bats with the D'backs after being acquired at the trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   As for free agents, Bernie Williams won't be coming despite
agent Scott Boras' strong relationship with owner Jerry Colangelo.
Same for Kevin Brown. Both want salaries in the $11-12 million
range. Randy Johnson has roots in the Phoenix area and Colangelo
might try to get him under market value, a strategy that has lately
worked with his Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza will not play where he will be naked in the lineup.
Finley will draw some attention. The big-money guys will not come
here. The D'backs are not going to spend a lot for a guy who will
take them to .500.
</P>
<P>
   News and notes: Cleveland's Charles Nagy raised his career mark
to 5-0 with a 1.27 ERA at Fenway Park on Friday when he defeated
the Boston Red Sox 4-3. He needed just 88 pitches in eight innings
to raise his overall record to 8-1 vs. Boston.... Toronto's Carlos
Delgado can expect a huge pay raise after hitting 38 homers and
driving in 115 runs. He is arbitration eligible and the Jays will
surely try to lock him up for four or five years at $5-$6 million a
year.... Teammate Shawn Green might be one of baseball's biggest
bargains next year. With 35 homers and 100 RBI in his first year as
an everyday player, Green already is signed through 1999 for $1.475
million.... Philadelphia right-hander Mark Leiter pulled off a rare
feat for futility, leading the majors in losses one year (17 in
1997) and blown saves (12 this season) the next. Like his brother
Al, who won 17 games with a 2.40 ERA for the Mets, Leiter is a free
agent. That's where the comparisons end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
Who was the NL RBI leader in the second half? Sammy Sosa with 77?
Mark McGwire? It was the Giants' Jeff Kent, who had 24 homers and
79 RBI after the All-Star break. Kent, who missed 28 games with an
injured right knee, finished with 31 homers and 128 RBI, joining
Rogers Hornsby as the only second baseman in history with at least
120 RBI in consecutive years. &QL; 
ROTISSERIE WATCH &QL; 
Pittsburgh second baseman Tony Womack has won two straight stolen
base titles but could be traded, especially with prospect Warren
Morris on the horizon. The Pirates are unhappy with his low on-base
percentage and shaky defense. Womack, however, is not yet eligible
for arbitration, critical for the cost-conscious Bucs. He also
started in center for the final five games of the season and could
wind up there if he's back next season. &QL; 
STAT OF THE WEEK &QL; 
Cleveland's Manny Ramirez went 5 for 10 with three homers in the
first three games of the American League Division Series against
Boston. In the last 12 games of the regular season, Ramirez had
eight homers and 17 RBI. The eight homers came in a five-game
stretch, which was followed by a 4-for-26 slump to end the season. &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
Again this year, one of the most popular players for offseason
trade talks will be Paul Konerko, the guy the Dodgers wouldn't give
up for closer Robb Nen last winter but did trade for Jeff Shaw at
the All-Star break. A bust at the plate this year, but still just
22. The Reds realize he can only play first but are committed to
Sean Casey. Might try left, but Dmitri Young batted .312 with 14
homers and 48 doubles. Could go to Arizona, but Travis Lee will
stay at first. &QL; 
QUOTABLE &QL; 
``Me and Darryl, we just knew we were going to have everything.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Davis, childhood friend and former teammate of Darryl
Strawberry, who like Strawberry has undergone surgery for colon
cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
