<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-ROENICK-A     10-03 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ROENICK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING UP IS TOP PRIORITY FOR ROENICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The poster boy has warts.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Roenick can admit it now. He finally can come clean. Even
if his legion of adoring fans isn't ready to hear it or believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is I was not being the type of person I
should have been,'' the Coyotes superstar center said. ``I was
screwing up in a lot of ways, and every part of me suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   It's never easy to acknowledge one's faults. It isn't always
easy to say you're sorry, either. But during a lengthy interview
after a recent practice in Scottsdale, Ariz. Roenick did a lot of
both, offering a rare, critical look at his hockey career and his
personal life _ and his desire to turn each of them around.
</P>
<P>
   He revealed he spent most of his nine seasons in the NHL not
caring so much about winning, but rather scoring goals and making
money. He talked about how he became preoccupied with his image and
how others perceived him. He also said he spread himself so thin,
caddying to a litany of acquaintances and selfish schedules, that
he nearly lost his family.
</P>
<P>
   Reality finally reached up and smacked him in the face this
summer. He made amends with his wife, Tracey, their two children,
and then the 28-year-old made a promise to himself _ ``It's time
for me to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely let myself decrease to someone I should not have
been,'' Roenick said. ``I spent most of my time playing golf, going
out and having fun, always doing stuff the easy way. I was doing
all that _ and other things _ instead of being dedicated to the
things that are important and working hard at things that are
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used to think about my wife caring if I'm going to be
here or there because she was my wife. But it just builds up,
builds up and . . . I just got caught up in the big trap of letting
too many people into my life and taking the easy way out of a lot
of things and not working hard enough at being a dad, at being a
husband and at being the hockey player that everybody expects me to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't make such a transformation overnight. It takes
commitment. It takes willpower. It takes dedication. None of which
Roenick said he exactly has excelled at throughout his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do it for my own benefit,'' he said. ``I went
through a lot in the last year, professionally and personally, and
to tell you the truth, I'm trying to get my life back. I'm hoping
with those things being straightened out, it helps me
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already, there aren't as many distractions. I can focus on
playing hockey. And I can focus on the most important thing, and
that's my family. The other (expletive) doesn't matter. It's all my
business.''
</P>
<P>
   On the hockey front, things seem to be shaping up nicely for the
three-time 100-point scorer and two-time 50-goal man. Coyotes Coach
Jim Schoenfeld said he plans to pair Roenick on the same forward
line with left wing Keith Tkachuk, the team's leading scorer each
of the past three seasons. It could be a dynamite 1-2 scoring
punch, every bit as dangerous as the Philadelphia duo of Eric
Lindros and John LeClair, or the pair in Anaheim of Paul Kariya and
Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really going to try and make it work,'' Schoenfeld said
last week. ``I've got a hunch it's going to go well.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been constant speculation Tkachuk and Roenick can't
play together because both always want the puck. Some claim
Roenick's free-wheeling, one-on-one style isn't conducive to a
north-and-south skater like the power forward Tkachuk. Supposedly,
it's a complete mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Tkachuk said, ``we're going to have to alter our
games a little for it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick seems up to the task. He's changed just about everything
else in his life, lately. What can be so hard about playing a
little bit more under control? It's got to be easier than trying to
live up to his flamboyant personality, which he says makes him feel
``like a cartoon character'' at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think definitely my flamboyance is going to decrease a
little bit, anyway, because I want people to realize I am a team
guy and I only want what's best for the Phoenix Coyotes,'' he said.
``What's important to me is that my teammates know I'm dedicated to
them and I'm dedicated to winning the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't always the case in the past.
</P>
<P>
   When he was flying down the ice for the Chicago Blackhawks, he
was more concerned with just trying to make a name for himself.
Winning, he said, was an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time in my career when I just cared about scoring
goals, scoring points and making money. I admit it,'' Roenick said.
``That's part of being immature and being a young player.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the trap of professional sports, Roenick said. If you're
good at it, you get paid a king's ransom _ he's in the third year
of a five-year contract worth $20 million. Most athletes aren't
mature enough to handle the distractions that follow suit. They
feast on the perks but choke on the hangers-on who elbow in to
share some of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   After deciding he needed to make a change at home, Roenick
decided he'd better make one on the ice, too. For the first time in
his career, he spent all summer working out and getting in shape.
He took his family to southern California, rented a condo for a
couple months, and hit the weights daily with a group of other NHL
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the biggest change I've seen in him since I've
known him,'' said teammate Oleg Tverdovsky, one of several Phoenix
players who trained with Roenick. ``He really worked his butt
off.''
</P>
<P>
   He got bigger and a lot stronger, which should make him all the
more dangerous when the 1998-99 season opens in another week. He
gained a solid six pounds of muscle, bringing him to 192 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was proud of me that I was making a commitment to
myself and my future,'' Roenick said. ``Plus, we got away from our
element. We had no distractions. We had very few people that
bothered us out there. It was just our family, and it was a great
month and a half or so of hard work and fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did anything like that before. I've always had a lot
of natural talent, which probably was God-given, but I just used to
take it for granted, like a lot of things in my life. . . . It's
time for me to grow up.'' &QL; 
He desperately wants to return to form on the rink, when he
annually ranked among the NHL's scoring leaders. He doesn't want to
dwell on how his numbers have dropped, from 32 goals and 67 points
in 1995-96, to 29 and 69 in 1996-97, and to 24 and 56 last season.
</P>
<P>
   He just wants to come back this year with a bang. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
