<HEADLINE>
AUNTIE MAME, A HORSE FOR A COURSE, WINS 5TH AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ For horses that like certain courses, consider
the filly Auntie Mame: She ran for the fifth time on the Belmont
Park grass Saturday, and for the fifth time she outran everybody
else, winning the $400,000 Flower Bowl Invitational by one length
and keeping her hometown winning streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old daughter of Theatrical won two straight this
summer before running third last month after a troubled trip in the
Diana Handicap at Saratoga. Auntie Mame was outrun that day by
Memories of Silver, who skipped Saturday's race, and B.A.
Valentine, who did not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, B.A. Valentine took the lead Saturday and held it to
the top of the homestretch. But then Auntie Mame, the queen of
Belmont, who had been stalking the pace every step of the way,
swept past the leader and made it five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really proved herself out there,'' said Angel Penna Jr.,
who trains Auntie Mame for Martha Gerry and her Lazy F Ranch. ``We
had a horrible trip in the Diana last time. But she proved today
that when she gets the chance to move, she'll win. With B.A.
Valentine in the race, we knew that we'd sit a stalking trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But Penna added that he probably would not press his luck in the
Breeders' Cup Turf at Churchill Downs on Nov. 7 against some of the
world's best male runners. He said he would give ``a little
consideration'' to it but was more likely to run Auntie Mame in the
Matriarch or the Japan Cup on Nov. 29. The Breeders' Cup will add a
turf race for fillies next year, but by then Auntie Mame will be
retired to a new career as a broodmare.
</P>
<P>
   B.A. Valentine, who entered the race after Memories of Silver
bowed out, finished one length in front of Bahr, with Yokama fourth
and the favorite, Maxzene, fifth and last. The winner ran the mile
and a quarter on the inner turf course in 1:59 1/5, paid $5.90 for
a $2 bet to win and went home with $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Skiffington, who trains Maxzene, reasoned that his beaten
favorite had raced only two weeks earlier in the Violet Handicap in
the Meadowlands, and added: ``This is the first time she's ever run
a bad race. I'm just kind of shocked. Throughout her career, she
has overcome everything that has been thrown at her.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES:
</P>
<P>
   In a driving four-horse photo finish, Draw Shot won the Ashley
T. Cole Handicap by a neck over Abenaki, who had a neck on
Bellingham, who held off Plato's Love by a head for third. The
winner, trained by Angel Penna Jr., ran the mile in 1:33 2/5 on the
Belmont turf course, paid $4.80 for a $2 bet to win and earned
$34,000 under a smooth ride by Jerry Bailey. ``This horse runs best
when he comes with one sustained rally, and that's what he did,''
Bailey said. ... Pacificbounty, who stumbled and fell during a
workout on June 19 and caused Skip Away to unseat his jockey and
break loose, will again cross paths with Skip Away, the 5-year-old
superstar, next Saturday in the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup.
Pacificbounty was not injured in the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
