<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SWIMMING-HALL-AZR     10-03 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMING-HALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL SEEKS REDEMPTION WHILE CHALLENGING SWIMMING POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The heat gauge on the 1970 Chevy Nova indicated the
28-year-old engine was about to boil. Gary Hall, Jr., decided to
have a look. He pulled over and popped the hood.
</P>
<P>
   The old cooling system erupted into Hall's face and onto his
right arm like a worn-out pressure cooker. The boiling coolant
missed his eyes, but left him blistered with second-degree burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look like a Nordic explorer with a severe case of frost
bite,'' said Hall, who spent Tuesday night at Scottsdale Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's accident is just the latest in the turbulent waters
that have surrounded Hall, a Phoenix swimmer who won two gold and
two silver medals at the 1996 Olympics. A lot has blown up in his
face since.
</P>
<P>
   He blames himself for some of it. A suspension for a positive
marijuana test in May was lifted by swimming's international
governing body, FINA, in August, because of confusing rules about
drugs and inconsistency within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hall admits there would never have been a problem
had he not used pot in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm incredibly embarrassed that it happened,'' said Hall, who
paid with the loss of a lucrative endorsement deal with Speedo.
``It was a mistake. If you involve yourself in that type of
activity, sooner or later something bad is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   From the bad, Hall forsees change.
</P>
<P>
   In himself.
</P>
<P>
   And within his sport.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, the first is a personal quest for vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely have incentive,'' said Hall, a Phoenix Swim Club
sprinter who had been training at the University of California
before returning home nine days ago for his 24th birthday. ``I feel
I need to redeem myself and my abilities. I don't want to be
remembered as the swimmer who got busted and that was the end of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger is part of his motivation. Hall is not happy with FINA's
methods and priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming is being torn apart by performance-enhancing chemicals
such as steroids, yet, Hall argues, he was busted amid
international publicity for a drug that has no impact on
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I've never cheated in the sport,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether FINA used Hall in a public relations
attempt at saying it was active in the battle against drugs. But
what drugs?
</P>
<P>
   At the time of FINA's announced suspension of Hall, Phil
Whitten, editor of the Valley-based ``Swimming World,'' said the
sport should be more vigilant about performance-enhanching
substances than marijuana, or alcohol or over-the-counter medicine
for sinus problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue that probably will be addressed at the Olympic
Congress, scheduled to begin next weekend in Phoenix. Hall says
he's willing to be the point man in a battle to tighten and
re-focus FINA's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   It's a role that could turn Hall into an unlikely ally for
impatient officials with United States Swimming, which often has
been infuriated by his off-beat, go-it-alone style that includes a
less-than diligent work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of awkward,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Hall has mocked U.S. Swimming in both word and
deed. The sport is trying to shake its country-club reputation. But
the sight of Hall in leather motorcycle pants behind the starting
blocks at major meets is more than some of the tradition-bound
officials can tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Hall went from being a subject of criticism to a real target at
the World Championships last January in Perth, Australia. U.S.
Swimming convened a disciplinary hearing on Hall for a variety of
what it regarded as offenses, all of which Whitten calls petty.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with a curfew violation. But Hall said he signed
the required check-out sheet.
</P>
<P>
   He missed a social function with dignitaries from the Australian
Olympic Committee for the 2000 Sydney Games. Hall said he was ill
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He also was charged with wearing a wig for the official team
photo. He admits to the wig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wearing the wig practically everyday I was down there,''
said Hall, who anchored two U.S. relays, one for a gold medal and
one for a silver, at the World Championships. ``It wasn't like it
just for the photo. I was having some fun, just being myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no law saying I can't wear a wig. Andy Warhol wore
one. Marv Albert, he wears one.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Swimming has not commented on the hearing. Hall believes it
is about to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, there are mounting signs that Hall has friends
within the organization. Even if he is disliked personally, his
talent is singular. Despite FINA's suspension and an inconsistent
year, Hall still has the world's fourth-fastest time in the 50
meters freestyle for 1998. He's eighth in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   At a U.S. Swimming convention last month, 1996 Olympic teammate
Josh Davis took the podium and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Gary Hall, Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, coaches continue to see him as America's only
legitimate threat in 2000 to Russia's powerful Alexander Popov, a
bitter rival who narrowly beat Hall in the 50 and 100 at the last
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take more than a car explosion to keep me from
doing that,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2324EDT &QL; 
