A8362 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-LOCKOUT-BICKLEY-A     10-03 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-LOCKOUT-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE US WHEN LOCKOUT'S OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Another day, another sport, another spat involving
money.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and lockouts. Union heads and arbitrators. Billionaires
and millionaires feuding over the interpretation of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Rich men haggling with rich kids over how to divide the great
cash pie.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a surprise we don't give a damn anymore?
</P>
<P>
   So the NBA has reached the crossroads. If the current lockout
lingers a few days longer, the season will be delayed. A 52-year
streak will come to an end. They will no longer be the only major
sports league in America not to lose a game due to a labor dispute.
They will be like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric is getting worse, not better. The NBA wants to meet
now, to see if an agreement can get hammered out, to protect the
legacy of the league that never stops. The players' union, waiting
for an arbitrator's decision that could bust the whole thing wide
open, says they can't meet until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bowled over to hear that we can't meet for nine days
while Rome is burning,'' NBA Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik said
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask him who struck the match,'' responded union director Billy
Hunter. ``They locked us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what, fellas? Nobody cares. Nobody is picking sides. And
nobody will pay attention until the balls start bouncing and the
sneakers start squeaking.
</P>
<P>
   If that means no hoops until 1999, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   People are simply fed up with labor issues. Even here, where
basketball is king, where more than 19,000 flock to every Suns
game. Thanks to Andre Wadsworth and Keith Tkachuk, people are sick
of being held hostage in a high-stakes game. Someone else's game,
where someone else benefits, where the loser is always a constant.
</P>
<P>
   You.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the nonsense, you must believe the unbelievable,
that as many as 15 of 29 teams are losing money. Of the $1.7
billion in revenue generated last season, almost $1 billion went to
the players.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are paying 57 percent of revenue towards labor. They
want a 50-50 split. And until the Larry Bird exemption is removed,
they claim that labor costs will continue to spiral out of control.
</P>
<P>
   It is the exemption that allows a team to pay its own free
agents as much as it likes without regard to the salary cap. It is
how the Bulls could pay Michael Jordan $33 million when the cap
figure was just over $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the owners want the players to lend a hand. To
protect the owners from themselves. Like the guy in Minnesota who
gave Kevin Garnett $126 million multiyear before he became a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The players are standing firm. Convinced in the ethics of
principle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one has missed a paycheck yet, either.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, an arbitrator named John Feerick _ the same
genius who reinstated Latrell Sprewell's $25 million contract _
must decide whether 230 guaranteed contracts must be honored by the
owners. After all, the players aren't on strike. So why shouldn't
they get paid?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, 25 exhibition games have been scrapped, and if there
isn't any significant movement this week, the regular season will
start taking a hit.
</P>
<P>
   This is good for no one. Not the league, which has probably lost
its pied piper in Jordan. And if they think nothing will change
without Superman around, well, they're idiots. Unless your idea of
a hero is the hemp-carrying Chris Webber or posse-toting Allen
Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   It's not good for the Suns, who have three players under
contract and will have to scurry to fill a roster if this thing
ever gets settled. And it's not good for the continuity and
integrity of the league, not with 200 free agents waiting to be
signed when the madness comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
   All because they can't figure out how to share a gold mine, a
windfall that will reach $2.6 billion next season thanks to a new
television contract with TNT and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   So whose to blame? Who cares.
</P>
<P>
   Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Just wake us when it's over. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
