<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS DUO OBJECT TO SEPARATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX Don't look now, but  &UR; Craig Hartsburg, the new head coach
in Anaheim, is toying with the idea of splitting up linemates  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Kariya and  &UR; Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder this guy got fired last season in Chicago. If he
breaks up this dynamic duo, he'll probably get bounced again.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't Hartsburg know what these guys have done together? In
only 115 games as linemates, they've amassed a staggering 328
points (79 goals, 167 points for Kariya; 75 goals, 161 points for
Selanne).
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks also are 57-41-17 (a .570 winning percentage)
in games in which Kariya and Selanne have played together. When one
or both players are missing from the lineup, Anaheim is 22-44-12
(.359).
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we'll do whatever Hartsburg wants,'' Selanne said.
``He's the coach. But if you find two guys who can play so well
together, I see no reason why those two guys should be split up.
That's why the game is so much easier, when you can do so much
damage because you read each other so well. That's the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even think about Edmonton without  &UR; (Wayne) Gretzky and
 &UR; (Jari) Kurri together. Or Pittsburgh without  &UR; (Mario) Lemieux and
 &UR; (Jaromir) Jagr. . . . He tells us he likes to try different things.
That's just fine. But I think it's just wasting so much if we don't
play together.'' &QL; 
Eric the great &QL; 
Seems like all that public trashing Philadelphia Flyers General
Manager  &UR; Bobby Clarke put on captain  &UR; Eric Lindros may have done
the trick. After six preseason games, Lindros was leading the
league with a whopping 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, after Clarke agreed to give Lindros a one-year
extension worth $8.5 million, he said Lindros better be prepared to
live up to it. He has so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the difference, even in the little things he's
doing out there,'' linemate  &UR; John LeClair said. ``Even when there's
been no play there, he's in there trying to make something out of
it. He'll get a skate in, try to make something happen. He's really
been a leader. He's been intense, and the team has been following
his example.'' &QL; 
Last of the landmarks &QL; 
As you may have heard, storied Maple Leaf Gardens will be shutting
its doors after 68 years when the Toronto Maple Leafs play their
final home game there on Jan. 13 against Chicago. They will be
moving into a new building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the hottest ticket in town,'' said  &UR; Karen Petcoff,
manager of communications for Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the street has it that scalpers already are offering up
to $1,500 a pop to catch the grand finale. Expect that figure to
soar by January. &QL; 
Rumor city &QL; 
The talk in Buffalo is that the center-hungry Sabres might make a
pitch for disgruntled Czech star  &UR; Peter Nedved. The Penguins still
control his rights, so it would have to involve a trade, which
apparently has been discussed. Signing Nedved to an offer sheet
doesn't make too much sense for Buffalo. Especially at his
five-year, $20 million demand. More to the point, the Sabres aren't
willing to part with five first-round draft picks as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Scotty Bowman probably won't return as coach of the Red Wings.
But it won't be just because of his health problems. The inside
skinny is that he's pushing associate coach  &UR; Barry Smith to be his
replacement, and the longer Bowman reflects on whether to retire or
coach again, the better chance Smith has to win management's
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Unsigned free-agent center  &UR; Doug Weight and his agent,  &UR; Mike
Barnett, will ask the Edmonton Oilers to trade him in the next
couple of days if they don't agree to pay him $4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four million? No way I can fit that into my budget,'' Oilers
GM
 &UR; Glen Sather said. ``You've got to win a lot of things or get a lot
of points to get $4 million. Doug had 70 points last year. I don't
think he's a $4 million player.''
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Felix Potvin trade probably will come down this week.
Squeezed out by the free-agent signing of  &UR; Curtis Joseph this
summer, Potvin is headed to Vancouver, Ottawa, Montreal or the New
York Islanders. &QL; 
Life in the desert &QL; 
Several Coyotes got a scare the other day during practice at the
team's new training facility in Scottsdale when a tarantula crawled
into the building and was lurking around the Zamboni machine.
</P>
<P>
   After removing the hairy spider and returning it to the friendly
confines of the desert, a giant scorpion _ about the size of a fist
_ was spotted in about the same place. It didn't meet as kind a
fate as the tarantula, though. Someone squished it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this,'' equipment manager  &UR; Stan Wilson said.
``We've been out here for almost a year now, and I've never seen
anything crawl into this place. Now in two hours, I've seen a
tarantula and a scorpion. I can't wait to go home. I'm sure when I
open my car door today, I'll see a huge rattlesnake curled up
inside my front seat.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
