<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' WAIVER LIST YIELDS NO SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As expected, the Coyotes didn't produce any major
surprises when submitting their protected list to the NHL for
Monday's waiver draft.
</P>
<P>
   The nine players they chose not to protect, who now become
available to any team who wants them, more or less figured to be
left exposed.
</P>
<P>
   They include left wings Andrei Vasilev, Barry Nieckar and Joe
Dzdiezic, center Rob Murray, right wingers Jocelyn Lemieux and J.F.
Jomphe, and defensemen Brad Tiley, Bryan Helmer and Sean Gagnon.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the nine are expected to start the season in the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Gagnon, who has a chance to be one of the team's busiest
fighters if he cracks the lineup, was seen as a bit of a stretch
because of his uncanny toughness. But the fact he signed a one-way,
guaranteed $350,000 contract, a deal matched by the Coyotes after
Dallas made him an offer sheet, probably will scare away most clubs
from considering him.
</P>
<P>
   Each NHL team could protect 18 skaters and two goalies. Some of
the bigger names around the league left unprotected by their clubs
included: Warren Rychel (Colorado), Aaron Gavey and Dave Reid
(Dallas), Brent Gilchrist (Detroit), Ray Ferraro and Nathan
Lafayette (Los Angeles), Jeff Norton and Kirk Muller (Florida),
Bill Berg and Jeff Finley (Rangers), Ron Sutter (San Jose) and Glen
Healy (Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   Players who have since announced their retirement, such as the
Rangers' Pat LaFontaine and Carolina's Al Iafrate, also were among
those left unprotected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-03-98 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981003.0253 </DOCNO>
