<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8365 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     10-03 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' ATTITUDE SPURS CONCERN 
 MANY PLAYERS DOUBT TEAMMATES' DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels players, fresh off another September collapse,
were acting anything but heavenly after their season ended last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Angels drew 2.5 million fans to their refurbished
stadium. Yes, the Angels contended for a playoff spot until the
final weekend. But no, this club's players are anything but content
with what's going on in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get two studs here, one pitcher who is a force and one
bat that will give you 30 to 40 home runs and 120 to 130 RBIs,
we'll be ready to take off then,'' veteran left-hander  &UR; Chuck
Finley said. ``I guarantee you, we'd have a come-catch-me team
then.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the Angels is relatively young. Players such as
 &UR; Darin
 &UR; Erstad,  &UR; Troy Glaus,  &UR; Todd Greene,  &UR; Garrett Anderson,  &UR; Troy
Percival and
 &UR; Tim Salmon are under 30. The problem, some players insist, is the
willingness of some unnamed players to accept losing so easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot looser now,'' hitting coach  &UR; Rod Carew said
after the club whipped Oakland, 10-6, one day after being swept in
a three-game series at home against Texas. ``They're losers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the players voiced their fury against teammates,
starting with the always competitive Erstad, who has future leader
written all over himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are happy we're going home,'' he said. ``It's
almost like a pressure has been taken off, and players are happy
now. Why that is, I don't know. But it makes me mad. I don't get
it. Maybe they handle losing better than I do. Maybe I'm going to
have to change. I'll tell you what, I'll never be happy with
losing.'' &QL; 
No fish for you &QL; 
Cleveland's  &UR; Dave Burba, who parachuted in from the bullpen to save
the Indians' hide in Game 2 after starter  &UR; Dwight Gooden and
Manager  &UR; Mike &UR; Hargrove were ejected in the first inning, was
supposed to be fishing in Alaska this week.
</P>
<P>
   Burba, who was with Cincinnati until Cleveland traded for him
one day before the season began, had planned a weeklong trip during
February, knowing his chances of advancing to the playoffs with the
Reds were practically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the trade, Burba called his buddy who had organized
the expedition and told him, ``Count me out. I'm going to the
playoffs.'' &QL; 
What were you thinking? &QL; 
Houston outfielder  &UR; Carl Everett learned a valuable lesson after
sticking both his feet in his mouth last week, possibly firing up
San Diego, the Astros' first-round playoff opponent, and
infuriating his teammates in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to fire anybody up,'' Astros first baseman
 &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Bagwell said. ``It's like the old saying _ you want to let sleeping
giants lay.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett was quoted in Tuesday's ``Houston Chronicle'' with this
beauty:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give anybody credit until after they do something. So
right now, who is  &UR; Kevin Brown? Your past history doesn't do
nothing for you. He's nothing until he does something.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown went out and struck out 16 batters, the second-highest
total in postseason history ( &UR; Bob Gibson struck out 17 in 1968).
Brown said he was unaware of the comments, which is highly
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' San Diego pitching coach  &UR; Dave Stewart said, ``I guess
he's done something now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was dominant in beating Houston ace  &UR; Randy Johnson in the
2-1 victory, Johnson's first loss in the Astrodome since arriving
in a July 31 trade from Seattle. As for Everett, Brown struck him
out on three pitches his first time out. Everett also flied out and
struck out one more time against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he learned his lesson,'' Stewart said. ``A statement
like that is the sign of an ignorant man. Kevin Brown knows success
at a big level. What success has Carl Everett had?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing stuff like that, you don't even belong in the big
leagues. There's a saying that if you stand in the corner and keep
your mouth shut, nobody knows how stupid you are. I never knew he
was that stupid until he said that stuff.'' &QL; 
Truly a Big Mac attack &QL; 
Count the ``St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' as one of the biggest
beneficiaries of  &UR; Mark McGwire's record-breaking summer. St. Louis'
largest newspaper earned an extra $1 million from additional
advertising revenue and single-copy sales within three days of
McGwire's 62nd home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like he hit the ball, and we caught it,'' said
 &UR; Terrance
 &UR; Egger, ``Post-Dispatch'' vice president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis believes McGwire's home run binge added around $60
million in gross revenue to the local economy. &QL; 
Mariners in the playoffs &QL; 
That's some playoff club the Seattle Mariners have put together
this season. A quick scan of the eight postseason rosters showed
that more than 30 former Mariners are participating in the 1998
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle Times'' baseball writer  &UR; Larry Stone compiled this
starting lineup: Catcher,  &UR; Jason Varitek; 1B,  &UR; Tino Martinez; 2B,
 &UR; Joey Cora; SS,
 &UR; Omar Vizquel; 3B,  &UR; Luis Sojo; OF,  &UR; Roberto Kelly; OF,  &UR; Darren
Bragg; OF,
 &UR; Mark Whiten; DH,  &UR; Reggie Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the pitching staff that is even more impressive.  &UR; Randy
 &UR; Johnson,  &UR; Mike Hampton,  &UR; Dave Burba and  &UR; Sterling Hitchcock could
start, with  &UR; Terry Mulholland,  &UR; Jeff Nelson,  &UR; Ron Villone and
closer  &UR; Mike Jackson in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   You want a bench? How about  &UR; Glenallen Hill,  &UR; Andy Sheets,
 &UR; Warren Newson and  &UR; Bill Haselman? &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; So, exactly how did they lose 99 games?: The Tampa Bay Devil
Rays had the fourth-best ERA and second highest fielding percentage
in the American League. Of course, their club batting average
ranked 13th out of 14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A very subtle difference between these two
 &UR; franchises: Atlanta's post-season media guide dedicated 36 pages to
the club's post-season history. The Cubs? Three pages.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Bob Dernier.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Does it mean anything? Not really, but what the heck: In 1941
 &UR; Stan Musial hit .426 with one home run and seven RBIs in 47
at-bats after a September call-up to St. Louis.  &UR; J.D. Drew hit .417
with five home runs and 13 RBIs in 36 at-bats after his call-up
last month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No, really, you shouldn't have: Cincinnati General Manager  &UR; Jim
Bowden, who has been angling for the same post in Baltimore,
probably wasn't too happy to have former Orioles Manager
 &UR; Davey Johnson endorse him. Johnson's opinion is not exactly
welcomed by owner  &UR; Peter Angelos, who fired Johnson last fall. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With five 16-game winners on its staff, Atlanta joined the 1902
Pittsburgh Pirates as the only clubs this century who can boast
that claim. The Braves' big five of  &UR; Tom Glavine,  &UR; Greg Maddux,
 &UR; John Smoltz,
 &UR; Kevin Milwood and  &UR; Denny Neagle combined for 88 victories and 23
complete games. The '02 Pirates group won 100 games with 125
complete games.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, which lost 11 of its final 13 games, finished 35
games behind division champion New York. That's the Orioles'
largest deficit since the 1955 club finished 39 games behind the
AL-champion Yankees. It was also just two years after the Orioles
were known as the St. Louis Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's  &UR; Tom Kelly and Milwaukee's  &UR; Phil Garner joined
 &UR; Connie Mack (13 years and 10 years),  &UR; Gene Mauch (seven) and
 &UR; Bucky Harris (six) as the only managers to guide the same club to
at least six consecutive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit reliever  &UR; Todd Jones, who suffered through a mostly
miserable season, called the Tigers dugout during last Sunday's
final game and asked for an opportunity to pitch if the situation
arose. Jones needed to retire one batter to get his ERA below 5.00.
He did and finished at 4.97.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marquis Grissom, a post-season staple the past three years (two
with Atlanta and one with Cleveland), is not playing in October for
the first time since 1993. ``I won't lie to you. It'll be nice just
to have time to rest and heal up my body a little bit,'' said
Grissom, now with Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Young, arguably the best player on Pittsburgh's roster,
is the first Pirates player to finish with at least 40 doubles and
25 home runs since  &UR; Dave Parker 19 seasons ago. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Los Angeles closer  &UR; Jeff Shaw, it's almost a done
deal that he will opt to be traded or become a free agent. Shaw can
force the move since he was traded in the middle of a multiyear
deal. ``Being this far away from (my family), for so long, was too
difficult. And it's not something I want to go through again,'' the
Ohio native said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it's almost a lock the Dodgers will buy out the
final year of  &UR; Ramon Martinez's contract for $600,000 rather than
pick up the $5.6 million option on a player who may not pitch
before June.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland will probably have to start looking for a No. 1 starter
very soon.  &UR; Kenny Rogers, who won 16 games this season, has made
little secret of his desire to be closer to his family in Florida
and of playing for a contender. Rogers can insist on a trade or
become a free agent by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes-beleaguered Oakland Manager  &UR; Art Howe suddenly has
some bargaining power as the Athletics insist they want him to
return. The club wants to offer him a one-year deal with a one-year
option. Howe, a candidate to take over in Colorado, wants at least
two guaranteed years.
</P>
<P>
   Now that  &UR; Don Baylor has been fired, Colorado has compiled a
short list of candidates. In order of preference, they are:
 &UR; Jim Leyland,  &UR; Felipe Alou and  &UR; Howe. The Rockies were also
interested in
 &UR; Phil Garner, but Milwaukee did not allow Colorado permission to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be completely surprised if  &UR; Davey Johnson winds up
interviewing for the managerial openings in Detroit and Los
Angeles. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
