<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-BRAVES-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CUBS SEASON ENDS IN DISAPPOINTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ First, Greg Maddux silenced Chicago's bats for seven
innings. Then a grand slam in the eighth inning by Eduardo Perez
silenced the fans at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Saturday night's game ended, the loudest noise at
the ball park came from the visiting clubhouse as the Atlanta
Braves celebrated making the National League Championship Series
for the fourth consecutive year with a 6-2 victory over the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Using their great starting pitching, and getting timely power
hitting, the Braves completed a three-game sweep Saturday night
before 39,597, most of them Cubs fans who watched another season
end in disappointment. The Braves will open the NLCS
four-of-seven-game series Wednesday night at Turner Field against
the winner of the Houston-San Diego series. The Cubs, who have not
been to a World Series since 1945 and have not won one since 1908,
must wait at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta took a commanding 6-0 lead with a five-run eighth
inning, capped by Perez's grand slam to left field against Cubs
closer Rod Beck, who entered the game in the eighth inning. It was
Beck's first appearance of the series, and it was a disaster. Beck
had not pitched since Monday's one-game tie breaker against San
Francisco, but he was worked too hard during Chicago's drive to the
postseason, and the Cubs paid the price Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart started the eighth inning with a leadoff single
off Terry Mulholland, who then walked Chipper Jones. At that point,
Beck entered the game and retired the next batter, Andres
Galarraga, on a fly ball to center field. But Gerald Williams hit a
hard liner to left field that was misjudged by Henry Rodriguez, who
leaped but watched the ball sail over his head for a base hit.
Lockhart scored as shortstop Jose Hernandez made a bad relay throw
that allowed Jones to move to third base, and Williams to second.
</P>
<P>
   After Andruw Jones was walked intentionally to load the bases,
Perez unloaded them with a blast over the left-field wall. Lopez
was mobbed by his teammates when he reached the dugout as the
Braves knew they were only six outs from advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago rallied in the eighth inning with two runs, starting the
surge with three consecutive singles that loaded the bases and
chased Maddux from the game. But reliever Kerry Ligtenberg escaped
the jam with minimal damage. Mickey Morandini's sacrifice fly
scored Hernandez, but Ligtenberg got a huge strikeout against Sammy
Sosa. A run-scoring single by Mark Grace scored Sandy Martinez, but
Rodriguez flew out to left field to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got the victory, pitching seven innings with four
strikeouts and no walks, while yielding seven hits. Chicago starter
Kerry Wood took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs entered the series with high hopes, riding momentum and
making their first postseason appearance since 1989. But it turned
out to be almost a cameo. The Cubs had no answer for Atlanta's
pitching, scoring just four runs in the series, and looked like a
team that had expended too much energy just to make the postseason.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Atlanta took a 1-0 lead into the eighth inning, riding its third
consecutive strong pitching performance, this time from Maddux, the
four-time Cy Young Award winner. It was a typical Maddux
performance, featuring pinpoint control, clever changes of speed
and an ability to pitch out of trouble whenever he encountered it.
</P>
<P>
   A passed ball by Cubs catcher Tyler Houston allowed Maddux to
score from third base for a 1-0 Atlanta lead in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs figured that Maddux might beat them with his arm. But
in this game, Maddux also hurt Chicago with his bat. A .240 hitter
during the season, Maddux led off the third inning with a line
drive into the left center-field gap. Instead of settling for a
single, Maddux hustled into second base and slid just ahead of
Lance Johnson's throw for a double.
</P>
<P>
   After advancing to third base on a one-out groundout by Keith
Lockhart, Maddux scored when Houston mishandled an ankle-high Wood
pitch, allowing the ball to bounce off of his mitt and roll to the
backstop. Maddux scored easily, and although Chipper Jones followed
with a single that would have scored Maddux anyway, the Cubs
continued to make fielding mistakes, just as they had in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's frustration continued, both at the plate and on the
base paths. The Cubs squandered a scoring chance in the second
inning when Rodriguez led off with a double off the ivy in left
field. Gary Gaetti moved Rodriguez to third base on a groundout to
second. But after the Braves moved their infield in, Houston hit a
high chopper to first base, and Rodriguez did not break for home
plate, although it would have been a close play if he had run on
contact. Instead, Andres Galarraga flipped the ball to Maddux, who
was covering first, to retire Houston. Maddux then ended the inning
by striking out Hernandez looking.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago threatened again in the fifth inning, only to fall
short. Singles by Gaetti and Hernandez gave the Cubs runners on
first and second with one out. Knowing he could not waste a scoring
opportunity, Manager Jim Riggleman pinch-hit for Wood. Brant Brown
hit a slow ground ball to shortstop, and Hernandez slid hard into
second base, breaking up the double play and leaving runners at the
corners with two outs. But with the crowd on its feet, Maddux
retired Johnson on an easy fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pre-game talk centered around Wood, and whether the
Cubs should risk using their 21-year-old rookie who had not pitched
since Aug. 31 because of a sore elbow. But the Cubs could not have
asked for much more than what Wood gave them. He threw 97 pitches,
struck out five, walked four and surrendered only three hits during
his five innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
