<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-CREW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON ENDS FOR METROSTARS IN A SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The soccer season came to an end for the
MetroStars Saturday night when they experienced their first loss in
four shootout games this season, while the Columbus Crew posted its
first shootout victory in six attempts.
</P>
<P>
   With a 3-2 edge in the shootout after regulation had ended in a
1-1 deadlock, Columbus eliminated the MetroStars in two games in
their first-round Major League Soccer playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew will face the winner of the D.C. United-Miami series in
the Eastern Conference finals. United leads, 1-0, with Game 2 in
Miami on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Stillitano, vice president and general manager of the
MetroStars, said after the game that he would soon start
negotiations with Coach Bora Milutinovic with the goal of signing
him to a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here,'' Milutinovic said when asked about staying. ``My
experience here is very nice. I was happy to meet with the
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic coached four different countries to the second round
of the World Cup finals and agreed to coach the MetroStars on a
handshake with one game left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Under Milutinovic the MetroStars won the last game of the
regular season in a shootout but lost both encounters with Columbus
in the playoffs. Talking about Saturday night's game, Milutinovic
said: ``Everything is possible when you're in a shootout. I don't
like to say we weren't lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Tab Ramos and Mike Sorber were the only successful players in
the shootout for the MetroStars, while Billy Thompson, Thomas
Dooley and Stern John succeeded for the Crew. John made the score
in the shootout 3-1 when he drilled a shot just inside the right
post.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos and John were the goal scorers in regulation, where the
MetroStars had the territorial domination, especially in the first
half. But the home team had difficulty converting its
opportunities, to the disappointment of the 11,686 fans who braved
the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos displayed his experience on the goal that ended the
MetroStars' scoring drought on the artificial surface at 389
minutes. He stepped up to the ball to take a free kick that was
awarded to the MetroStars outside the penalty area on the left and
took it when he saw an opening and while the Columbus players were
setting up to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus scored on its first possession in the MetroStars'
penalty area, which came in the 22nd minute. John, who led the
league in scoring during the regular season, scored the goal on a
header after a free kick on the right by Andy Williams, who
assisted on two of the goals in the 5-3 victory in the first game
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus had only two other possessions near Tony Meola in the
first half. John had the best chance for another goal before
intermission, but he was denied by Meola in the last minute of the
half.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars had three new starters following the loss in
Ohio. Mike Petke started at right fullback, Billy Walsh in midfield
and Miles Joseph on the attack. Walsh and Joseph played in the
second half in Ohio, and the MetroStars showed considerable
improvement by scoring three goals in the second half of that game.
</P>
<P>
   With Petke playing at right fullback, Diego Sonora was freed to
move to the right side of the midfield, giving the MetroStars more
speed and experience on that side, especially since Ramos spent a
great deal of time on that side during the course of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Petke, a rookie with plenty of promise, was the last man in the
shootout for the MetroStars, and his attempt was parried to the
right side by Juergen Sommer, ending the third season for the
MetroStars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
