<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D-BACKS-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS MUST GET USED TO TICKET HIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Baseball fans in an uproar over the Diamondbacks'
ticket price increases should know a few things before they take
the kids out to the ballgame next season and buy them some peanuts
and Cracker Jack:
</P>
<P>
   Sports business experts say the 12.1 percent increase is
typical.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a ticket probably will keep rising like a Mark
McGwire home run.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised by another increase next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little like the stock market,'' said Sean Brenner,
editor of ``Team Marketing Report,'' &UR; a Chicago-based sports trade
publication that tracks costs for a family of four to attend
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't always predict the future based on past performance,
but typically professional sports franchises raise their ticket
prices by about 7 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball teams, according to our figures, went up
about 10 percent on average last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase hasn't set well with some fans because the
first-year expansion club compiled a record of 65-97, Maricopa
County collected $258 million in sales taxes that helped pay for
the ballpark, and fans spun the turnstiles 3.6 million times in
support of their new team. Attendance was third-highest in baseball
this season.
</P>
<P>
   After all, aren't these new baseball parks money-making
machines? Owners say they need parks that provide premium seating,
luxury suites, naming rights and extensive signage to compete, yet
the average fan still gets popped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fair question,'' said John Genzale, editor of
``Street and Smith's ''``''``SportsBusiness Journal,'' &UR; a national
publication that covers and investigates sports business issues.
</P>
<P>
   Genzale believes that while the 12 percent increase was near the
average, it is a little higher than the Diamondbacks needed because
of other revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three decades ago, the chief source of revenue, no
matter what the sport, was the gate,'' he said. ``Then clearly, TV
took over. Now we're in a time when the key thing is the stadium
because the TV revenue is shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ballpark is a money-making cow for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Team President Rich Dozer agrees that Bank One Ballpark is
generating tremendous revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a lot of money,'' he said. ``But we're spending
it to put the best product out there that we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that may be the only way the Diamondbacks satisfy
their paying public. Unless the club ponies up for a major free
agent, such as Astros pitcher Randy Johnson or Yankees outfielder
Bernie Williams, the grumbling is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't pleased when it reached the point of having to
consider a price increase, but after analyzing the entire
situation, we felt it was a necessity,'' said Jerry Colangelo,
managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   That situation, according to club sources, included about $9
million more in player payroll than expected. The team spent about
$32 million on player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Some expenses also came in high, including the cost for
air-conditioning the ballpark. Ticket revenue came in about $1
million below projections.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks ranked third in attendance and 13th in average
ticket price, and 17th based on the average cost of tickets sold.
Dozer said baseball hasn't released final numbers, but he predicted
the club will end up about 11th in total ticket revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Dozer said the club doesn't expect an exodus of season-ticket
holders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know more in about a month,'' he said. ``I don't think
that (a drop-off) will be the case. We might be mistaken there, but
we feel the experience (for fans at the ballpark) was good this
season, and we want to keep improving the product.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Diamondbacks had the most season-ticket holders in
baseball with 36,200. The club has a waiting list of 500 who have
paid deposits for season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get a charge out of raising ticket prices,'' Dozer
said. ``Looking at our situation, where we are next to the rest of
the teams in baseball, financially we needed to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the facts, we're in the middle of the crowd.
And when all is said and done, most teams are going to go up and
we'll still be in the middle third.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming most teams increase ticket costs by about 10 percent
again, Arizona likely will remain near the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Increase projected &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on figures published in July by the ``SportsBusiness
Journal,'' the Diamondbacks' ticket increase is in line with
projections that were given to potential investors in a Preliminary
Limited Offering Memorandum prepared by Merrill Lynch and Salomon
Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   That document, which was published in its entirety by
``SportsBusiness'' ``Journal,'' projected an increase of 12 percent
from 1998 to 1999 in the club's gate receipts. That is virtually
the same as the ticket price increase.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the projection for the year 2000 calls for another
increase of 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not gospel,'' Dozer said. ``Our ticket prices might
remain flat, they could go up 2 percent or 8.7 percent. We'll
re-adjust based on where we stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took seats that we thought maybe were priced a little low
and raised them. We priced them 2{ years ago because we needed to
start selling them. We didn't know then what the market would be
like. We tried to price them a little low.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest increases were in prime lower-level seats behind
home plate, which jumped from $25.50 to $35. A total of 69 seats in
the picnic overhang areas also proved to be more popular than
anticipated. Those jumped from $8 to $22.50. Seats in the
second-tier Diamond level rose by up to $4, those in the upper deck
rose by 50 cents to $2, and the $1 seats remained the same.
</P>
<P>
   Will fans see another increase next year? Genzale said the
Diamondbacks are likely to follow the projections set in their
limited offering, if possible. That would mean another increase
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you promise a bank or an investor to do that, you're sort
of committed to do that,'' Genzale said. ``They have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does it end? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, fans keep buying tickets even as they continue to
spiral upward in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies increased their ticket prices only slightly
after their first season in 1993. However, when the Rockies moved
into Coors Field for their third season, the prices jumped about 30
percent. After holding ticket prices firm for the 1996 season, the
Rockies bumped the average cost of a ticket by 24.3 percent to
$15.86 last season, the biggest bump in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the big increase, the Rockies still led the major
leagues in attendance, drawing more than 4 million fans to Coors
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets raised their average ticket price 23.3 percent
last season, and the St. Louis Cardinals raised theirs 18.5
percent, according to ``Team Marketing Report''.
</P>
<P>
   Every team trailed the Boston Red Sox, who charged an average of
$20.63 a ticket, highest in the majors. The Minnesota Twins had the
lowest average cost, $8.22.
</P>
<P>
   Four teams did not change their prices, and three _ the Cubs,
Giants and Phillies _ saw their average ticket prices go down
slightly in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' polled other National League West clubs
to determine whether their increases for 1999 are in line with the
Diamondbacks'. Most of the clubs have not announced their ticket
prices for next season, although several are expected to do so this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, Arizona's expansion partners,
will announce early this week whether they will increase ticket
prices for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you I think the Diamondbacks' increase was
modest,'' said Debra Duncan, director of ticket operations for the
Los Angeles Dodgers, who expects the team to bump the average price
of a ticket by $2-$3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to find new sources of revenue. I didn't
think there was anything too shocking in what Arizona did. We're
one of the sports that is still marketed to families. Our tickets
are still relatively inexpensive when you compare us to other major
professional sports. But our payrolls are just as significant. It's
a real challenge for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Norelli, vice president of ticket sales for the San
Francisco Giants, said prices will increase 6 percent to 8 percent
for his club. And he said Giants fans will see a significant jump
when the club moves out of 3Com Park and into its new facility in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of (the increase) is a transition to the new stadium,''
Norelli said. ``We don't want them to go into shock. We'll still
have affordable seats for the general public, but the best seats,
the infield seats, the first-level seats, will see a significant
increase.'' &QL; 
Can I afford to go back? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a ticket at Bank One Ballpark to see the
Diamondbacks in their inaugural season was $14.69. Prices ranged
from $50 for 1,098 seats in The Clubhouse section to $1 for 344
seats in the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, the average cost of a ticket jumps $1.79 to $16.48.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks report that 24,569 tickets still will be
available for $12.50 or less, and 17,893 for $10 or less. The club
also said 26,215 of the seats increased by $1 or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we usually see when a sports team raises its prices is
the higher-cost tickets increase more,'' said Brenner of ``Team
Marketing'' ``Report.'' ``They're paying more anyway, so they're
not going to feel the increase quite as much. Teams tend to try to
keep the low-priced tickets about the same so the game is still
accessible to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozer said that while talk radio shows may be buzzing about the
increase, Diamondbacks phone lines are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people call and say they wish we weren't raising the
ticket prices, but most of them have said they're going to renew,''
he said. ``We haven't had an outpouring at all. It's not like we've
gotten hundreds of calls. And I don't listen to talk radio.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
