<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SAD CHAPTER IN RED SOX SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the Red Sox. Good turns into bad. Victory dissolves
into defeat. Joy gives way to sadness. We go to the theater and
enjoy the performances, but the script never changes. In the end,
the Titanic sinks, Hamlet dies, and the Red Sox lose the last game
that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Time to bring the storm windows up from the cellar and peel the
tarp off the cordwood, sports fans. Boston's baseball summer is
over. Mo Vaughn's Red Sox career might be over. The Olde Towne Team
is not going to win the World Series. Again.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox lost Game 4 of their American League Division Series
against the Indians, 2-1, at Fenway Park Saturday. It was an
excruciating defeat that gave the Tribe a 3-1 win in the
best-of-five series and sent the Sox home for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   After the final out, wonderboy shortstop Nomar Garciaparra (11
RBIs in the four games) stood in front of the Sox dugout and
implored the fans to cheer. They cheered for a while, then chanted,
``We want Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrill was gone. Maybe so is Mo. And it isn't easy being a
Sox fan. Since Bill Buckner's fateful error, your team has lost 16
of 17 postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good things happened,'' said a reflective manager
Jimy Williams. ``But we lost our last game. In October. A lot of
kids left it out on that field. That's all we can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his lieutenant, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, were
vindicated when their controversial selection as starting pitcher,
Pete Schourek, excelled (5 1/3 innings, two hits, no runs). But the
brain trust still had some explaining to do when they then departed
from form and summoned closer Tom Gordon earlier than at any point
in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who saved 46 games this year, including a major
league-record 43 straight leading into the playoffs, was never
called at the start of the eighth inning this season. But Saturday,
after Derek Lowe retired five straight batters in the sixth and
seventh, Kerrigan and Williams panicked and called for Gordon to
pitch the eighth and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It backfired. Gordon got the first batter he faced, then gave up
three straight hits, including a two-run double by David Justice.
That was the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right man, right spot,'' said the ever-obtuse Williams. ``He
was a fresh arm. Lowe had done his job. (Gordon) has been a starter
before. Maybe we hadn't started him in the eighth, but he'd
certainly gotten five outs before. It wasn't a situation that was
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan added, ``Lowe had thrown 58 pitches in three days and
19 pitches today. He did his job. Before the game, we said if we
can get to Flash for six outs, we would do it. Because he had two
days off.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it looked like the Sox were panicking when Gordon came in
so early. And the removal of Lowe is mildly reminiscent of Darrell
Johnson's lifting of Jim Willoughby for a pinch hitter (resulting
in rookie Jim Burton giving up the winning run) in the final game
of the 1975 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans could only moan about the anemic batting order.
Boston's best chance to score a second run came in the sixth, when
third base coach Wendell Kim, again running against season-long
form, sent John Valentin to home-plate death after Mike Stanley
singled to left with Valentin on second in the sixth. Valentin was
easily gunned down by Justice.
</P>
<P>
   It was totally uncharacteristic for the conservative Kim and
perhaps made a statement about the Sox' lack of confidence in their
lineup. But again, the Sox brass refused to second-guess itself.
It's a baseball thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was the right call,'' said Williams. ``Any time you
get a chance to score on a play like that, you go. You've got to
tip your cap. Justice made a perfect throw. To me, if we would do
it over again, we'd do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said, ``Were you watching the game? Justice was playing
toward center field. Val got a good jump and Justice had to make a
perfect throw, which he did. It was early in the game (sixth?). I
don't see you guys (reporters) hardly ever. Justice hasn't played
much left field and he'd been hurt. I felt we had a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox threatened in the bottom of the eighth when Vaughn _ in
what might have been his final at-bat as a Red Sox player, hit a
one-out double off the wall (``The damn wind was blowing the wrong
way'' _ Mo). Donnie Sadler ran for Vaughn, and after Nomar grounded
to third and Stanley walked, Troy O'Leary (1 for 16 in the series)
popped weakly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to the ninth, on toward another Red Sox winter.
</P>
<P>
   The hot stoves will glow again in November, December, and
January. We'll watch to see if Mo stays or goes and what the Sox do
to improve their anemic lineup. It'll be 1999 and there'll be some
new logs on that fire. Fans will discuss the decision to lift Lowe
for Flash, Wendell's folly, and all the other things that happened
in the four score and one year since the Red Sox last won a World
Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
