<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DIDN'T HAVE ENOUGH TO GO FURTHER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   That is what the Indians performed on the Red Sox Saturday.
David Justice administered the last rites with a laser-beam two-run
double in the eighth inning and Mike Jackson officially pulled the
plug at 7:30 EDT when he fogged a fastball by Darren Bragg to end
the game, series, and season for a Red Sox team that simply did not
deserve to go any further.
</P>
<P>
   This was never going to be The Year. In order to win the 1998
World Series, the Red Sox would have needed to figure out a way to
win three series in succession, the last two against teams that had
won in excess of 100 games and had far more top-to-bottom weaponry.
The Red Sox were an Ohio Valley Conference team trying to win the
NCAAs. Murray State is not going to win the NCAA tournament any
time soon, and the Red Sox, as constituted, aren't going to win the
World Series, either. Until further notice, their reward for a nice
season is going to be an invitation to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is for you and me to say. You won't hear them
say it. There is no room for the athlete to be objective. The
athlete has to believe in miracles. He figures if he's good enough
to be in the tournament, he's good enough to win it. The athlete
doesn't think about the fact that the Yankees, who won 114 games,
have no weaknesses, or that even if the Sox could have somehow
gotten by New York, an Atlanta, Houston, or San Diego _ all far
superior teams _ would be waiting. They don't think that way. They
think only positive thoughts. That's who they are.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the shortstop. ``I went out there with the
same mind-set I had for 162 games,'' said Nomar Garciaparra.
``These playoffs weren't any different. I come out here to win.
That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn isn't quite as monomaniacal as Nomar _ no one is _ but
he honestly thought the team could have beaten the Yankees. ``I
think this team, if it played relaxed and played to its
capabilities, had the opportunity to beat anybody in the American
League,'' he declared. ``Who knows what would have happened against
the National League? The World Series is just blood and guts. I
really felt this team had the opportunity to get there _ no doubt
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar, Mo, and anyone else on the team harboring similar
thoughts, I respect your ability and I appreciate your position.
You have to prepare yourself to play and you can't do that if
you're already rolling a Greg Maddux-David Cone Game 1 matchup
around in your mind. I have no such shackles. I can go by what I
saw, and what I saw was a likable, hustling team with a lot of
heart that was able to camouflage some tremendous weaknesses during
the regular season. But when the serious games started, you were
exposed.
</P>
<P>
   All season long, people watching this team kept asking
themselves, ``How are they doing it with that lineup?'' Once anyone
got beyond Mo and Nomar, what did they have? I said it in May and
I'll say it once again: Troy O'Leary batting fifth for any length
of time was a frightening admission of offensive weakness. Start
with that. Then move through the rest of the order. Who was there
with the capability of scaring anybody?
</P>
<P>
   Every worst fear about the impotence of the lineup was justified
in this series. O'Leary, Scott Hatteberg, Jason Varitek, Mike
Benjamin, and Darren Bragg combined for five singles in 53 at-bats.
That's an .094 average, and that will not get it done. The entire
Red Sox offense consisted of John Valentin, Nomar, Mo, and, to some
extent, leadoff man Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything,'' confirmed Mike Stanley, whose bat had
at least a little life, ``but it would have been nice if someone
else would have been able to make a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were a better team this year because they could
catch the ball, and that's fine. Pitching and defense are still the
most important components of a winning team. But there are people
out there who can both hit the ball and catch the ball, and it
might be nice if the Red Sox could find some of them and put them
in one of their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   And the best that could be said about the overall catching
situation is that it could have been worse. I think. As much as you
want to like Scott Hatteberg, he really does give up far too many
non-Wakefield passed balls. His bat is pesky, but he's not scary.
Some people think Jason Varitek might be the long-range answer, but
I think that depends on the question. Dan Duquette has to do
something about this position if the Red Sox are ever going to
advance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a given that they need another good starting pitcher, but
aside from the Braves and Yankees, who doesn't? Perhaps the Duke
will have a successful shopping expedition this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Look, it was a fun year. April was magical. The team usually
went down hard, very often scoring a run or two in the late innings
when it was behind. There was usually a reason to stick around for
that final at-bat. We luxuriated in the wild-card race because,
well, what choice did we have? But it was the JV game to New York's
varsity, and any reasonable person knew it.
</P>
<P>
   The players invest their hearts and souls into the enterprise,
so they can be forgiven for being unrealistic. Not us. When there
are four teams as good as New York, Atlanta, Houston, and San Diego
out there, sooner or later, we here in Boston must sober up and
realize that the Red Sox are nothing but a lounge act. The only way
this was going to be The Year was if there were about five plane
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians? Who cares about the Indians? They're about to be
bludgeoned by the Yankees. If the Red Sox are Murray State,
somebody had better tell the Indians they are Austin Peay.
</P>
</TEXT>
